INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('bd98d387-cb53-4356-8e61-05ae16a286f5','2025-10-27 14:36:50','26082f23-1ac1-409c-a24b-07f84d6ee419',6,'Isaac, you started the conversation well by identifying the high profitability of the catering business as a key reason to continue it. However, your performance declined when pressed for a more detailed analysis. You struggled to recall specific information from the case, and your proposed solutions were generic and lacked justification from the provided material. To improve, focus on a more thorough reading of the case materials to support your recommendations with specific details and data throughout the entire conversation.','[{"score":2,"feedback":"You correctly identified that catering has high profit margins, which is a key point from the case. However, you seemed unfamiliar with other crucial details, such as the explicit stages of the catering process, which you were unable to recall even with a hint. A more thorough review of the material would allow you to bring more specific facts into the conversation to strengthen your analysis.","question":"Q1. Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":2,"feedback":"Your initial answer regarding profitability was a strong start. As the conversation deepened, however, your answers became more generic and evasive, such as deflecting a question back to the CEO and suggesting a vague \'pilot program\' without detailing what it would entail. Try to build on your strong points by thinking through the operational details and potential challenges mentioned in the case.","question":"Q2. Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":2,"feedback":"You did a good job using the case to justify your first point about profitability. That was an excellent start! However, you did not apply that same level of justification to subsequent questions about standardizing the process, instead offering general ideas without connecting them back to the specific challenges and details outlined in the reading, such as Dan Evans\'s unique expertise and time commitment.","question":"Q3. Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','liberal',1,3,'the hard questions that were asked','more help when i asked questions','gemini-2.5-flash','gemini-2.5-pro','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: what are the core restaurant operations currently?\n\nCEO: Good question, STUDENT. Our core restaurant operation, as you\'ve read, is a "fast casual" pizza restaurant. We focus on quick service, a healthy menu, and our social cause of donating a meal to Malawi for every meal purchased. We\'ve built a strong brand around this model.\n\nNow, let\'s bring it back to the main question. **How does our catering business fit into or diverge from these core operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: what do you think?\n\nCEO: STUDENT, I\'m here to hear *your* analysis. You\'ve read the case. I\'m looking for your informed perspective on whether catering aligns with our core restaurant operations or pulls us away from them.\n\n**What specific facts from the case lead you to believe catering is either a good fit or a distraction?**\n\nSTUDENT: I think that we should continue to cater because of the high profit margins\n\nCEO: That\'s a solid point, STUDENT. The case does mention that catering is the "most profitable part of the restaurant operation." I appreciate you grounding your recommendation in a specific fact.\n\nHowever, profitability isn\'t the only factor we need to consider. The case also highlights that our catering operation, as it currently stands, is "an ex