fitability** of our catering business compared to the main restaurant? That foundational fact is key to understanding whether we should even be trying to do "more events." What does the document tell us about that?\n\nSTUDENT: they mentioned that catering was more profitable because the clients were paying a "premium" right?\n\nCEO: You\'re absolutely on the right track, STUDENT, excellent deduction! The idea of clients paying a "premium" certainly points to higher profitability. That\'s a keen observation about customer behavior and pricing.\n\nNow, let\'s get even more specific with the case facts. The document uses a very direct phrase to describe catering\'s profitability relative to the restaurant. Can you find the exact wording the case uses to describe *how* profitable catering is? It\'s a key phrase that really emphasizes its financial importance to Malawi\'s Pizza.\n\nSTUDENT: can i get a hint?\n\nCEO: Certainly, STUDENT. Everyone gets one free hint, so here\'s a pointer:\n\nLook towards the beginning of the case, specifically in the section that discusses the company overview and the role of catering within Malawi\'s overall business strategy. There\'s a very direct statement there about catering\'s financial standing relative to the main restaurant.\n\nRemember, after this, each hint will cost you a point. Now, can you find that specific phrase?\n\nSTUDENT: catering was seen as the much more profitable, low overhead and higher profit margin\n\nCEO: Excellent, STUDENT! You\'ve hit on some crucial points. The case indeed states that "Catering was seen as a much more profitable model than traditional restaurant service because of the low overhead (i.e., no need to maintain an entire restaurant facility) and higher profit margin." That\'s a solid, fact-based justification from the document!\n\nAnd you\'re right, it even goes a step further, stating that catering was the "most profitable part of the restaurant operation." That\'s the key phrase!\n\nSo, with that confirmed, it\'s clear catering is a financially attractive part of our business. Now, let\'s pivot to your earlier excellent point about scaling. You mentioned minimizing the amount of time it takes to plan a catering event. The case highlights that our current catering process heavily relies on Dan Evans\'s "intuition, experience, and knowledge," and that planning can take him "3 to 10 hours."\n\nGiven our goal to franchise, how do you propose we address this operational bottleneck and standardize the planning process so we can do more events per year without burning out Dan, or requiring every franchisee to have a "Dan Evans"? Your insights here would be invaluable.\n\nSTUDENT: I would make a standardized catering plan across all customers to maximize planning time\n\nCEO: That\'s a very direct and practical solution, STUDENT! Standardizing the catering plan is an excellent idea for streamlining the process and reducing the heavy reliance on Dan Evans\'s personal time and expertise. It directly addresses the scalability issue we\'re facing.\n\nNow, let\'s dig into the implications of that. The case mentions that we have two types of clients: "professional event planners" and "non-professionalseveryday people with little to no experience planning events." Dan currently spends significantly more time with the non-professional clients, often feeling like he\'s "planning the whole event instead of only catering it."\n\nIf we move to a standardized catering plan, how do you see that impacting these two distinct customer segments? And how can we ensure we still meet their needs, particularly the non-professional clients who currently require more guidance, while still achieving that standardization?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 4\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: I liked how you led me to the answer but didn\'t give it directly\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: I felt like I answered your answer in the beginning but you didn\'t want me to move on becasue I didn\'t give you an exact answer\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: ok\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: ok\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: ok\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: ok\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future student