s of attendees."\n\nHowever, you mentioned that focusing on "customers and their needs will also be our greatest asset as we plan to franchise." The case also highlights a significant challenge in our current catering operation that directly contradicts this idea of easy replication for franchising.\n\n**What is the biggest operational hurdle, as described in the case, that makes our current catering model *unsuitable* for franchising, despite its profitability?**\n\nSTUDENT: I do understand that we heavily rely on the general manager and we don\'t have any standardized menu items or procedures. It also takes a lot of prep time for the general manager to do so. One suggestion that I would have moving forward is to train other employees in the catering business. You don\'t have to hire new managers but the ability to train managers on a standardized catering plan and allow them to interact with customers would greatly take some of the workload for the general manager. Especially when franchising, you cannot have the same manager at every event across franchises.\n\nCEO: You\'re absolutely right, STUDENT. The case clearly states that the catering process "depended on the intuition, experience, and knowledge that Evans had gained throughout his career." And his planning meetings can take "anywhere between 3 and 10 hours." That\'s a significant bottleneck and a major problem for franchising.\n\nYour suggestion to "train other employees" is a logical next step to address the reliance on Evans. But let\'s dig a bit deeper.\n\n**Beyond just training employees, what specific *process changes* could we implement to standardize the catering operation and reduce the need for Evans\'s extensive personal involvement, making it more scalable and replicable for future franchises?** Think about the different types of clients and their needs.\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: sure\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: the responses that I received is what I would imagine an executive would ask m\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: If I had read the case in advance\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: Yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
