career." How do you propose we address this reliance on Dan if we want to expand, especially with our ultimate goal of franchising?\n\nSTUDENT: It says that Dan has played an essential role in developing this catering operation. If we would like to move away from this over-reliance on Dan, I would suggest a training system run by dan to employees who are looking to take on the role of the head caterer in our franchised businesses\n\nCEO: That\'s a thoughtful approach, STUDENT. Training employees to take over Dan\'s role is certainly a possibility mentioned in the case.\n\nHowever, the case also notes that Dan\'s involvement in planning can take "anywhere between 3 and 10 hours depending on the client\'s needs." Even with trained employees, how do we ensure this process becomes scalable and replicable for a franchise model when it\'s currently so time-intensive and reliant on individual client interaction?\n\nSTUDENT: I think that we need to create a standardized process that can be adjusted based on customer needs but offer a pretty basic outlay at first\n\nCEO: A standardized process is a good idea. What specific elements of the current catering process do you think could be standardized to address the scalability issue and reduce the time burden on individuals like Dan?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: sure\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 4\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: I liked that the questions actually made me think about the case and possible solutions\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: I think it was fin\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: Sure\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('9b08fe32-afd1-4447-9575-0aecdd7b3299','2025-10-27 16:03:05','d8bdcbce-a8a5-4d1c-a34f-dc3a552821e9',15,'Jacob demonstrated a strong grasp of the case material and provided insightful, actionable recommendations. He effectively addressed the core challenges of scalability and replicability for Malawi\'s catering business, particularly in the context of franchising. His suggestions, such as creating standardized catering packages, encouraging pre-meeting client research, implementing customer feedback mechanisms, and developing comprehensive training for franchisees, were well-reasoned and directly responsive to the dilemmas presented. Jacob showed a commendable ability to think strategically about process improvement and customer experience.','[{"score":5,"feedback":"Jacob demonstrated a very thorough understanding of the reading material, consistently referencing specific details from the case to support his arguments and identify key challenges and opportunities in Malawi\'s catering operation.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":5,"feedback":"Jacob provided excellent, well-articulated, and actionable answers. His suggestions for streamlining the planning process with packages, leveraging Dan\'s expertise for specialized needs, and implementing training for franchisees were very solid and complete.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":5,"feedback":"Jacob consistently justified his answers by drawing directly on relevant information from the business case. He effectively linked his proposed solutions to specific problems and details outlined in the text, such as Dan Evans\' time commitment and the need for franchising replicability.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','leading',0,5,'i liked how quickly the responses were and how my answers led to informed questions from you based on the case','maybe you could implement audio so that I don\'t have to type out my full answer','gemini-2.5-flash-lite','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: I think we should stay in the catering business\n\nCEO: That\'s a strong stance, STUDENT! I appreciate your confidence. You\'re right, the catering business does present some significant opportunities. What specifically in the case leads you to believe we should continue with catering?\n\nSTUDENT: It doesn\'t require much effort outside of what we normally do at the restaurant\n\nCEO: That\'s an interesting observation, STUDENT. You\'re right that catering can leverage existing resources like our kitchen and staff. The case does mention that "For the most part, catering didn\'t require a lot of extra effort outside of the restaurant\'s normal operations."\n\nHowever, the case also highlights that Dan Evans spends a significant amount of time with clients during the planning phase, sometimes between 3 to 10 hours per client. How do you reconcile that substantial time investment with your point about "not much extra effort"?\n\nSTUDENT: I think you should create packages of options to narrow down this time. Also you can invest more time and resources into having the customer do their research before a meeting. Different options can be given prior so that the meeting is more efficient\n\nCEO: That\'s a very insightful approach, STUDENT! Creating standardized packages is a fantastic idea to streamline the planning process. And encouraging customers to do their research beforehand would certainly make those meetings more efficient. You\'re touching on a key area for improving scalability.\n\nNow, thinking about how these packages would be structured, what specific types of events or customer needs do you envision these packages addressing, based on the information in the case?\n\nSTUDENT: Kind of pizza, expected number of guests, payment, and especially cleanup details\n\nCEO: Excellent points, STUDENT! You\'ve hit on some critical elements. Offering packages that clearly define pizza types, guest counts, payment terms, and especially cleanup details would indeed address some of the ambiguities we\'ve encountered. This sounds like it could really help manage client expectations and reduce the time spent on those less structured parts of the planning.\n\nGiven that catering is described as our "most profitable part of the restaurant operation," how would these packages help us maintain or even increase that profitability while also making the process more manageable for franchising?\n\nSTUDENT: also gratuity\n\nCEO: Yes, absolutely, STUDENT! Including gratuity in the packages is a great detail to add for clarity and to ensure we\'re capturing that revenue consistently. It shows a thorough understanding of our pricing structure.\n\nNow, let\'s think about the operational side of these packages. The case mentions that catering is our "most profitable part of the restaurant operation" but relies heavily on Dan Evans\' expertise. How do you see these packages helping us scale the catering operation and make it more replicable for franchising, especially considering Dan\'s current central role?\n\nSTUDENT: These packages will help us cut down time on planning and maximize efficiency of operations. We won\'t have to pay for the time spent planning. The consumer satisfaction will also go up because their time will be maximized. We can invest that time and money into the creation and explanation of the packages\n\nCEO: That\'s a very positive outlook, STUDENT, and I like your focus on efficiency and customer satisfaction. By creating clear packages, we can certainly streamline the planning process and potentially reduce the time Dan spends on each client. Investing that saved time and money into developing and explaining these packages is a smart move.\n\nHowever, the case also highlights that Dan Evans\' role involves a significant amount of "intuition, experience, and knowledge." How would these standardized packages address situations where clients have unique or complex needs that might fall outside of a pre-defined package? And how do we ensure the *quality* of the experience remains high, as the case emphasizes that attendees are our primary source of new business through word-of-mouth?\n\nSTUDENT: If clients have needs that fall outside of our packages, they can have a longer meeting to draw upon Dan\'s expertise. After all, if their needs are specialized, they will need the time to express them. Also our team has seen a lot and can probably cover most situations. I think that we should start surveying our clients after every event and ask them how likely they are to recommend Malawi to a friend. We can also start to give discounts if they were referred by someone who paid for our catering services in the past\n\nCEO: That\'s a very thoughtful approach, STUDENT. Allowing for extended meetings for specialized needs acknowledges that not every situation fits neatly into a box, and leveraging Dan\'s expertise in those cases is wise. It\'s also smart to think about how to gather feedback and incentivize referrals. The Net Promoter Score (NPS) idea is excellent for measuring customer satisfaction, and a referral discount is a classic, effective strategy.\n\nNow, let\'s consider the franchising aspect. If we\'re aiming to franchise Malawi\'s Pizza, how can we ensure that this catering model, even with packages and client feedback, is easily replicable by franchisees who may not have Dan Evans\' extensive experience or intuition? What specific steps would you recommend to transfer that knowledge and ensure consistency across different franchise locations?\n\nSTUDENT: Training videos and curriculum will always be able to supplement the transfer of knowledge\n\nCEO: Training videos and a comprehensive curriculum are excellent ideas, STUDENT! That\'s exactly the kind of structured approach we need to ensure consistency and replicability for franchising. Having a robust training program will be crucial for passing on the necessary skills and knowledge.\n\nThinking about the practicalities, what specific elements of the current catering process, beyond just the menu packages, would need to be documented and included in these training materials to ensure a franchisee can successfully execute a catering event from start to finish?\n\nSTUDENT: Equipment set up. Proper safety protocols for handling the semi-raw pizzas, how to run the event, cut a pizza, etc\n\nCEO: Excellent, STUDENT! You\'ve identified some critical operational components. Equipment setup, safety protocols for handling the par-cooked pizzas, and the actual execution of the event, including pizza cutting, are all vital pieces of information that need to be standardized. This shows you\'re thinking about the end-to-end process.\n\nNow, let\'s pivot slightly. The case mentions that catering is "highly seasonal with chunky demand patterns," and that we only cater about ten events per year, mostly in the summer. How would your proposed package system and training program help us address this seasonality and potentially increase the utilization of our catering assets, like the mobile oven, throughout the year?\n\nSTUDENT: If people can do the whole process correctly, it will lead to increased demand through word of mouth\n\nCEO: That\'s a great point, STUDENT. Increased customer satisfaction through well-executed events, facilitated by your proposed training and packages, should naturally lead to more word-of-mouth referrals and thus, increased demand. That\'s a very positive feedback loop you\'re envisioning.\n\nHowever, the case also points out that catering is "highly seasonal with chunky demand patterns" and that the mobile oven has low utilization outside of peak times. While increased word-of-mouth is valuable, what *specific* strategies could we implement, perhaps even within the package structure or through targeted marketing, to smooth out that demand and better utilize our catering resources during the off-peak seasons?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yeah sure\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: i liked how quickly the responses were and how my answers led to informed questions from you based on the case\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: maybe you could implement audio so that I don\'t have to type out my full answer\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: Yeah sure\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALU