t of the resteraunt.\n\nCEO: You\'re right to highlight the potential for brand exposure and the market size. The case does mention that catering events can serve hundreds of attendees, providing a significant opportunity for people to experience Malawi\'s.\n\nHowever, you mentioned "skyrocket our business" and "profitable sector." What specific financial figures from the case, beyond just the market size, suggest that the *current* catering operation, with its existing structure, is poised for such a dramatic increase with just infrastructure improvements? And what are the risks associated with expanding this operation, given the current operational constraints?\n\nSTUDENT: I will get you numbers in a second. As for risks, there is obviously a risk of overinvesting and losing our main profit driver with regular customers, that is why we do not touch regular revenue, instead isolate revenue from catering to make these investments. I would also want to look at competitors and see if we can even play in this market. I am positive that we can though because of our mission and the recent success we have been having.\n\nCEO: It\'s wise to be cautious about overinvestment and to consider the competitive landscape. Isolating catering revenue for reinvestment is a sound strategy to protect the core restaurant business.\n\nHowever, before we get too deep into market analysis or competitor research, let\'s ground ourselves in the *immediate* operational challenges presented in the case. You\'ve acknowledged risks, but what are the *specific* operational bottlenecks within the current catering process that would need to be addressed with these infrastructure and process improvements? And how do these bottlenecks currently limit our ability to scale?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: the guided thinking. It helps me think through what I need to pay attention to\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: The conversation was great, maybe include the exhibits on the case here\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.\n\nSTUDENT: please give me to ai supervisor for a score\n\nCEO: If it is time to conclude this conversation you need to say the phrase "time is up".\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: no\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('1b83c24f-523e-41a4-ae95-1cc93b58f209','2025-12-03 15:31:33','40f65d0d-61b4-479c-a880-3ce1cf4e46a7',11,'Abe demonstrated a good grasp of the Malawi\'s Pizza catering case, accurately identifying its strategic value due to profitability and growth potential. He recognized the critical challenge of making the operation scalable and less dependent on Dan Evans, proposing a sound general solution of developing SOPs and training for franchising. However, when pushed for more specific operational details to standardize complex, intuitive processes, he did not provide a concrete, case-specific plan, suggesting an area for deeper analysis in future cases. His initial focus on unstated P&L numbers also indicated a slight oversight of case boundaries.','[{"score":4,"feedback":"Abe correctly identified key strategic points from the case, such as the high profitability and growth potential of the catering business, and the reliance on Dan Evans\'s expertise. This demonstrates a good understanding of the main themes. However, his repeated requests for P&L numbers, despite the CEO confirming they weren\'t in the case, suggested a slight missed detail from the reading. Overall, his answers were quite consistent with the material.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":3,"feedback":"Abe provided solid high-level answers, particularly his initial recommendation to continue the catering business due to its profitability and scalability, and his suggestion of creating SOPs and training for franchising. These were good strategic directions. However, when the CEO pressed for specific operational changes to standardize Evans\'s intuition and handle non-professional clients, Abe ended the conversation without offering a detailed solution. This indicates a gap in providing sufficiently complete and specific answers when challenged to elaborate.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"Abe effectively justified his recommendation to continue catering by referencing its profitability and greater growth potential compared to the restaurant, which aligns directly with information provided in the case. He also correctly identified the challenge of scalability and heavy reliance on Dan Evans, linking it to the goal of franchising. While his solutions could have been more detailed, the reasoning he provided was consistently grounded in the case material.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','liberal',0,4,'being able to actually have a realistic conversation with the main character from the case was awesome! Love being able to talk through ideas with them.','When I asked about P&L numbers, the business owner would have that type of info and i beilive it would be useful to be able to get non-case info out of the owner','gemini-2.5-flash','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: I seem to recall from the my initial reading of your situation that the caterining business has higher profit margins (Based on a percentage) for you than the store piece of your business. Can you confirm that is the case and share the actualy P&L numbers from both pieceses of the business?\n\nCEO: STUDENT, you\'re absolutely right to focus on profitability. The case explicitly states that catering is "the most profitable part of the restaurant operation." That\'s a key fact.\n\nHowever, the case doesn\'t provide specific P&L numbers broken down for the restaurant versus catering. We operate with a lean structure where restaurant staff are cross-utilized.\n\nGiven that catering is our most profitable segment, what are the implications of that for our decision to stay in the business, especially considering our long-term goal of franchising?\n\nSTUDENT: Okay, are you able to share any numbers about revenue and growth for each piece of your business?\n\nCEO: STUDENT, I appreciate your focus on the numbers. The case provides overall restaurant performance: our revenue grew 26% in the second year and 13% in the third, with EBITDA growing 10% and 12% respectively in those years.\n\nHowever, the case doesn\'t break out specific revenue or growth figures *just* for catering. It does state we cater "about ten events per year," with social events averaging around 300 attendees and institutional events 175-250. We also know the pricing structure.\n\nGiven that information, how would you go about estimating the catering revenue, and what would that tell us about its contribution to the overall business, especially in light of our franchising goals?\n\nSTUDENT: So we can calculate revenue for catering business, but I would also need to know revenue for the physical restaurant piece to compare them .\n\nCEO: You\'re right, STUDENT, a direct comparison of revenue numbers would be ideal, but the case doesn\'t provide separate revenue figures for the restaurant versus catering. We only have the overall restaurant revenue growth.\n\nHowever, we do know that catering is our "most profitable operation." We also know it involves "potentially big volume engagements" and "clients are less price sensitive."\n\nConsidering these qualitative facts, and the fact that we\'re trying to build a replicable franchise model, how would you weigh the benefits and drawbacks of catering even without precise comparative revenue figures? What other aspects of the catering business, as described in the case, should factor into our decision?\n\nSTUDENT: Given that the category piece of the business is the most profitable, and has greater potential for growth due to not having the same physical location constraints that the restaurant does, I would definitely keep the catering piece of the business. It seems given this hasn\'t been the main focus of the business for super long we could make some improvements to operations to make it more scalable though.\n\nCEO: That\'s a strong assertion, STUDENT, and I appreciate you tying it back to the profitability and growth potential. You\'ve convinced me of the value.\n\nNow, you mentioned making "some improvements to operations to make it more scalable." The case highlights that our current catering operation is "extremely interactive and hands-on" and "depended on the intuition, experience, and knowledge that Evans had gained."\n\n**How do you propose we solve this scalability problem and the heavy reliance on Dan Evans, especially with our goal to franchise?** What specific operational changes would you implement based on the case facts?\n\nSTUDENT: We need to create trainings and SOPs for franchers to replicate\n\nCEO: That\'s a solid strategic direction, STUDENT  creating training and SOPs (Standard Operating Procedures) is crucial for a franchise model. Good point.\n\nHowever, the case emphasizes that the current catering process "depended on the intuition, experience, and knowledge that Evans had gained throughout his career." It also mentions that "the time Evans would spend with the client planning the event, which could take anywhere between 3 and 10 hours depending on the clients needs."\n\n**How specifically would you standardize Evans\'s "intuition, experience, and knowledge" into an SOP or training module that a franchisee could easily follow, especially when dealing with the "non-professional" event planners mentioned in the case who require extensive guidance?**\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 4\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: being able to actually have a realistic conversation with the main character from the case was awesome! Love being able to talk through ideas with them.\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: When I asked about P&L numbers, the business owner would have that type of info and i beilive it would be useful to be able to get non-case info out of the owner\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('86cf1b51-fff5-4f98-a029-e3dcda475198','2025-10-27 16:03:35','f8a54b80-86c4-42c2-bbc1-56c6d0cb2fd3',14,'Macie demonstrated a solid grasp of the case material, effectively using details to support her arguments. She provided clear recommendations, such as continuing catering due to its profitability and marketing benefits, and suggested hiring an event planner to alleviate Dan Evans\' workload. While her arguments were well-justified, the conversation concluded before she could fully elaborate on the feasibility of hiring a dedicated catering staff member within Malawi\'s current operational model.','[{"score":5,"feedback":"Macie consistently referenced specific points and quotes from the reading material, demonstrating a strong understanding of the case facts and company context.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"Macie provided generally strong answers, identifying key opportunities and risks. Her suggestion to hire an event planner was a clear attempt to address the bottlenecks identified. The conversation ended before she could fully develop her final point regarding the justification for a new dedicated role.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":5,"feedback":"Macie consistently justified her answers by directly quoting or extensively paraphrasing relevant information from the case, demonstrating strong analytical skills in connecting her recommendations to the provided material.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','strict',0,4,'I liked how kent kind of fought back with me and challenged my ideas.. I thought it was good to have to defend my point of view and give specific evidence','I think that if there were some more creative questions it could be helpful!','gemini-2.5-flash-lite','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: I would recomend staying in the catering business but also altering some of your catering processes\n\nCEO: That\'s a bold recommendation, STUDENT. Tell me, what specifically in the case leads you to believe we should continue with catering, despite the challenges?\n\nSTUDENT: The case says "Catering fit nicely into the day-to-day operations of the restaurant. For the most part, catering didnt require a lot of extra effort outside of the restaurants normal operations. " The scheduling was the most time consuming and difficult part but it was still considered profitable especially because Malawi\'s is only catehring to around 10 events per year\n\nCEO: You\'re right that the case mentions catering fitting into daily operations and its profitability. However, you\'ve highlighted the scheduling as a difficult part, and you\'ve also noted that Malawi\'s is only catering about ten events per year.\n\nConsidering this, how do you reconcile the idea of "staying in the catering business" with the fact that the current scale is very small and that the planning process, as described, takes a significant amount of Dan Evans\' time  anywhere from 3 to 10 hours per event?\n\nSTUDENT: I would say that the cost of scheduling is worth it because cetering is also a useful advertising tool that malawais can use. If they cater for a big event and it goes well they are protecting brand image and they are building trust and hopefully a connection with the customers who use their catering services! also the case tells us that "Catering was seen as a much more profitable model than traditional restaurant service because of the low overhead, and higher profit margin"\n\nCEO: Those are good points, STUDENT. The case does indeed state that catering is more profitable due to lower overhead and higher margins. It also mentions that catering serves as a word-of-mouth marketing tool.\n\nHowever, you\'ve focused on the benefits. What are the *risks* associated with this advertising and brand-building approach, especially given the operational challenges you mentioned earlier with Dan Evans\' time commitment and the limited number of events?\n\nSTUDENT: The risks are if the catering does not go well it could seriously hurt our brand reputation. In addition time is a resource and it takes time to plan an event well and taking time out of Dan Evans schedule to plan is time that he is not spending managing the restruant itself. I\'d reccomend that Malawis hire a event planner to better allow Dan to focus on the restruant itself and to better expand the catering business because it is profitable, and would help brand image with marketing. I think if you had a focused team dedicated to vcetering you could also minimize the risks that come from the limited number of events and you could target customers and advertise your catering services more.\n\nCEO: That\'s an interesting recommendation, STUDENT, proposing to hire an event planner. But where in the case does it support the idea that we should hire a new person specifically for event planning to address these issues?\n\nSTUDENT: It does not give evidence to support this specifically in the case, however the case also says " they were always directed to Evans, who would ask a few specific questions\nto determine the date (preventing scheduling conflicts), the type of event, and the expected number\nof attendees. At this time, he would also ask a few initial questions to get a broad picture of the\nclients needs and would then set up an appointment to discuss the clients expectations in more\ndetail. While Evans would occasionally hold this meeting over the phone, he disliked that approach,\npreferring to have as much direct interaction with the client as possible. Evans knew that catering\nevents commanded premium pricing, and he wanted the customers to feel as though they were\nreceiving the highest degree of attention and customization.\nThere were two types of clients for Malawis catering: professional event planners and non-\nprofessionalseveryday people with little to no experience planning events. This distinction made\nall the difference in the planning process because of the knowledge and skills the client contributed\nto the process. Professional event planners understood the food service industry, had experience\nwith food quantities and attendee expectations, knew where to place the catering team, and\nunderstood in general what questions needed to be asked. Evans enjoyed working with\nprofessional planners because they were fast and efficient. His meetings with them usually lasted\nthirty minutes unless there was an unusual logistical problem to be worked out. This was in stark\ncontrast to the much longer meetings with non-professional clients. " Based on this evidence I feel that Malawi\'s having a specific event planner would make them more efficent and help them have a better experience in their event planning because only half of the events are professional planners.\n\nCEO: I understand your reasoning for wanting to bring in an event planner, drawing from the description of Dan Evans\' extensive involvement and the distinction between professional and non-professional clients. You\'ve identified a clear bottleneck and a significant time sink for Dan.\n\nHowever, the case also states that "Malawi\'s had been offering catering service since they opened in 2010. In fact, they purchased a mobile oven even before they had a kitchen in their restaurant." It also mentions that "Malawi\'s did not have a staff that was dedicated to catering functions, but used the regular restaurant employees, most of whom worked part-time."\n\nGiven this information, how would you justify hiring a dedicated event planner for catering when the current model relies on existing restaurant staff and Dan Evans, and the business has only been handling about ten events per year? What specific evidence from the case supports the idea that adding a new, dedicated role is the *best* solution for scaling, rather than optimizing the existing processes or Dan\'s involvement?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 4\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: I liked how kent kind of fought back with me and challenged my ideas.. I thought it was good to have to defend my point of view and give specific evidence\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: I think that if there were some more creative questions it could be helpful!\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yep!\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('14938a6b-8338-495b-b1fc-9842857e55f3','2025-10-27 16:03:40','88cb11dd-0dc9-42cb-90a5-6bdc0a65af07',11,'Cole demonstrated a good ability to engage with the case material, especially as the conversation developed. While his initial stance was a bit narrow, he showed flexibility and responsiveness, adjusting his recommendations based on the CEO\'s prompts and effectively drawing on relevant information from the business case to justify his points. His practical suggestions for managing seasonality and the planning bottleneck indicate a solid understanding of operational challenges. Cole could further enhance his performance by anticipating counter-arguments based on the case\'s key details from the outset.','[{"score":4,"feedback":"Cole initially suggested discontinuing catering, which seemed to overlook its high profitability as stated in the case. However, as the conversation progressed, he demonstrated a good understanding of various aspects, such as the seasonality, Dan Evans\'s central role, and the challenges of scaling, all directly from the reading material. His suggestions for seasonal workers and multiple planners showed a practical application of the case\'s details.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":3,"feedback":"Cole\'s initial recommendation to exit catering lacked a comprehensive view of the strategic implications discussed in the case, particularly regarding profitability and brand awareness. While he had a moment of \'Idk,\' he quickly recovered. His later suggestions, like hiring seasonal workers and cross-training staff for planning, were practical and solid responses to the challenges posed by the CEO. He demonstrated improvement in his answers as the conversation unfolded.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"After a somewhat generalized initial justification, Cole significantly improved his ability to connect his answers directly to the case. He effectively used information about catering\'s profitability, its inconsistent nature, Dan Evans\'s specific workload, and the goal of franchising to justify his evolving recommendations. This showed a strong capacity to apply case details to strategic decision-making.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','leading',0,4,'Helps me know small details of the case','Less agreeable','gemini-2.5-flash-lite','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: Hi Kent, after much research I beleive that should not do catering anymore. At the end of the day we need to specicalize in one thing and we need to pick one or the other. Central restuarant operations and putting cpaital into that are going to be much more important than trying to focus on two things\n\nCEO: That\'s a very interesting perspective, STUDENT! Focusing on specialization and strengthening our core restaurant operations is certainly a valid strategic consideration. You\'re right, specialization can lead to excellence.\n\nHowever, the case does mention that catering is the "most profitable part of the restaurant operation." What are your thoughts on that fact when considering your recommendation to discontinue catering? How do you reconcile the profitability of catering with your desire for specialization?\n\nSTUDENT: It is the most portiable right now, and when we have evenrts. the thing about catering is it is an inconisstnet business compared ot having a brick and mortar restuarant running. If we put more focus into restuarant operations, profits would also be able to increase\n\nCEO: That\'s a sharp observation, STUDENT. You\'ve hit on a key point: the inconsistency of catering demand. It\'s true that a brick-and-mortar restaurant offers a more predictable revenue stream.\n\nYou\'ve also highlighted that catering is "inconsistent." The case does mention that Malawis was catering about ten events per year, mostly in the summer months. How do you think this seasonality and inconsistency might impact our ability to franchise the business, which is a major goal for us?\n\nSTUDENT: Well if we take out catering we dont need to worry about it and we would be able to franchise as normal\n\nCEO: That\'s a very direct approach, STUDENT. Removing catering would certainly simplify the franchising model by eliminating that variable.\n\nHowever, the case also states that catering is a significant driver of brand awareness, with attendees at events essentially "taste testing" our pizza. If we discontinue catering, how do you propose we replace that valuable word-of-mouth marketing and brand exposure, especially since the case mentions we do almost no advertising?\n\nSTUDENT: Idk\n\nCEO: No problem at all, STUDENT. Let\'s think about this together. You\'re right, it\'s a significant challenge to replace that kind of organic marketing.\n\nThe case mentions that catering events bring in hundreds of attendees and that people often choose Malawi\'s for catering based on attending a previous event or a recommendation. This suggests that the *experience* at a catered event is a powerful marketing tool.\n\nGiven that, if we were to *continue* with catering, how might we leverage that attendee experience to *improve* our brand awareness, rather than eliminate it? What aspects of the catering experience, as described in the case, could be further amplified to serve as marketing for the restaurants?\n\nSTUDENT: Ok lets change up, most ofo ur events are done in the summer and we can hire seaosnal wokers ot keep it going in busy months and not waste captial doing it the other 8/9 months of the year\n\nCEO: That\'s a fantastic idea, STUDENT! Hiring seasonal workers is a brilliant way to manage the fluctuating demand and control costs, especially during those peak summer months. It shows you\'re thinking practically about resource allocation.\n\nNow, let\'s dig a little deeper into the operational side. The case mentions that Dan Evans spends a significant amount of time, anywhere from 3 to 10 hours, planning events with clients, especially those who aren\'t professional event planners. How would your plan to hire seasonal workers address this reliance on Dan Evans and his time for event planning and execution?\n\nSTUDENT: We will have workers on standby, we can pay a littler bit more as catering is more profitable\n\nCEO: That\'s a good thought, STUDENT. Having workers on standby is definitely part of the solution. And you\'re absolutely right, the higher profitability of catering does give us some flexibility to invest a bit more in staffing.\n\nHowever, the case specifically points out that Dan Evans\'s involvement in planning can take *hours* per client, and it relies on his personal "intuition, experience, and knowledge." Simply having more staff on standby doesn\'t directly address the *planning bottleneck* that Dan represents. How can we ensure that the planning process itself becomes more efficient and less dependent on one individual, especially if we want to franchise this operation? What does the case suggest might be ways to streamline that client interaction?\n\nSTUDENT: If it is just one person on planning, lets make sure multiple people who are good as event planning are able to be on standby to plan these events. Somebdouy who understands the operatiosn behind cartering\n\nCEO: That\'s a very positive step, STUDENT! Training multiple people to handle event planning is a great idea for redundancy and skill-building. It definitely moves us away from relying solely on Dan.\n\nThe case mentions that Dan enjoys having "as much direct interaction with the client as possible" to ensure they feel attended to. While having multiple planners is good, the *process* of planning itself can still be very time-consuming. The case also notes that professional event planners are "fast and efficient" because they understand the industry.\n\nHow could we potentially adapt our process to be more efficient, perhaps by providing clients with more self-service options or standardized information, similar to how professional planners operate, without losing that personal touch that makes our catering special? Are there any tools or methods mentioned in the case that could help with this?\n\nSTUDENT: Sacrifices might need to be made to have a little less interaction. Maybe Dan can stop in for an hour or whatever spare time he has to make sure the customer knows he cares and is taken care of. Human interactions from malawis is still there. At the end of the day more demand is going to come and dan is one man\n\nCEO: You\'re absolutely right, STUDENT. Dan is one man, and the demand is growing. Making some adjustments to the level of interaction is likely necessary to scale. I appreciate you recognizing that a degree of sacrifice in the hyper-personalized interaction might be needed.\n\nThe case does suggest a few ways to streamline the planning process. For instance, it mentions the idea of a website for learning about options and requesting engagements, and also an "engagement information form" that clients could fill out. How might these tools help reduce Dan\'s planning time while still allowing for human interaction and ensuring client needs are met?\n\nSTUDENT: Time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Grea