arce) individuals like Evans? Think about how we manage the *process* itself.\n\nSTUDENT: We can also buy another oven and have Evans work full time as a caterer planner between our restaurants as they go to these events and have him oversee both sites\n\nCEO: Purchasing another mobile oven is certainly a tangible step towards increasing capacity, and having Evans oversee multiple events could distribute his time.\n\nHowever, the case also mentions that the *planning* and client interaction itself is a significant bottleneck, taking 3-10 hours per client. Simply having more ovens won\'t solve the problem of Evans being the sole point person for intricate client needs. How does the case suggest we can streamline or offload that planning burden, even if Evans is overseeing multiple events?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 4\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: I enjoyed how it made me site the case and refer back to the material provided\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: I think it might be nice to have more time to do it and think through my responses. I enjoyed it and want to go further.\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing t