n scaling this operation?\n\nSTUDENT: Market more to the more formal event spaces rather than the more seasonal ones like weddings. Sports venues and business events happen more year round so securing business from these sectors could better justify the investment\n\nCEO: That\'s an interesting idea, STUDENT. Focusing on year-round institutional events could indeed smooth out demand. However, the case states that "social events, such as wedding dinners and wedding receptions, constituted roughly half of the events they catered each year," and these are typically larger events with more attendees.\n\nHow would shifting our focus to institutional events impact the volume and profitability of our catering business, considering the case highlights the "potentially big volume engagements" from social events?\n\nSTUDENT: It would mean that general volume and profitability per event would decrease, given that increased attendees increase the margin per plate. However the increased exposure in these event settings would highlight Malawi\'s order winners compared to other catering options (like the ambiance created by the specialized ovens) and create a higher volume of business, ensuring value in hiring catering-specific employees\n\nCEO: I see your point about potential exposure and utilizing dedicated staff. However, the case also highlights that "non-professional event planners often want advice about event planning, which is like free consulting and takes up a lot of manager Dan Evans time." This is a significant operational burden.\n\nHow would you propose to manage the planning process for these institutional clients, especially if they are also non-professional event planners, without replicating the time-intensive involvement of Dan Evans?\n\nSTUDENT: Developing simplified manuals with general event planning principles that coincide with Malawi\'s general methods of operation could ensure that clients see how the process would work from the very beginning and minimize the consulting that Dan is currently doing\n\nCEO: That\'s a good thought, STUDENT. Providing clients with planning resources could streamline the process. However, the case specifically mentions that the time Evans spends with clients can range from "3 to 10 hours depending on the clients needs."\n\nHow would a manual, even a detailed one, fully address the unique needs and questions of a non-professional event planner who might require that level of personalized guidance, and what specific details from the case would support your belief that a manual alone is sufficient?\n\nSTUDENT: I don\'t necessarily think that manuals alone are sufficient. By increasing year-round business we can justify hiring staff specific to the catering field, freeing up leaders like Evans. These staff could also make bonuses for giving extra time to helping clients, and clients could pay premiums for specialized consulting services\n\nCEO: Hiring dedicated catering staff and offering premium consulting services are indeed potential solutions to reduce Evans\'s burden. However, the case also points out that "Malawis had been offering catering service since they opened in 2010... Malawi\'s was catering about ten events per year, mostly in the summer months with one or two in the winter."\n\nGiven this low volume of events, how can we justify the cost of hiring dedicated catering staff and offering specialized consulting services when the current demand doesn\'t seem to support it? Where in the case does it suggest we can generate enough business to sustain these new roles?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? 