fore even agreeing to business, malawi\'s and evans would send a document over with their expectations and if the customer can meet these, then they would do business?\n\nCEO: That\'s an interesting idea, STUDENT. A pre-engagement document outlining expectations could certainly help filter clients and clarify the scope of our services. It aligns with the idea of setting clearer expectations.\n\nHowever, the case also points out that a significant portion of our catering clients are "non-professionalseveryday people with little to no experience planning events." How would this document address their potential lack of knowledge and ensure they understand our expectations, rather than just being overwhelmed or confused by it? What would be in this document to make it effective for them?\n\nSTUDENT: We could provide a list of event planners in the area they could coordinate to and help direct them to people that would handle logistics and party planning and all we do is cooridnarte with the planner and show up on time with the pizza\n\nCEO: That\'s a creative solution, STUDENT. Leveraging professional event planners for the logistical and planning aspects would certainly streamline Dan Evans\'s involvement. It addresses the "free consulting" issue head-on.\n\nThe case does mention that professional event planners are "fast and efficient" to work with. However, what are the potential downsides or risks of relying on third-party event planners, especially considering our goal to franchise Malawi\'s Pizza? How do we ensure brand consistency and quality when another entity is managing a significant part of the client interaction?\n\nSTUDENT: We send updates to the client after major decisions are made and cc them on any messaging--however we make it clear our job is to serve the food and show up ontime and thats it\n\nCEO: I understand the desire to clearly define our role. However, the case also highlights the importance of the "attendee experience" and "word-of-mouth" for