quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: Hi Kent, thank you for meeting with me. After analyzing your situation, I believe Malawis Pizza should stay in the catering business, but with a more focused strategy. Catering aligns with your mission of Pizza with a Purpose, increases brand exposure, and drives additional revenue. However, to avoid it becoming a distraction, I recommend streamlining operationsperhaps by dedicating a small, specialized team or simplifying the catering menu. This way, you can maintain efficiency in restaurant operations while still benefiting from catering growth.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, that\'s a fantastic start. I really like how you\'re thinking about this strategically, not just as a yes or no question. You\'ve hit on some key themes: brand exposure and revenue. That\'s exactly right.\n\nHowever, I\'m looking at the operational side of this. The case notes that Dan Evans, my General Manager, spends between 3 and 10 hours planning each event. That\'s a huge time commitment for a key employee. It seems like a significant distraction.\n\nFrom a purely financial standpoint, convince me. What evidence is there in the case that this time-consuming catering operation is actually worth the investment and the drain on my manager\'s time?\n\nSTUDENT: Thats a great point, Dans time is definitely valuable, and 3 to 10 hours per event is a lot. But from a financial perspective, the numbers show that catering still makes sense. The case mentions that catering brings in about 15% of total sales with higher profit margins than dine-in orders, since many of the costslike rent and utilitiesare already covered by the restaurant. So even though it takes time, its generating solid returns and helping cover fixed costs. If we can find ways to make the process more efficient, like delegating some tasks or standardizing event planning, we can keep those financial benefits without draining Dans time as much.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, that\'s a brilliant way to frame itfocusing on the financial returns and covering fixed costs. That\'s exactly the kind of sharp analysis I was hoping for.\n\nYou mentioned it brings in about 15% of sales with higher margins. I\'m trying to find that specific number in the case myself. While I\'m looking, could you point me to the most powerful statement in the case that describes the financial contribution of our catering business? I feel like there was a very direct quote about its importance.\n\nSTUDENT: Thats a great point and youre right, Dans time investment is huge. But financially, the case is clear that the catering operation is worth it. The most direct statement comes when it says, the catering process was an important part of the planned movement into franchising, and catering was the most profitable part of the restaurant operation. Thats about as strong as it gets  it shows that even though its time-consuming, catering isnt just a side project; its the highest-margin part of the business and key to Malawis long-term strategy.\nSo from a financial standpoint, the case shows that catering directly drives profitability and future growth. Its not just worth the investment  its essential to the business model Malawis is trying to scale.\n\nCEO: Excellent, STUDENT. That\'s the exact quote I was looking for. "The most profitable part of the restaurant operation." That\'s a powerful statement. You\'ve clearly read the case and understand the financial stakes. Good, you\'ve convinced me of the value.\n\nSo, let\'s pivot to the \'how.\' You\'ve sold me on keeping the business. But the case makes it crystal clear that the whole operation depends on Dan Evanshis intuition, his experience, and the 3-10 hours he spends per client. That\'s not a process we can franchise.\n\nHow do you propose we solve that scalability problem and the heavy reliance on Dan Evans? Your insights here would be invaluable.\n\nSTUDENT: Youre totally right, Kent, thats the biggest issue. Right now, catering works because of Dan, not because of a system. To scale it, wed need to turn his process into a repeatable system.\nId suggest mapping everything he does using Process Chain Network (PCN) analysis  breaking down each step from client contact to event delivery. That would help us see which parts require his expertise and which can be standardized or delegated.\n\nOnce thats clear, we can create **templates, checklists, and training guides** so future managers or franchisees can follow the same process without needing Dans intuition. In short, wed be turning his personal skill into a scalable system.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, that\'s a brilliant insight! Using PCN analysis to map Dan\'s process is exactly the kind of structured thinking we need. "Turning his personal skill into a scalable system"... you\'ve absolutely nailed the core challenge for franchising. Fantastic.\n\nLet\'s make this concrete. The case highlights two types of clients: the efficient professional planners and the non-professionals who take up hours of Dan\'s time, essentially getting free event planning advice.\n\nUsing your idea of templates and checklists, how could we create a specific tool or process to streamline the interaction with those non-professional clients, freeing up Dan\'s time while still making them feel valued?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 4\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: That it would respond to my response then pose a new question that made me think deeper.\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: Honestly I thought it was great\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes you can\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('aac18751-9ab7-4365-97d9-06907d6e735a','2025-10-27 19:04:16','4951dc9d-f88e-458e-b3ee-e14a296d6722',12,'Carsyn demonstrated a strong understanding of the business case, effectively using details from the text to support their responses. They provided thoughtful, practical suggestions for improving the catering operation\'s scalability and profitability. While the answers were solid, there\'s an opportunity to provide even more specific details in response to certain prompts.','[{"score":4,"feedback":"The student consistently referenced specific details from the case, such as Dan Evans\'s planning time, the concept of PCN Analysis, and the importance of customization. This indicates a strong understanding of the provided material.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"The student provided thoughtful and well-reasoned answers that directly addressed the CEO\'s concerns. They demonstrated an ability to synthesize information from the case and offer practical solutions, although some suggestions could have been more detailed.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"The student effectively used information from the case to support their arguments, particularly when discussing profitability, scalability, and the importance of customization. They linked their suggestions back to the challenges and opportunities presented in the business case.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','strict',0,4,'It caused me to get specific on my suggestions and back up everything with the case details','I\'m not sure','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash-lite','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: Yes, we should stay in the catering business as the case reveals that catering is the most profitable part of our restaurant operation. It is profitable because it gets the brand out there, provides high margins, and low overhead. However the way we approach catering need to be reframed because it is currently very labor intensive and structured in a  way that creates a stressful bottleneck in operations. These pain points are addressable so we should not give up on the initiative entirely until those have been addressed.\n\nCEO: You\'ve identified the core tension, STUDENT. You say it\'s profitable, but you also say it\'s a "stressful bottleneck."\n\nThe case mentions Dan Evans can spend between 3 and 10 hours planning a single event. That\'s a huge time commitment for my General Manager. How can we call this a high-margin business when my most skilled manager is spending that much unbilled time just on planning?\n\nSTUDENT: Youre right. Dan spending up to 10 hours planning one event definitely cuts into the margins. I dont think that means catering isnt profitable though, it just means the process isnt scalable yet. Right now it relies too much on his personal touch.\n\nIf we document and standardize how those events are planned, like using preset menu options, pricing templates, or offering simpler tiers such as a drop-off option, we can cut that planning time way down. I would also look at training another employee to handle the front-end logistics so Dan can focus on quality and operations.\n\nCatering can stay high-margin. We just need to structure it so the time and effort match the return.\n\nCEO: Standardization and templates... that sounds efficient.\n\nBut the case says Evans believes we command premium pricing precisely *because* we offer "the highest degree of attention and customization."\n\nAren\'t you worried that by standardizing, we\'ll lose the very thing that allows us to charge a premium, STUDENT? We might become just another generic pizza caterer.\n\nSTUDENT: Youre right, the personalization is what makes Malawis catering feel special, and we dont want to lose that. Standardization doesnt have to make us generic. What Im suggesting is creating customizable templates that use a clear decision-making framework.\n\nThat framework would outline which parts of the process must stay consistent with the Malawis brand and which can be adjusted for each client. It keeps the same high-quality service and mission-driven story but gives flexibility to adapt menu options, presentation, or service style based on the event.\n\nIt also means larger strategic decisions stay with leadership while smaller, on-the-ground calls can be made by the catering team in real time. This balance lets us stay efficient and consistent across future franchises while still feeling personal to the customer.\n\nBy combining structure with flexibility, we protect what makes Malawis unique, free up management time, and make the model something we can actually scale.\n\nCEO: That\'s a solid point, well-supported by the facts. A "decision-making framework" sounds like a good theoretical approach.\n\nSo, let\'s get practical. You\'ve convinced me of the value. Now, how do we solve the scalability problem and the heavy reliance on Dan Evans, especially with our goal to franchise? The case specifically says the process depends on his \'intuition, experience, and knowledge.\' How do you propose we document something as intangible as \'intuition\' so that a franchisee in another state can replicate this successfully?\n\nSTUDENT: Youre right, that is the hardest part. Dans intuition is what makes everything run smoothly, and we cannot just hand that off in a manual. What we can do is break his intuition down into patterns and decisions that can be observed and documented.\n\nThe first step would be to shadow Dan through several catering events and map his process using something like a PCN Analysis. That would help us see where his judgment is most critical, what types of decisions he makes, and why. From there, we can turn those insights into teachable principles and clear guidelines that others can follow.\n\nWe could also build a short training program with real examples and scenarios so new managers can practice making similar decisions before an event. It will not fully replace Dans experience, but it will let franchisees understand the logic behind his choices and apply that same reasoning.\n\nIn short, we turn his intuition into a framework for good judgment rather than trying to copy his instincts word for word\n\nCEO: Breaking down his process is the right idea. But let\'s get specific.\n\nThe case mentions that a large part of Evans\'s job with non-professional clients is to "explain how catering works" and that this often leads to him feeling like he\'s "planning the whole event."\n\nHow would your new, documented process handle a client who hasn\'t chosen a venue yet, or who needs advice on things outside of the food service? What specific tool or procedure would you give a franchisee to manage that situation efficiently without alienating the customer?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 4\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: It caused me to get specific on my suggestions and back up everything with the case details\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: I\'m not sure\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: Yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
