i\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: You should stay in the catering business\n\nCEO: I hear you, STUDENT. But my main concern is that the entire operation seems to depend on Dan Evans. The case mentions he spends 3 to 10 hours with each client, and the process relies on his personal intuition and experience.\n\nHow can we possibly franchise a business that\'s so dependent on one person\'s expertise?\n\nSTUDENT: Dan can make standard operation procedures based on his knowledge and expereicne and train those that wish to franchise\n\nCEO: That\'s a logical step, STUDENT. But the case mentions that with non-professional clients, Dan often ends up acting as a free event planner. That\'s where the hours rack up.\n\nHow can a standard operating procedure possibly replicate that level of customized hand-holding for a franchisee?\n\nSTUDENT: When starting off with a client, we could list off information required from the customer to help streamline the process or only work with professional event planners\n\nCEO: Interesting, you\'re suggesting two different paths there, STUDENT. Let\'s explore the second one for a moment: only working with professional event planners.\n\nThe case mentions that social events, like weddings, make up roughly half of our catering business. Many of those are planned by the very non-professionals you\'re suggesting we turn away.\n\nWhat would be the financial impact of cutting out half of our most profitable business segment?\n\nSTUDENT: It would initally cut or business but it would give us the ability to scale in a way that requreis less man hours on our end\n\nCEO: I see the logic in simplifying the process, STUDENT. But you\'re telling me to cut revenue from our most profitable operation in half.\n\nHow does that decision align with our goal of *growing* the business through franchising? It seems counterintuitive to shrink the customer base to grow.\n\nSTUDENT: give me a hint\n\nCEO: Of course. You\'re right that the time spent with non-professional clients is the bottleneck. The case mentions that Dan feels like he\'s planning the whole event for them because they have so many basic questions.\n\nInstead of turning away that entire customer segment, think about how we could give them the guidance they need in a more scalable way. Is there a tool or a process we could create that would answer their common questions and guide them through the planning steps, making them more efficient to work with, much like the professional planners?\n\nThat\'s your one free hint. Any future hints will cost you a point on your evaluation.\n\nSTUDENT: That was the lesser of the  we could create a list of questions that we need the client to answer prior to meeting with us to help guide them on information we need to streamline the amount of time we need to meet with those clients\n\nCEO: Okay, a pre-meeting questionnaire is a good, practical idea. I see how that could streamline things.\n\nBut we\'ve had some real on-the-ground problems. The case mentions an event where the team had to back the oven down a long, curvy driveway, which caused a huge delay. Another time, there was no place to park at all.\n\nHow would your questionnaire prevent that kind of logistical nightmare for a new franchisee who doesn\'t have Dan\'s years of experience to fall back on?\n\nSTUDENT: Make it clear that we need a place to park on the questionaire and that would be a question we ask the client in person when we meet with them. And that is also why the new franchisee would go through training with dan so that they could gain experience and be able to come up with a solution in one of those situations\n\nCEO: Okay, so the questionnaire puts the responsibility on the client. I can see that.\n\nBut STUDENT, a non-professional planner might not know what "accessible by a pickup with a large trailer" truly means. They might say \'yes\' on a form without understanding the turning radius or the clearance we need, leading to the exact kind of on-site disaster described in the case.\n\nHow can we make this process foolproof so that a franchisee isn\'t just relying on a client\'s best guess?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 4\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: That it stuck to the case and refered back to it when it pushed back on my ideas\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: It didn\'t seem to like the idea of training and the exptrise that could be passed on\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_m