ents expect? Are there ways to streamline the client interaction itself, rather than just training more people to do the same time-consuming process?\n\nSTUDENT: The specific event planner is the solution! This role would allow intense commitment to clients, the time necessary to work through the details, and the expertise necessary. They would actually be better than Dan because they won\'t be tied in a million other directions running the restaurant and the actual catering events.\n\nCEO: I understand your point about a dedicated event planner, STUDENT. Having someone solely focused on client interactions could certainly improve service quality and potentially reduce Dan\'s direct workload.\n\nHowever, consider our goal of franchising. If each franchise location needs to hire a dedicated "specific event planner" to spend "3 to 10 hours" per client, how does that impact the scalability and profitability of the catering operation for a franchisee? The case mentions that "wages were expected to account for approximately 30% of an average catering firms\' expenses." Adding a dedicated, high-touch planner for potentially only ten events a year, as we currently do, seems like it could significantly inflate labor costs for a franchisee.\n\nHow do we make this dedicated planner role efficient and cost-effective enough for a growing franchise?\n\nSTUDENT: Time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: Yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: It pushed back\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated