5,'The pressure from Ken','In a real discussion, Ken would ask pointed, short questions to drive into it.','gemini-2.5-flash','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: Hi Kent, it\'s a pleasure to meet with you today. After reviewing your margins, core competencies, capabilities, and experience thus far, I recommend you should stay in the catering business. Let me explain.\n\nCEO: That\'s a strong opening statement, STUDENT. You\'ve mentioned margins, core competencies, capabilities, and experience. Can you elaborate on **why catering is a good fit for Malawi\'s Pizza, specifically referencing facts from the case to support your claim?**\n\nSTUDENT: The two overarching points as to why you need to maintain your catering business are 1.) create consumer occasions that extend beyond the restaurant and 2.) it provides financial capabilities and stability that enhances your overall mission to support your social initiative for the children in Malawi. \n\nRegarding the first point, due to your limited size and scope of the business today, offering catering services enables you to broaden your reach and to show potential franchisees about the Malawi culture.\n\nCEO: You\'ve brought up "consumer occasions" and "broadening reach," which sounds like marketing. And you\'ve tied it to our social mission and franchising.\n\n**How does the case specifically support the idea that catering "broadens your reach" or helps "show potential franchisees about the Malawi culture?"** What evidence from the document suggests catering is an effective marketing tool or a good demonstration of our brand for future franchisees?\n\nSTUDENT: Based upon the data and context you provided, Malawi\'s offers catering options to special events like weddings and anniversaries, alongside professional events where the customer is put at the center of the experience. It creates a unique experience for consumers and with your unique oven it brings about the feeling of Malawi with a fire oven. Furthermore, citing specifically that at multiple events you have people walk over to the preparation area to see the entire cooking experience.\n\nCEO: You\'re right, STUDENT. The case does mention attendees commenting on the mobile oven and being interested in the cooking experience. It also notes that "Malawi\'s did almost no advertising of the catering service, they depended heavily on word-of-mouth and attendee experience."\n\nSo, you\'re arguing that the catering operation serves as a valuable marketing and brand-building tool, leveraging the unique mobile oven and the interactive experience to generate word-of-mouth. Good, you\'ve clearly read the case.\n\nNow, let\'s pivot to the practical implementation of your strategy. You\'re advocating for continuing catering. **How do you propose we solve the existing operational problems, specifically the scalability issue and the heavy reliance on Dan Evans, especially with our goal to franchise?**\n\nSTUDENT: Time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: Yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: The pressure from Ken\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: In a real discussion, Ken would ask pointed, short questions to drive into it.\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: Yes of course\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('46868cc0-5099-49c1-9dd1-5fa50db22df0','2025-12-03 15:30:19','ec4ddcd9-4ad4-4c73-8233-41cb176fbbea',13,'Brady demonstrated a strong understanding of the Malawi\'s Pizza case, effectively arguing for the continuation of the catering business by highlighting its strategic importance and unique offerings. The student thoughtfully addressed the challenges of scalability and replicability for franchising by proposing a dedicated catering manager role. While most answers were well-justified and articulated, the student could have provided more specific strategies when discussing the standardization of intuition-based processes to further enhance the depth of the response. Overall, it was a very good performance with clear logical reasoning.','[{"score":5,"feedback":"Brady demonstrated an excellent grasp of the case material, accurately referencing Malawi\'s vision, operational fit, and the unique on-site catering experience. The student also directly quoted the case to support their initial stance, showing a thorough understanding of the provided information and its relevance to the discussion.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"Brady\'s initial answers were solid, confidently stating a position and backing it up with relevant case details. The suggestion to create a dedicated catering manager role to address scalability and standardization was a strong strategic move. However, the last answer regarding how to standardize Dan Evans\'s intuition felt a bit generic, proposing a training program without delving into specific strategies for codifying complex, experience-based knowledge, which could have been more robust.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"The student consistently attempted to justify answers using information from the case, particularly in the early responses by directly quoting and referencing key aspects like Malawi\'s vision and operational efficiency. The proposed solution for a dedicated catering manager was also well-aligned with the case\'s discussion of franchising needs. While the justification was generally good, the final explanation for standardizing Evans\'s intuition could have drawn more deeply on specific challenges or opportunities presented in the reading material to provide a more robust justification.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','liberal',0,5,'I like that it gave me direction for what I need to consider','I liked it, no improvements','gemini-2.5-flash','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: You should stay in the catering business\n\nCEO: That\'s a strong opening statement, STUDENT. Tell me, what in the case makes you so confident that we should continue with catering? Please be specific with your reasoning and draw from the facts presented in the document.\n\nSTUDENT: Part of your vision from the beginning was catering. Additionally, it is one of the strongest differentiators you have.\nPizza is a very popular item to order for events, and you\'re method occupies a unique place in the competitive landscape. The experience of having the pizzas cooked on site it part of your appeal.\nAdditionally the case says " Catering fit nicely into the day-to-day operations of the restaurant. For the most part, catering didn\'t require a lot of extra effort outside of the restaurant\'s normal operations. "\n\nCEO: You\'ve hit on some key points, STUDENT: our initial vision, the unique on-site experience, and the general operational fit. I appreciate you citing the case directly.\n\nHowever, you mentioned that catering "didn\'t require a lot of extra effort outside of the restaurant\'s normal operations." The case also states that "the main exception was the time Evans would spend with the client planning the event, which could take anywhere between 3 and 10 hours depending on the client\'s needs."\n\nHow do you reconcile this significant time commitment from our General Manager, Dan Evans, with the idea that catering doesn\'t require "a lot of extra effort"? And what are the implications of this for our goal of franchising?\n\nSTUDENT: The implication is important to note. One solution is to separate out the roles. You should have a catering manager and a general manager with distinct responsibilities\n\nCEO: That\'s a direct approach, STUDENT. Creating a dedicated catering manager role could certainly alleviate the burden on Dan Evans.\n\nHowever, the case also mentions that "the catering process was an important part of the planned movement into franchising, and catering was the most profitable part of the restaurant operation." If we\'re going to franchise, we need to ensure our processes are replicable and scalable across multiple locations, not just dependent on one highly skilled individual.\n\n**How would creating a new, separate catering manager role at each potential franchise location address the issue of replicability and standardization, especially when we\'re trying to hand over processes to new franchisees?**\n\nSTUDENT: It would address the issue because you could have a standardized process with catering. The manager would be able to work out kinks with the process until it runs smoothly enough. Then you can codify it and distribute it to franchisees. They in turn can have someone in charge of catering that will own implementation\n\nCEO: That\'s a solid point, STUDENT. You\'re suggesting that a dedicated catering manager could be instrumental in *developing* and *documenting* a standardized catering process, making it replicable for franchisees. I like the idea of owning the implementation.\n\nHowever, the case highlights that our current catering process "depended on the intuition, experience, and knowledge that Evans had gained throughout his career in the restaurant industry." This isn\'t easily codified.\n\n**Specifically, what aspects of Dan Evans\'s current role would this new catering manager standardize, and what concrete steps would they take to move beyond Evans\'s "intuition and experience" to a documented, franchise-ready process?**\n\nSTUDENT: Although the experience Dan has is valuable, the steps are simple. Dan could provide a training program to pass on the key points.\n\nCEO: A training program is a good starting point for knowledge transfer, STUDENT. However, the case also points out that Dan spends "3 to 10 hours" with non-professional clients, often feeling like he\'s "planning the whole event instead of only catering it." This goes beyond just intuition; it\'s a heavy time commitment for personalized consulting.\n\nHow would a standardized training program specifically address this significant time drain and the need for *less* direct, high-touch interaction in a franchise model? What could be *standardized* or *automated* to reduce this reliance on individual expertise and extensive personal planning time?\n\nSTUDENT: Time is up.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: Sure\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: I like that it gave me direction for what I need to consider\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: I liked it, no improvements\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: Yes, please do!\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('bf0014a9-1283-4734-ad1a-f6d849decbb6','2025-12-03 15:30:20','f31e6574-38b5-4f0a-b393-ff86571f497b',14,'Ben demonstrated a strong grasp of the Malawi\'s Pizza case, clearly articulating key strategies and operational differences between the restaurant and catering business. He effectively used case facts to support his arguments and showed good analytical skills. While the conversation concluded prematurely, his contributions were insightful and well-justified.','[{"score":5,"feedback":"Ben demonstrated a strong understanding of the case material, accurately identifying Malawi\'s core strategies and specific operational details like the adjustment of POS stations. His answers consistently reflected a thorough reading of the provided text.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"Ben provided solid and well-reasoned answers, particularly in outlining Malawi\'s core strategies and detailing the operational differences between the restaurant and catering models. His response regarding the charitable aspect was thoughtful and balanced. While the final question was cut short, his preceding answers were strong.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":5,"feedback":"Ben excelled at justifying his answers by directly referencing specific details and quotes from the reading material. His ability to connect his arguments to concrete facts from the case demonstrated a strong analytical approach.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','moderate',0,4,'Your feedback and questions were deeper than surface level and did make me think more deeply about the case.','I would have liked more time to dig into the conversation.','gemini-2.5-flash','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: It depends on how closely you\'d like to stick to the main three strategies that Malawi\'s current focuses on.\n\nCEO: That\'s an interesting opening, STUDENT. To be clear, are you suggesting our existing strategies might be at odds with our catering operation?\n\nBefore we delve into "how closely" we stick to them, tell me this: **What are those main three strategies you\'re referring to, and how do they relate to the catering business?** Ground your answer in the facts of the case, please.\n\nSTUDENT: The three strategies are: 1) a healthy menu, 2) a fast casual service model, and 3) providing meals to those in need. The catering model is fundamentally different from a fast casual service model and the connection to providing meals to those in need get\'s muddied through the catering model (you personally aren\'t spending your money to help others). It is also unclear whether catering revenue is equated to service meal donations.\n\nCEO: You\'ve identified the core pillars of our brand well, STUDENT. I appreciate you bringing them up.\n\nNow, let\'s challenge that a bit. You claim the catering model is "fundamentally different" from fast-casual and that the charitable aspect "gets muddied."\n\n**Can you use specific facts from the case to explain *how* the catering model is fundamentally different in a negative way, and *why* you believe the charitable connection is weakened, rather than strengthened, by catering?**\n\nAnd regarding the meal donations, the case states "for every meal purchased by a customer the restaurant would donate a healthy meal to a child in Malawi." Does the case provide any information that specifically excludes catering meals from this promise?\n\nSTUDENT: The case states that "the catering process can vary widely depending on the event and the offering of the caterer" while the normal process in the restaurant is quite consistent in getting customers their food in a timely manner. It has been stated that the initial store build out included three points of sale, but was decreased because service operations were almost too quick. The catering model does not provide that same consistency and speed. Additionally, the case does not specifically say that catering meals are excluded from the promise, but it also doesn\'t specifically reinforce that they are included. This would be something important to highlight not only to the catering customer, but also those that ultimately eat the pizza. Without making that known, you are missing out on a key value of the company.\n\nCEO: You\'ve honed in on the operational differences, STUDENT, specifically the variability of catering versus the consistency and speed of our in-restaurant model. I agree that catering inherently involves more variables.\n\nHowever, you\'re focusing on the challenges. The case also clearly states that "catering was the most profitable part of the restaurant operation" and that Beck felt "in the future, catering could be a larger portion of Malawi\'s business, especially as they moved toward franchising."\n\nGiven these facts, **how do you reconcile the operational inconsistencies you\'ve identified with the clear financial benefits and strategic growth objectives tied to catering?** Should we simply abandon a highly profitable venture because it\'s not as "fast casual" as our main restaurant?\n\nSTUDENT: Time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: Yes.\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 4\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: Your feedback and questions were deeper than surface level and did make me think more deeply about the case.\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: I would have liked more time to dig into the conversation.\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: Yes.\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('0a3ec84d-8754-4c33-b329-2c1ce69c8a0c','2025-12-03 15:30:23','a5b250f3-982d-447f-8375-c7b457ec79c3',14,'Tyler demonstrated a strong understanding of the case material and provided well-reasoned answers throughout the conversation. He effectively used direct quotes and relevant information from the case to support his arguments, particularly regarding the profitability of catering. His suggestions for addressing scalability, such as developing a "playbook" and implementing a shadowing/supervised training program, were practical and directly aimed at the challenges presented. While the conversation concluded before fully addressing the nuanced challenge of reducing direct interaction time while maintaining a premium experience, Tyler showed good engagement and a thoughtful approach to problem-solving.','[{"score":5,"feedback":"Tyler demonstrated a thorough understanding of the reading material, consistently referencing specific details and themes from the case, such as the profitability of catering and the reliance on Dan Evans\' expertise. The CEO even explicitly stated, \\"Good, you\'ve clearly read the case, Tyler.\\"","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"Tyler provided strong, practical answers, especially by suggesting a \\"playbook\\" and a shadowing/supervised training program to address the scalability and knowledge transfer issues. While the final complex question about reducing client interaction time wasn\'t fully resolved before the conversation ended, his suggestions were well-considered and directly applicable to the challenges presented.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":5,"feedback":"Tyler excelled at justifying his points, most notably by directly quoting the case for the profitability argument. His subsequent suggestions consistently aimed to address challenges explicitly identified in the case, demonstrating a clear and solid link between his recommendations and the reading material.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','strict',0,5,'Kent challenged my thinking and pushed me to go deeper. He also revealed issues in my thinking that I hadn\'t considered.','It felt like Kent was trying to get at "a right answer" that he already knew. Maybe that\'s good maybe that\'s bad, I\'m not sure','gemini-2.5-flash','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: I think you should stay in the catering business as it can have better profit margins than the regular restaurant operations.\n\nCEO: That\'s a direct assertion, STUDENT. Can you back that up with specific facts from the case? Where does it state that catering has better profit margins?\n\nSTUDENT: Of course! The case states "Catering was seen as a much more profitable model than traditional restaurant service because of the low overhead (i.e., no need to maintain an entire restaurant facility) and higher profit margin. Even for full-service restaurants, catering was an exceptionally profitable activity."\n\nCEO: Good, you\'ve clearly read the case, STUDENT. That\'s a solid point, well-supported by the facts.\n\nHowever, the case also highlights significant operational challenges with our current catering model. Specifically, it heavily relies on Dan Evans\' personal involvement, taking anywhere from 3 to 10 hours for client planning alone. This isn\'t sustainable, especially with our goal to franchise.\n\nSo, if we\'re going to continue and expand catering, **how do you propose we solve the scalability problem and the heavy reliance on Dan Evans, particularly with our goal to franchise?**\n\nSTUDENT: I hear your concern. Scaling any venture definitely requires investment whether it\'s financially or with time. There will be trade offs. However, if the catering operations are more profitable than normal restaurant operations, it\'d be wise to allocate your resources more towards the most profitable option. One idea I thought about with your franchising question had to do directly with Dan Evans. Right now he\'s core to the catering operations. He\'s the one meeting with potential clients, scheduling the event, and organizing it, all organized in his paper notebook. In order to scale and franchise, you\'ll need a playbook that people besides Dan Evans can follow in order to successfully run the catering operations. Internal training materials can help a new catering lead pitch Malawi\'s services, close the sale, run them through a checklist of what they need to prepare and do in order to run a successful event. You can also prepare external sales materials that new leads can use to essentially dump all of the knowledge in Dan\'s head on a paper or presentation to make sure important pieces don\'t fall through the cracks.\n\nCEO: You\'re suggesting a "playbook" approach, STUDENT, which sounds like standardizing processes. That\'s a reasonable idea for franchising in general.\n\nBut let\'s ground this in the specifics of the case. Dan Evans\' involvement isn\'t just about a lack of documented process; the case states it "depended on the intuition, experience, and knowledge that Evans had gained throughout his career in the restaurant industry."\n\n**How specifically would your proposed "internal training materials" and "external sales materials" capture and replicate this "intuition, experience, and knowledge" so that a franchisee\'s catering lead could perform at Dan\'s level without his direct involvement?** Give me some concrete examples based on the challenges described in the case.\n\nSTUDENT: That\'s a great question. The playbook would offer a standardized source of truth, but there\'s definitely intuition and personal experience at play that makes the catering a success. Malawi\'s could set up a training program where a potential catering lead comes and shadows Dan Evan\'s in his catering operations for a time period before they are allowed to go off and do it on their own. To pass the training, Dan can have the trainee fully run an event to see how it goes. Once they pass the training program they\'re ready to do it on their own as a franchise.\n\nCEO: Shadowing and a supervised event are good ideas for transferring some tacit knowledge, STUDENT. I appreciate you trying to get specific.\n\nHowever, the case also points out that Dan spends "anywhere between 3 and 10 hours depending on the client\'s needs" just on planning. He\'s essentially acting as an event planner, especially for non-professional clients, answering many questions that "they should be answering, not asking."\n\nEven with shadowing, how does a new catering lead, or even Dan himself, scale this time-intensive, personalized planning for *every* client when our goal is to increase the *number* of catering events and franchise? **How do we reduce the direct interaction time required per client while maintaining that "premium pricing" experience?**\n\nSTUDENT: Time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: Yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: Kent challenged my thinking and pushed me to go deeper. He also revealed issues in my thinking that I hadn\'t considered.\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: It felt like Kent was trying to get at "a right answer" that he already knew. Maybe that\'s good maybe that\'s bad, I\'m not sure\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: Yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('2ea4b7ba-0c05-489a-9a30-ab5b543f4b6a','2025-12-03 15:30:23','e8922252-77d5-44a2-9f74-002be36df878',3,'Felix struggled significantly with understanding and applying the core facts of the Malawi\'s Pizza case. His initial recommendation to abandon catering was based on a misinterpretation of the restaurant\'s financial health and growth. While he eventually identified Dan Evans\'s time as a potential bottleneck, his arguments remained largely generic and lacked the specific, case-based justifications needed to develop a robust strategy for the company\'s franchising goals. To improve, Felix should focus on meticulous reading comprehension and practicing how to integrate specific case facts to support his recommendations.','[{"score":1,"feedback":"Felix\'s initial assessment of Malawi\'s Pizza\'s core business, stating it was \\"struggling\\" and had \\"closed down\\" a location, directly contradicted key financial and operational successes detailed in the reading material. While he later picked up on the \\"time\\" constraint mentioned, this initial factual inaccuracy heavily impacted his ability to build a consistent argument based on the provided information.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":1,"feedback":"Felix\'s answers were often generic and lacked the specificity required to address the CEO\'s questions effectively. His core argument that catering was a \\"distraction\\" was not supported by solid, case-based reasoning, especially when confronted with the high profitability of catering and the restaurant\'s overall success. While he eventually identified \\"time\\" as an issue, his responses didn\'t evolve into a comprehensive solution or well-articulated justification for his initial stance.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":1,"feedback":"Felix struggled to justify his answers using relevant information from the case. His early justifications were based on incorrect interpretations of the company\'s performance. Later arguments remained largely unsubstantiated by specific details, failing to connect his claims (e.g., catering \\"hurts\\" the main business) to factual evidence provided in the reading material.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','liberal',0,3,'stick to the case','Talk about the real facts about the business','gemini-2.5-flash','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: its a distaction\n\nCEO: That\'s a bold stance, STUDENT. The case explicitly states that catering is the "most profitable part of the restaurant operation." If we were to discontinue it, what\'s your plan to replace that high-margin revenue, and what impact would that have on our overall growth and profitability goals? Please justify your reasoning with specific facts from the case.\n\nSTUDENT: You should focus on a brick-and-mortar. You can see that it\'s a distraction because you opened a Spanish Fork location and closed it down. After so many years you still only have one location and its struggling.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, I appreciate your focus on our core business, but I need you to base your recommendations on the facts presented in the case.\n\nThe case actually states that the original Malawi\'s Pizza restaurant was a "quick success." It "broke even the first year," and "revenues grew 26% the second year and 13% the third year." Similarly, "EBITDA grew 10% in year two and 12% in year three." Furthermore, we "opened a second Malawi\'s Pizza restaurant in 2012, forty miles north of the original location," not closed one.\n\nGiven that the core restaurant operation is performing well and growing, and we have *two* locations, how do you reconcile your argument that catering is a distraction with the fact that it\'s our "most profitable part of the restaurant operation"?\n\nSTUDENT: the restaurant business is demanding. You want to restaurant business to be successful first beforeyou venture off\n\nCEO: I agree that the restaurant business is demanding, STUDENT. However, the case also points out that catering "fit nicely into the day-to-day operations of the restaurant" and "didn\'t require a lot of extra effort outside of the restaurant\'s normal operations" for the most part.\n\nGiven that, and the high profitability of catering, why do you believe it\'s a distraction rather than a complementary and beneficial part of our overall business strategy?\n\nSTUDENT: because it hurts your real bussiness to venture off\n\nCEO: STUDENT, I need you to be more specific. How exactly does catering "hurt" our main restaurant business, according to the facts in the case? Can you point to any negative impacts on our restaurant operations or brand that are directly caused by catering?\n\nSTUDENT: time\n\nCEO: Time is a critical resource, STUDENT, especially for a growing business. You\'re right to highlight it.\n\nThe case mentions that "the main exception was the time Evans would spend with the client planning the event, which could take anywhere between 3 and 10 hours depending on the client\'s needs." It also states that "managing its operations continued to consume most of his time."\n\nSo, if time is the primary "hurt" that catering inflicts, how do you propose we address this specific challenge to make catering less of a drain on Dan Evans\'s time, while still maintaining its profitability and contribution to our brand?\n\nSTUDENT: thats hard to do because it seems like you cant do both given you results. Yes your catering bussiness is great right now at a small scale but every business is like that at the start. You can let go of your real business because it might not be good in the long run. Clearly\n\nCEO: STUDENT, you\'re making a strong claim that we "can\'t do both." However, the case indicates our restaurant operations are *not* struggling. We have two successful locations, and both revenue and EBITDA are growing consistently.\n\nYou\'ve highlighted Dan Evans\'s time as the bottleneck. But if we are to achieve our primary business goal of **franchising**, we need to develop processes that are scalable and replicable, not dependent on a single individual like Dan.\n\nSo, if you truly believe we "can\'t do both" and catering is inherently unscalable, are you recommending we *discontinue* catering entirely? If so, again, how do you propose we replace its "most profitable" revenue stream? Or, if you believe there\'s a way to make it work, how would you specifically address the "time" issue to make catering scalable and replicable for a franchise model, given Dan\'s current workload?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: Yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 3\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: stick to the case\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: Talk about the real facts about the business\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
