eople and get word of mouth out about Malawi\'s. Once people are familiar with malawi\'s offering, new franchises can gain traction easier and earlier.\n\nCEO: You\'ve highlighted some compelling points, STUDENT. The projected industry growth and the fragmented nature of the catering market certainly present an opportunity for a more structured player like Malawi\'s. And you\'re right, the case does emphasize that catering is a key driver for word-of-mouth marketing, which is crucial for our brand and future franchising efforts.\n\nHowever, the case also states that catering is "an extremely interactive and hands-on process that depended on the intuition, experience, and knowledge that Evans had gained throughout his career." You mentioned the need for a "dedicated employee or third party" to handle inquiries. Given our goal to franchise, how do you propose we standardize and replicate this highly personalized, Evans-centric process across multiple locations, without Evans himself being present?\n\nSTUDENT: Evans can hire a dedicated in-house employee and train them to take his place. This employee should have catering experience (preferably pizza-related) and can shadow Evans to get a feel for how he evaluates incoming catering requests. Part of leadership is to delegate and empower others and this is an opportunity for him to do that.\n\nCEO: That\'s a valid point about delegation and empowerment, STUDENT. Training a dedicated in-house employee to shadow Dan Evans could certainly transfer some of his expertise.\n\nHowever, the case also mentions that Evans spends anywhere from "3 to 10 hours" with clients, especially non-professional event planners, explaining "how catering works" and feeling "as though he was actually planning the whole event instead of only catering it."\n\nIf we simply hire and train another person to do what Evans does, aren\'t we just replicating the same scalability problem, but with a different individual? How does this solve the fundamental issue of the process being so time-intensive and reliant on individual expertise, rather than a standardized, replicable system for future franchisees?\n\nSTUDENT: Great question. I propose having a standardized catering menu with variations based on size of party, diet restrictions, and event venue. This will allow clients to choose the option rather than negotiating everything with that dedicated catering employee.\n\nCEO: That\'s a solid strategy, STUDENT. Standardized catering packages or menus, with variations for party size, dietary needs, and venue, could significantly streamline the planning process. It would definitely reduce the amount of time a dedicated catering employee would need to spend with each client, especially the non-professional planners who currently require extensive hand-holding. This directly addresses the "3 to 10 hours" Evans spends per client.\n\nNow, let\'s pivot to a different challenge. The case highlights operational issues beyond just planning. For instance, there were problems with venue accessibility (narrow driveways, no parking), and miscommunications leading to client dissatisfaction (like the cleanup incident).\n\nHow would your proposed standardized menu and a dedicated catering employee help us mitigate these on-site logistical challenges and prevent future miscommunications, especially as we aim for a consistent, high-quality experience across multiple franchised locations?\n\nSTUDENT: While there still should be a dedicated employee, there should be an online quesionnare that can estbalish all the base parameters of the event so they know about our restrictions and we know about their location restrictions.\n\nCEO: That\'s an excellent addition, STUDENT. An online questionnaire to establish base parameters and clarify restrictions upfront is a smart move. It could certainly help address issues like venue accessibility and reduce miscommunication, as clients would be prompted to provide specific details about their location and expectations before the event. This also aligns with standardizing processes for franchising.\n\nYou\'ve made a strong case for continuing catering, addressing both the planning bottleneck and some logistical issues. Now, let\'s talk about the financial implications. The case states that "catering was the most profitable part of the restaurant operation." If we were to implement these changes  hiring a dedicated employee, developing standardized menus, and creating an online questionnaire  what impact do you foresee these investments having on that high profitability, and how would you ensure catering remains a significant profit driver as we scale?\n\nSTUDENT: Thank you for talking! Time is up unfortunately.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: Yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: I liked the follow up questions which challenged my recommendations and helped me think deeper.\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: Less recap of what I just said.\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: Yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
