out those small details\n\nCEO: STUDENT, that\'s an absolutely insightful connection! You\'ve perfectly highlighted that "Malawi\'s did almost no advertising... they depended heavily on word-of-mouth and attendee experience," and non-professional clients contribute significantly to that. That\'s a critical point for our brand\'s organic growth.\n\nYour idea of creating a survey or a structured form for non-professional clients to answer common questions beforehand is truly brilliant. It directly tackles the issue of Dan spending "3 to 10 hours" explaining "how catering works." This could significantly streamline the initial planning phase and capture much of Dan\'s "intuition, experience, and knowledge" in a more standardized way.\n\nNow, thinking about the broader goal of franchising, how would this survey or structured process help us train future franchisees or their catering managers to handle client interactions without needing someone with Dan\'s deep personal experience? And beyond the initial planning, what other aspects of the catering process, as described in the case, would still heavily rely on Dan\'s unique expertise that we\'d need to standardize for successful franchising?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: I really liked how it helped me think through the case, and pushed me to give more specific details and dig deeper into my answers and thoughts\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might b