tering model presents some complexities in that regard. The portable brick oven is indeed a crucial asset, but also a capital investment for each potential franchisee.\n\nNow, let\'s dig a bit deeper into those complexities. The case mentions that our catering is the "most profitable part of the restaurant operation" but also highlights its heavy reliance on a particular individual. **Who is that individual, and how does their central role create a scalability challenge for franchising, according to the case?** Your insights here would be invaluable.\n\nSTUDENT: Ken you are the individual. In order to scale this process, you would have to make that process replicable and then remove yourself from the process by hiring someone or making it part of the franchise owner\'s duties\n\nCEO: You\'ve absolutely nailed the core issue, STUDENT  the reliance on a single individual for the catering operation is indeed our biggest hurdle to replication. My role, as founder, is to ensure the overall vision, but the case actually points to **Dan Evans**, our General Manager, as that central figure for catering.\n\nYou\'re spot on that we need to make the process replicable and less dependent on one person for franchising.\n\nNow, thinking about Dan\'s specific role, what activities or responsibilities does the case say he undertakes that make the catering process so dependent on his "intuition, experience, and knowledge," making it difficult to scale for a franchise? What specific details from the case highlight this dependency?\n\nSTUDENT: There is industry knowledge that is needed to know in order to operate the catering side of the business. From the case "professional event planners and non-professionalseveryday people with little to no experience planning events. This distinction made all the difference in the planning process because of the knowledge and skills the client contributed to the process." Being able to educate the non-professionals is key. I think nailing down a process with the right questions and education is possible to help train an individual doing this job\n\nCEO: Excellent, STUDENT! You\'ve precisely identified a critical aspect of Dan Evans\'s role: educating non-professional event planners. The case explicitly states that his "intuition, experience, and knowledge" are heavily leveraged when dealing with these clients, often to the point where he feels like he\'s "planning the whole event instead of only catering it." That\'s a fantastic point, well-supported by the case facts.\n\nYou\'re absolutely right that "nailing down a process with the right questions and education" is key to training others. Now, let\'s think practically about that. **What specific mechanisms or tools could we implement to standardize Dan\'s knowledge and streamline the planning process for non-professional clients, making it replicable for a franchisee who might not have Dan\'s deep experience?** Think about how we could reduce that 3-10 hours of planning time per event.\n\nSTUDENT: you could implement a survey online to know exactly what people are looking for. This would then make it so you could ask the right questions\n\nCEO: That\'s a brilliant suggestion, STUDENT! An online survey is a fantastic idea to standardize information gathering and guide clients, especially the non-professionals, through the planning process. It\'s a very modern and efficient approach.\n\nTo build on that, the case mentions that Dan spends a significant amount of time discussing menus, pricing, and even venue considerations. **How could an online tool or other standardized resources, beyond just a survey, further assist in these specific areas to reduce the need for Dan\'s direct, lengthy interaction, while still providing that "premium" feel the clients expect?**\n\nSTUDENT: You could build a tool online that let\'s the customer build out the catering process and what they would like\n\nCEO: That\'s a powerful idea, STUDENT! A "build-your-own-catering" tool online would be incredibly effective. It leverages technology to put control in the client\'s hands, which can feel very premium and customized, while simultaneously standardizing the process on our end.\n\nNow, let\'s think about the practical details. The case mentions that Dan provides samples and discusses popular pizzas. **How could an online tool effectively convey menu options, suggest popular choices, and even handle pricing calculations without direct interaction, while still addressing the client\'s need for guidance and customization?** What elements would such a tool need to include, based on the information in the case?\n\nSTUDENT: tell me\n\nCEO: Ah, a hint request! Very well, STUDENT. Everyone gets one free hint, so consider this yours.\n\nThink about what Dan *currently* does during those lengthy planning meetings, as described in the case. He "recommends certain popular pizzas," "provides samples" (though an online tool can\'t do that, it can simulate it), "calculates the per-plate price on the fly" based on various factors, and even "works with budgets." He also answers questions about things like "weather" or "choosing a venue."\n\n**Hint:** How can you take these specific pieces of information and decision-making that Dan currently handles personally, and translate them into features or content on an online platform? Consider how a well-designed website or tool could offer pre-set packages, interactive pricing calculators, or even a FAQ section based on common client questions, to replicate Dan\'s guidance in a scalable way.\n\nRemember, after this, each hint will cost a point. Now, what are your thoughts on how an online tool could incorporate these elements?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\n