uition, experience, and knowledge that Evans had gained." We\'re trying to franchise Malawi\'s. **How do you reconcile continuing and expanding catering with this heavy reliance on one individual, and our goal to make processes replicable for franchisees?**\n\nSTUDENT: While Dan Evans is currently an essential piece to the catering business, his expertise can be passed on to multiple managers who can do the same thing. Writing down the process and FAQ of catering into a handbook can provide assistance as well to other managers who are doing catering and may have questions.\n\nCEO: That\'s a good point, STUDENT. Documenting processes and training other managers like Ed Jones could certainly help distribute the workload and reduce reliance on Dan\'s direct involvement.\n\nHowever, the case also mentions that planning meetings with non-professional clients can take Evans "anywhere between 3 and 10 hours." These clients "had no prior knowledge of catering," leading Evans to feel "as though he was actually planning the whole event instead of only catering it."\n\n**Even with a handbook, how do you propose we standardize and streamline this highly time-consuming, customized planning process for a franchise model, especially when dealing with clients who need so much hand-holding?**\n\nSTUDENT: Training several high-up managers how to do catering and leading them through on-site training can help them be leaders. They then can be the experts. In terms of streamlining, creating a written planning process can ensure that key points that clients are confused about are addressed every time one of these meetings is set up.\n\nCEO: Training managers and having a structured planning process are valid steps, STUDENT. That would certainly help ensure consistency.\n\nHowever, the case also presents another angle. It mentions Jane Goodman, a potential client who was upset when we couldn\'t accommodate her request for par-cooked pizzas for a self-catered event. Evans declined because "if the pizzas were not heated properly the quality might suffer, which would not reflect favorably on the Malawi\'s high-quality image." Yet, customers have also expressed interest in renting our mobile oven.\n\n**Given these points, have you considered alternative catering service models that might reduce the operational burden on our staff and Evans, while still leveraging our brand and product?**\n\nSTUDENT: Time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: Sure\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 4\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: He got to the important points rather quickly and brought up significant issues\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: I spent too much time thinking out responses and couldn\'t get deep into the analysis.\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUE