stry that if Malawi\'s pizza does it right, it can be a leader.  Catering also offers a great way to advertise to new customers.  An inherent risk of catering is the food you serve catering is not the same quality of food served in the restaurant which can potentially damage brand image.\n\nCEO: You\'re right, STUDENT, the case does explicitly state that catering is our "most profitable part of the restaurant operation," and it certainly offers a great way to advertise through word-of-mouth.\n\nHowever, you mentioned that catering "does not interrupt the day-to-day operations." The case also highlights that the planning process for catering events consumes a significant amount of Dan Evans\'s time  anywhere from 3 to 10 hours per client. How do you reconcile that with your assertion that it doesn\'t interrupt operations, especially when our goal is to franchise? And regarding the "growing industry," what specific growth figures from the case support that claim?\n\nSTUDENT: Can you give me a hint?\n\nCEO: Certainly, STUDENT. When considering Dan Evans\'s significant time commitment, think about the distinction between professional and non-professional event planners mentioned in the case. How does that distinction impact the time Evans spends, and what are the implications for standardizing our catering process if we want to franchise? Also, for the industry growth figures, refer to the "Catering Industry Overview" section in the case.\n\nRemember, everyone gets one free hint, and after that, each hint will cost you a point.\n\nSTUDENT: It shows that the catering business grows 2.3% annually.  I actually don\'t think that this is a significant growth rate and not worth the risk.\n\nCEO: You\'ve accurately cited the industry growth rate from the case, STUDENT. A 2.3% annual growth rate might not seem explosive on its own.\n\nHowever, the case explicitly states that catering is our "most profitable part of the restaurant operation." How do you reconcile your claim that