state "low overhead", not no overhead. Additionally, there are some things that make catering difficult.\n\nBut I would posit that while catering fresh pizza poses some unique challenges, there are some unique benefits. Par baked pizzas can be prepared ahead of time, and they only require a short time to finish cooking. I think if you can nail your training of new caterers, then this thing can go!\n\nCEO: You\'re right, STUDENT, par-baked pizzas are a logistical efficiency for the *event itself*. The case states they only take about 90 seconds to finish cooking, which is certainly fast.\n\nHowever, my concern about scalability isn\'t primarily about the speed of cooking at the event. The case clearly states that "the time Evans would spend with the client planning the event, which could take anywhere between 3 and 10 hours depending on the clients needs" and that the process "depended on the intuition, experience, and knowledge that Evans had gained."\n\nHow do you propose that "nailing your training of new caterers" would address this significant planning bottleneck and Evans\'s indispensable role, especially when our ultimate goal is to franchise and replicate this business model?\n\nSTUDENT: The process currently depends on evans intuition, but that does not mean that it needs always to depend on him. Creating training and standard operations processses for catering would lower the barrier of entry to becoming a good caterer. The setup is relatively lean, with just a truck and an oven. Standardizing processes, and potentially implementing a planning and scheduling system or portal, could allow customers to schedule in advance and not be dissapointed when time slots fill. Additionally, standardizing and simple automations of planning tasks and selections can drastically diminish the amount of time required in the planning process\n\nCEO: That\'s a solid point, STUDENT. You\'re suggesting we can standardize Evans\'s "intuition, experience, and knowledge" into a replicable process, and use technology like a portal to streamline client interactions. This directly addresses the bottleneck of Evans\'s time.\n\nNow, let\'s get practical. How specifically would you propose we standardize this highly customized, interactive planning process? What are the key elements of Evans\'s current 3-10 hour client meetings that we can either automate, simplify, or offload, keeping in mind the distinction between professional and non-professional planners mentioned in the case? And how would these changes ensure we maintain the "premium pricing" and "highest degree of attention and customization" that Evans currently delivers, especially as we look to franchise?\n\nSTUDENT: Time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: Yes!\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: A unique, catered case experience just for me, and just for the way I think. This experience was fast, fast learning\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: Maybe an initial assessment of understanding to guide Kent\'s interaction with the customer\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
