n the case.\n\nBut let\'s focus on the customer experience. A packet, a pricing grid, a website... that sounds very transactional. The case specifically says Evans wants customers "to feel as though they were receiving the highest degree of attention and customization" to justify our premium price.\n\nHow do you maintain that premium, high-touch feel when you\'re pushing clients to a standardized online form?\n\nSTUDENT: I think the meeting can still happen, after the potential client has self educated with out materials, and has an idea before the meeting starts of what exactly they want. \n\nThis also increases transparency so costs (fixed and variable) for the customer do not come as a surprise.\n\nCEO: I see. So the meeting still happens, but it\'s more efficient because the client comes in prepared.\n\nBut the case makes a clear distinction between professional planners and non-professionals. The non-professionals are the ones consuming those 10 hours, asking Evans for what amounts to free event planning advice.\n\nHow does your proposed system effectively handle these less experienced clients without them just bypassing the materials and calling Evans directly, which puts us right back at square one?\n\nSTUDENT: By having a standardized process beginning to end, that has clearly controlled for what aspects of the process are customizable, the non professional planners have a clear sense of direction and are able to know what we will and won\'t do. The professionals will also feel more comfortable plugging in our process into their workflow.\n\nCEO: A "clear sense of direction" is a good goal, STUDENT. But these are clients who, according to the case, don\'t even know what questions to ask. They\'re looking to Evans for basic event planning advice.\n\nLet\'s consider the Jane Goodman situation. Our inability to handle her non-standard request for par-cooked pizzas cost us a client and generated negative word-of-mouth. How does your more standardized, \'clearly controlled\' process avoid making that problem even worse for clients who don\'t fit neatly into your new boxes?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: I like that it pushed back and made me think hard and actually justfiy my answers\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: no recommendations\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes please do\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
