ategic connections from the case could have strengthened his arguments further.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','strict',0,5,'Challenged assumptions','I think it could be improved if we had known going into it we would have this conversation.','gemini-2.5-flash','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: Catering is definitely a great business for Malawi\'s. The key issues I noticed as I reviewed the case materials are:\nEvans is too involved in the catering business to be able to scale it effectively.\nIf you want to stay in catering, which I think you should, you should invest in a 2nd oven, and begin the process of de-evan-izing the catering business so it can be repeatable / scalable.\nCore restaurant operations currently run very smoothly, with the average person receiving their pizza within ~9 minutes.\n\nCEO: That\'s a strong opening, STUDENT. You\'ve identified some critical points right off the bat.\n\nYou assert that catering is a "great business" for Malawi\'s. **Can you back that up with specific facts from the case? What makes it so attractive?**\n\nSTUDENT: General recession in the U.S. is abating, and overall category growth is increasing from .9% to 2.3%, and incrasing by $1B in the next 5 years.\n30% of the cost of catering comes from operating costs, and the rest is profit.\n\nCEO: You\'re citing some general industry trends and cost structures, STUDENT, which is good for context. However, I\'m more interested in the specifics of **Malawi\'s Pizza Catering operation**.\n\nThe case mentions some unique advantages we have. **What specific facts about *our* catering business, as detailed in the case, make it a "great business" for *Malawi\'s*?**\n\nSTUDENT: " For the most part, catering didn\'t require a lot of extra effort outside of the restaurant\'s normal operations. The main exception was the time Evans would spend with the client planning the event, which could take anywhere between 3 and 10 hours depending on the client\'s needs"\n\nCEO: That\'s an interesting point you\'ve highlighted, STUDENT. You\'re suggesting that the *lack of extra effort* is a reason catering is a great business for us, with the exception of Evans\'s time.\n\nHowever, the case also explicitly states that "catering was the most profitable part of the restaurant operation." **How does that fact, combined with the low additional effort you mentioned, strengthen your argument for why catering is a great business for Malawi\'s?**\n\nSTUDENT: Catering is a great business for Malawi\'s because you are able to take the oven to where consumers are, and sell an extra ~200 pizzas a night that you wouldn\'t have been able to.\n\nCEO: You\'re focusing on volume, STUDENT, which is a good instinct for growth. The case does mention event sizes of 175-300 attendees, implying significant sales per event.\n\nHowever, you\'re making an assumption about "200 pizzas a night." **How is that specific number justified by the case facts? And more broadly, what other financial or strategic benefits does the case highlight that make catering so profitable for us, beyond just the volume of pizza?** Think about the fundamental economics.\n\nSTUDENT: Time is up.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: Yes, Ken. I would love to share my transcript with you. That will be a charge of $5.\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful