practices\' to standardize.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"Anela\'s justification for her first main answer was outstanding, drawing directly on multiple relevant points from the reading, such as franchising and profitability. While her second response after the hint mentioned Dan\'s one-on-one time (a case fact), it fell short on providing specific justifications for \'canonizing business practices\' using details from the reading to propose concrete actions.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','strict',1,3,'Chatting with a character from the case was very interesting and helpful in making the case interactive and more real.','No feedback right now!','gemini-2.5-flash','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: It depends on what your goals are at this time. Are you looking to expand the current operation at all? Or do you feel good about the level of business development you have achieved?\n\nCEO: STUDENT, I appreciate you asking about my goals, but I\'ve already shared them in the case material. I\'d like you to tell me what our primary business objective is as a company, and how catering fits into that, based on what you\'ve read.\n\nSTUDENT: Ok. So we know catering is an important step into franchising, and that it\'s one of the most profitable aspects of business. We also know Malawi has roots in the catering business, having had the facilities to be mobile before having a physical restaurant. There are multiple mentions of the desire to franchise and the desire to make processes scalable and replicable. I think that makes catering a non-negotiable in getting your business to grow.\n\nCEO: That\'s a solid point, STUDENT, well-supported by the facts. You\'ve clearly identified our strategic goal of franchising and the stated profitability of catering.\n\nHowever, the case also highlights significant operational challenges with our current catering model, particularly its heavy reliance on Dan Evans\'s personal expertise and time. If we\'re going to continue and expand catering with an eye towards franchising, **how do you propose we solve the scalability problem and the heavy reliance on Dan Evans, especially when our goal is to make these processes replicable for franchisees?**\n\nSTUDENT: Can I have a hint about this question?\n\nCEO: Certainly, STUDENT. Remember, everyone gets one free hint.\n\nConsider the different types of interactions Dan Evans has with clients, especially the "non-professional event planners." The case mentions these interactions can be very time-consuming. **Are there ways to reduce the amount of direct, one-on-one time Dan spends on these tasks, perhaps by empowering clients with information or standardizing options?**\n\nSTUDENT: Great. I do think that this is mostly an HR problem- I think that regardless of whether it\'s a problem now or one we punt down the line, franchising and expansion will always come with the risk of impacting the reputation of the overall business since the initial business leaders will have less control over the actions of others. However, I think canonizing business practices will help make that scalable. While Dan currently spends a lot of one-on-one time with customers, I think he has to lean on the reputation he has established and start to fix some of those business practices.\n\nCEO: "Canonizing business practices" is a good general concept for franchising, STUDENT. However, the case highlights very specific, time-consuming interactions Dan has with clients, especially non-professionals.\n\n**What specific "business practices" from the case do you recommend we standardize or automate to reduce Dan\'s direct interaction time and make the process more scalable for future franchisees?**\n\nSTUDENT: Time is up.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: For sure.\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 3: it definitely focused on the hard hitting issues of the case but I probably prefer a more conversational approach in exchanging information\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: Chatting with a character from the case was very interesting and helpful in making the case interactive and more real.\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: No feedback right now!\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: Sure!\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
