g to get a certain point from me, but didn\'t just keep asking','Being a little more specific with questions, IE like how many ideas you are looking for','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: I think we should stay in the catering business\n\nCEO: Interesting. I\'m not entirely convinced, STUDENT. The case mentions we only do about ten events a year, and it\'s incredibly dependent on Dan Evans\' personal time and expertise. That doesn\'t seem scalable, especially with our goal to franchise.\n\nWhat makes you so sure catering is worth continuing?\n\nSTUDENT: I think that we have a good synergy between our cocial events and catering opportunities. We know how important catering and the experience is and it is such a massive opportunity for us. Of course we will have to change some thigns\n\nCEO: "Synergy" is a good business concept, STUDENT, but "massive opportunity" is a strong claim. The case says we only do about ten events a year, which doesn\'t sound massive to me.\n\nWhat specific facts from the case led you to conclude that catering is such a significant opportunity for us?\n\nSTUDENT: This is more about the market size of the project. We only do 10 events a year but especially in Utah there are going to be so many more opportunities with marriages, work events and all of that. The case specifically mentions that we don\'t do any real advertising, so if we do 10 events with almost no advertising we could increase that with more\n\nCEO: That\'s a fair point, STUDENT. We don\'t do much advertising, so there\'s likely untapped demand.\n\nBut more events could just mean more headaches for Dan and more logistical nightmares like the ones mentioned in the case. What does the case say about the financial performance of catering that makes it so attractive? Is it actually worth the trouble?\n\nSTUDENT: The first thing it mentions is that catering doesn\'t requrie a lot of effort outside of the normal operations, so it doens\'t come with any lost revenue. It only takes a few hours and with the starting fee and then auto grateuity I think it is more than worth it. I think we may have to come up with a more standard menu as time moves on\n\nCEO: You\'re right to point out the pricing structure with the fee and the gratuity, STUDENT. That\'s a solid detail from the case.\n\nHowever, I\'m concerned about your comment that it "only takes a few hours." The case states that Dan Evans can spend between 3 and 10 hours just in the planning phase with a single client.\n\nIs the profit from one of these events really significant enough to justify that much of my General Manager\'s time?\n\nSTUDENT: Yes, I do believe that is a significant cost because it is a general manger that is doing it. I think having him train a specific employee that will head up catering will be a  much more effective way and allow the catering business to be scalable\n\nCEO: That\'s a good thought, STUDENT. But the case specifically says the process depends on Evans\'s "intuition, experience, and knowledge." That sounds like something you gain over a long career, not something you can just train into a junior employee in a few weeks.\n\nSo, beyond just assigning this to someone else, how would you propose we change the *process* itself so it doesn\'t require a Dan Evans clone at every franchise?\n\nSTUDENT: Great point. I do think expertise is neccessary. The first thing I want to do is make a more standard menu and process, right now Evans does everything on the fly. But, if we were to standardize the menu and process it would allow other people to run the events without needing evans at every one.\n\nCEO: Standardizing the menu is a good start, STUDENT. I\'ll give you that.\n\nBut the case says Evans spends a lot of his time acting as a free event planner for clients who don\'t know what they\'re doing. A standard menu doesn\'t fix that. How do we standardize the *client interaction* part of the process to solve that problem?\n\nSTUDENT: Yes, it does mention that. I think having an onboarding document or video that you provide could be helpful. If he was able to provide a potential client with a pamphlet showing what is actually in cluded in the catering and what isn\'t that would be extermely beneficial. We need to stick more with the food portion and not as much with the event planning.\n\nCEO: Okay, a pamphlet or a clear guide is a step in the right direction for setting expectations. I see the logic there.\n\nHowever, the case makes a clear distinction between professional event planners and non-professionals. The pros are quick and easy. The non-pros are the ones who take up all of Evans\'s time with planning questions.\n\nHow does a standard pamphlet effectively serve both of those groups? I\'m concerned we might lose the non-professional clients who seem to value that high-touch, personal guidance.\n\nSTUDENT: That is a great point. I think we need to focus more on the non-pros. A standard pamphlet could be provided to the pros that would allow them to know if they want to use our service quickly. For the non-pros I think we could have someone (not evans) talk through what we will provide and set those expectations. And then maybe have someone give a quick rundown the day before or of the event. The most important thing is right now catering is the most profitable part of the company, and so doing what we can to increase those sales is pivotal\n\nCEO: You\'ve hit on the key point, STUDENT. The case does state that catering is the "most profitable part of the restaurant operation." Good, you\'ve clearly read the case and you\'ve convinced me of its value.\n\nNow, let\'s talk about the real challenge: franchising. Your plan involves having "someone" trained to handle these clients. How do we create a system that a new franchisee in, say, Arizona can use to deliver the same high-quality catering experience without having their own Dan Evans on staff?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: sure\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 4\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: I loved how it was trying to get a certain point from me, but didn\'t just keep asking\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: Being a little more specific with questions, IE like how many ideas you are looking for\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: Yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
