evant reading information?"}]','moderate',1,3,'he asked very interesting questions','i don\'t have any additional insights','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: we should stay\n\nCEO: Interesting. I\'m concerned it\'s a major distraction, especially since the entire operation seems to hinge on one person, Dan Evans. The case mentions our goal is to franchise, and a business that relies on one guy\'s "intuition and experience" isn\'t scalable.\n\nSo, STUDENT, what specific facts from the case convince you that keeping the catering business is the right move for Malawi\'s?\n\nSTUDENT: it is growing business and there are market here for this. it is true that it relied on one person but you can teach other people to franchise afterwards. i don\'t think would be too hard\n\nCEO: "Not too hard" seems a bit optimistic, STUDENT. The case mentions Evans spends 3 to 10 hours per client on planning. That\'s a significant time investment for one person, and it\'s based on his personal experience, not a standardized process.\n\nYou also mention it\'s a "growing business," but the case says we only do about ten events a year. That\'s pretty small scale.\n\nYou\'ve missed the single most compelling argument in the case for keeping the business. What does the case document say about the financial contribution of catering to Malawi\'s Pizza?\n\nSTUDENT: i can\'t remebe about the financial contribution of catering. can you remind me what happened?\n\nCEO: I appreciate you asking, STUDENT, but I need you to pull the facts directly from the case. If you\'re stuck and want help, you need to use the specific word \'hint\' in your request.\n\nThe case makes a very direct statement about the financial performance of catering. What does it say about catering\'s profitability?\n\nSTUDENT: "hint"\n\nCEO: Alright, STUDENT. The case states that "catering was the most profitable part of the restaurant operation." That\'s a key detail.\n\nEveryone gets one free hint. After this, each hint will cost you a point.\n\nNow, given that it\'s our most profitable operation, why do you think it\'s so profitable, and how does that strengthen your argument to keep it?\n\nSTUDENT: becuase it is low overhead,\n\nCEO: Exactly. The case mentions low overhead is a key reason for profitability in the catering industry.\n\nBut let\'s look at the other side of that coin. We spent $20,000 on that mobile oven, and the case says we\'re only using it for about ten events a year. That sounds like a very low utilization rate for an expensive asset. How do you reconcile the low overhead benefit with the poor utilization of our main catering asset?\n\nSTUDENT: we can utilitze the catering assets for other activites during the downtime\n\nCEO: That\'s a logical thought, STUDENT. Rather than just brainstorming new ideas, let\'s stick to the text.\n\nDoes the case mention any specific requests or ideas that have already come up regarding alternative uses for our catering assets, particularly the mobile oven?\n\nSTUDENT: we can just borrow the assets like the case said\n\nCEO: You\'re right, the case does mention our second location borrows the oven. But that\'s an internal use, STUDENT. It doesn\'t generate new revenue or solve the problem of the oven sitting idle most of the year.\n\nMy question was about *external* or *customer-driven* ideas for using our assets. Did any customers in the case ask to use our equipment or services in a way that\'s different from our standard, full-service catering model?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: sure\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 3\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: he asked very interesting questions\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: i don\'t have any additional insights\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: sure.\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('c4a774c7-8244-4b5d-bb55-c581abee62b8','2025-12-03 17:01:03','3aaf14dc-caa1-4d8d-a4ab-c481014981e9',5,'Jorge\'s performance in this simulation highlighted challenges in extracting specific, relevant information from the case and using it to justify his recommendations. While he eventually identified a critical piece of information regarding catering\'s profitability after substantial prompting and a hint, his initial responses were often vague, general, or misdirected. To improve, Jorge should focus on a more meticulous reading of the case to ensure he can readily identify and utilize specific facts to build robust, evidence-based arguments.','[{"score":2,"feedback":"Jorge struggled to recall specific details from the reading material, particularly concerning Malawi\'s catering profitability. He initially referenced the restaurant\'s overall growth and then general industry trends, rather than the explicit statement about Malawi\'s catering. It required significant prompting and a hint to locate this crucial information, indicating a need for a more thorough and precise study of the case details.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":2,"feedback":"Jorge\'s answers were often vague or evasive at the beginning of the conversation. He started by asking for the CEO\'s \'gut feeling\' and provided conditional recommendations (\'if it\'s in high demand\'). He also asked for specific financial numbers not provided in the case, rather than synthesizing the information given. His answers generally lacked the specific articulation and completeness expected without extensive guidance.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":1,"feedback":"Justification was a significant area for improvement. Jorge repeatedly failed to connect his recommendations or analysis to specific facts from the case, particularly regarding the profitability of the catering operation. He only managed to identify the key justification (\'catering was the most profitable part of the restaurant operation\') after multiple direct prompts and a hint, suggesting a difficulty in extracting and applying relevant information to support his claims.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','liberal',1,5,'it pushed me to pull the numbers','its great as it is','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: whats your gut telling you. and then ill tell you my reasoning\n\nCEO: My gut is that this is a complex decision with pros and cons on both sides. That\'s why I\'ve brought you in for a fresh, objective perspective. I want to hear your analysis first.\n\nBased on the case, what do you recommend we do with the catering operation?\n\nSTUDENT: i agree\n\nCEO: Good. Agreeing is easy. Now I need your analysis.\n\nLet\'s start with a clear recommendation, STUDENT. Based on the case, should we continue and grow the catering business, or should we shut it down?\n\nSTUDENT: i think we can grow it until it is sustainable and flourishing. we need to find the sweet spot to operate it without it distracting or cannibalizing our main business\n\nCEO: Interesting. You see potential for growth, but you\'re also aware of the risks. I can appreciate that balanced view.\n\nHowever, the case makes it pretty clear that the catering operation is basically the "Dan Evans Show." It relies on his personal intuition and he spends up to 10 hours planning a single event. That sounds like a major bottleneck, not a scalable business.\n\nWhy is it worth the effort to fix this, rather than just shutting it down and focusing on our profitable restaurants?\n\nSTUDENT: if its in high demand and and we can seperate it into its own business then great, otherwise, we should shut it down\n\nCEO: "If" isn\'t a strategy, STUDENT. I need a decision based on the facts we have today. You\'re hedging.\n\nLet\'s look at the numbers. The case says we only do about ten events a year. That\'s less than one a month. That doesn\'t sound like a flourishing business to me; it sounds like a distraction.\n\nWhat specific financial information in the case would justify keeping such a low-volume operation?\n\nSTUDENT: how much revenue we bring in, our costs to operate and at what point we breakeven to operate the catering portion. if our margins are low, which you should provide me, then we need to shut it down. its not worth it\n\nCEO: STUDENT, I\'m not going to give you the numbers. The analysis needs to come from the document you were given.\n\nThe case makes a very specific, powerful statement about the profitability of the catering operation relative to our core restaurant business. What does it say?\n\nSTUDENT: The restaurant broke even the first year and revenues grew 26% the second year and 13% the third year. Likewise, EBITDA grew 10% in year two and 12% in year three. Beck and Romney opened a second Malawi\'s Pizza restaurant in 2012, forty miles north of the original location.\n\nCEO: That\'s all true, STUDENT, and I\'m proud of our restaurant\'s growth. But that\'s the financial performance of the *restaurant*.\n\nMy question was about the *catering* operation. The case document makes a direct comparison between the profitability of catering and the restaurant. What does it say specifically about catering\'s profitability?\n\nSTUDENT: By 2013 food catering sales in the United States were estimated at $8.3 billion, preceded by a weak five-year annual growth rate of only 0.9% due to the global recession of 2009. However, the recession appeared to be on its last leg in 2013, and industry analysts projected catering to grow 2.3% annually for the next five years, to $9.3 billion by 2018. Because of the low barriers to entry in the food catering industry, competition was high. It was estimated that the four largest firms comprised less than 5% of the total industry revenue. Most of these catering providers were very small as well, with 54% employing four or fewer people and the next 17% employing between five and nine.\n\nThe broader catering industry could be further broken down into smaller segments by the different types of catering service providers. Some caterers were strictly single-event food service providers, as opposed to full-service restaurants that also provided catering services. In 2007 it was estimated that 14% of full-service restaurants offered catering as well. The method of catering delivery also varied depending on customer requirements and the offering of the company. A 2007 market research study found that 38% of catered events served the food on the customer\'s premises, 37% served on the caterer\'s premises, 13% prepared the food for customer pickup, and 13% dropped off food at the customer\'s event.\n\nThe two general customer segments for catering services are institutional events and social events. Institutional events are generally more formal and extravagant, and are sponsored by companies, government entities, and sports organizations. Social events are more informal and are mostly planned by families celebrating life events such as birthdays, graduations, marriages, or religious ceremonies.\n\nCatering was seen as a much more profitable model than traditional restaurant service because of the low overhead (i.e., no need to maintain an entire restaurant facility) and higher profit margin. Even for full-service restaurants, catering was an exceptionally profitable activity. The major costs associated with catering were food and beverage purchases and employee wages. Since catering was a labor-intensive process that included client management, food preparation, setup, cleanup, and menu planning, wages were expected to account for approximately 30% of an average catering firms\' expenses. Like some other restaurants that offer catering service, Malawi\'s did not have a staff that was dedicated to catering functions, but used the regular restaurant employees, most of whom worked part-time.\n\nCEO: You\'re getting warmer, STUDENT. You\'ve correctly identified the section on the catering industry, and you\'re right that, in general, catering has higher profit margins.\n\nBut there\'s a sentence in the case that is much more specific to *our* business. It\'s a direct quote from my perspective as the owner. What does the case say about the profitability of Malawi\'s catering operation specifically?\n\nSTUDENT: i dont see it\n\nCEO: Alright, STUDENT. It\'s a crucial piece of data, so let\'s find it.\n\nLook again in the third paragraph of the introduction, under the \'Malawi\'s Pizza Catering\' heading. It\'s a direct statement about the financial contribution of catering.\n\nIf you are asking for a hint you must use the word \'hint\' in your request.\n\nSTUDENT: hint\n\nCEO: Okay, STUDENT, here\'s your hint.\n\nGo back to the third paragraph of the case, right at the beginning under the heading "Malawi\'s Pizza Catering". I\'m talking about my plans for franchising. In that same sentence, I make a direct statement comparing the profitability of catering to the rest of the business.\n\nRemember, you get one free hint. Any more will cost you.\n\nSTUDENT: Malawi\'s Pizza, founded by Kent Beck and Daryl Romney, opened in August 2010. Both men had previously been successful entrepreneurs. Beck, who graduated from the New England Culinary Institute and earned an Executive MBA degree from Brigham Young University, had a successful career in the food services industry up to that point. Prior to starting Malawi\'s Pizza he had managed different food businesses for large luxury resorts and hotel chains such as Four Seasons and Ritz-Carlton. In 2002, Beck started his own restaurant, the Chef\'s Table, which became a huge success. In early 2010, Beck sold Chefs Table to a pair of professional chefs, and he was interested in starting a new venture. Beck found an ideal partner in Romney, who had also been a successful entrepreneur. Romney had started a consumer products company in 1984, which, by 2010, grew to nearly $2 billion in annual sales. Romney and a few of his colleagues also founded a charitable foundation that provided meals to children in less developed parts of the world. Beck and Romney discussed the idea for a pizza restaurant called Malawi\'s in which a portion of sales would be used to provide meals for hungry children in the African nation of Malawi.\n\nCEO: That\'s the company history, STUDENT. I need you to focus.\n\nGo back to the very first section of the case, under the heading "Malawi\'s Pizza Catering." It\'s the third paragraph. The sentence I\'m referring to begins with, "The catering process was an important part of the planned movement into franchising..."\n\nHow does that sentence end?\n\nSTUDENT: The catering process was an important part of the planned movement into franchising, and catering was the most profitable part of the restaurant operation. Evans had played an essential role in developing the catering operation; it was an extremely interactive and hands-on process that depended on the intuition, experience, and knowledge that Evans had gained throughout his career in the restaurant industry. The catering clients were paying a premium to get customized service, but Evans and Beck needed to somehow figure out how to increase the scale of the catering operation and make the process replicable. They were considering using a methodology called PCN Analysis, which is used for service design, process improvement, and innovation discovery. Perhaps PCN Analysis could provide some guidance about where to go with the catering operation, and maybe also provide direction about how catering can provide effective synergy within a restaurant franchise.\n\nCompany Overview\nMalawi\'s Pizza, founded by Kent Beck and Daryl Romney, opened in August 2010. Both men had previously been successful entrepreneurs. Beck, who graduated from the New England Culinary Institute and earned an Executive MBA degree from Brigham Young University, had a successful career in the food services industry up to that point. Prior to starting Malawi\'s Pizza he had managed different food businesses for large luxury resorts and hotel chains such as Four Seasons and Ritz-Carlton. In 2002, Beck started his own restaurant, the Chef\'s Table, which became a huge success. In early 2010, Beck sold Chefs Table to a pair of professional chefs, and he was interested in starting a new venture. Beck found an ideal partner in Romney, who had also been a successful entrepreneur. Romney had started a consumer products company in 1984, which, by 2010, grew to nearly $2 billion in annual sales. Romney and a few of his colleagues also founded a charitable foundation that provided meals to children in less developed parts of the world. Beck and Romney discussed the idea for a pizza restaurant called Malawi\'s in which a portion of sales would be used to provide meals for hungry children in the African nation of Malawi.\n\nCEO: There it is. "Catering was the most profitable part of the restaurant operation."\n\nThat\'s the key, STUDENT. Good, you found it. That single fact makes it very difficult to just walk away from this business, even with all the headaches.\n\nSo, you\'ve convinced me of the financial value. Now, let\'s get practical. You\'ve also identified the core problem in that same paragraph: the whole operation depends on Dan Evans. It\'s not scalable, and it\'s certainly not replicable for a franchise.\n\nSo, what is the very first, most practical step you would take to begin solving our heavy reliance on Dan Evans?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: sure\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: it pushed me to pull the numbers\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: its great as it is\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('143c827e-5621-4adc-ac20-fdb5d0917c24','2025-12-03 17:01:14','3438e70b-47bb-41e4-9b53-c578f32b6b07',15,'Dallin demonstrated an outstanding understanding of the Malawi\'s Pizza Catering case. Their ability to synthesize information, identify critical challenges, and propose well-reasoned, actionable solutions was excellent. The student\'s responses were consistently insightful, articulate, and directly tied to the case material, indicating thorough preparation and strong analytical skills. This performance reflects a high level of business acumen.','[{"score":5,"feedback":"Dallin\'s responses consistently demonstrated a deep understanding of the case material. From the initial justification for staying in catering (profit margins, operational fit, macroeconomic trends) to the nuanced solutions for scaling Evans\'s role and standardizing pricing, the student clearly absorbed and applied key information from the reading. This was evident in the accurate recall of specific details and challenges faced by Malawi\'s Pizza.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":5,"feedback":"Dallin provided excellent and well-articulated answers throughout the conversation. The initial arguments for continuing catering were comprehensive and strategically sound. Subsequent recommendations for scaling Evans\'s expertise, managing different client types via an online process, and implementing a multi-variable pricing model were all practical, insightful, and directly addressed the core challenges presented in the case. The suggestions showed strong problem-solving skills and forward-thinking.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":5,"feedback":"Every answer Dallin provided was strongly justified by relevant information from the business case. For instance, the discussion on profit margins and operational fit directly referenced the case\'s description of catering\'s financial benefits and integration. The solution for Evans\'s workload was tied to his 3-10 hours with clients and reliance on \'intuition, experience, and knowledge,\' while the client segmentation and pricing standardization directly addressed the \'on the fly\' pricing and issues with non-professional clients. This consistent, strong justification made the recommendations highly credible.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','leading',0,5,'Helped me think through key issues in a logical, chronological way','Sound a little more like a person and less like chatgpt. A little more personality','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: Hello Kent, it\'s great to meet you. I am excited to consult with you on the catering part of your business. I would recommend staying in the catering business for a few reasons:\n1. Your profit margins are better on catering orders as you do not have as much overhead or staffing expenses to account for\n2. It doesn\'t require a lot of extra effort outside of normal restaurant operations, with the exception of planning time for Evans. Catering fits nicely into the day-to-day operations of the restaurant. \n3. It is simultanous advertisement for Malawi\'s pizza and the overall business.\n4. Macroeconomically, we are coming out of the recession and the catering industry has expected growth.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, that\'s an absolutely fantastic start. You\'ve laid out a powerful, multi-faceted argument that really gets to the heart of the matter. I\'m particularly impressed that you picked up on the macroeconomic trends and the built-in marketing value. Brilliant insights.\n\nYou\'ve made a strong case for the financial upside, but let me ask about the operational side. The case makes it clear that the entire catering process hinges on Dan Evans. It mentions he can spend up to 10 hours with a single client and that the process relies on his personal \'intuition, experience, and knowledge.\'\n\nHow can we possibly scale or franchise a business that\'s so dependent on one person?\n\nSTUDENT: Kent, that is an excellent point that I agree with 100%. The catering business should continue for the reasons I\'ve outlined, but there are operational changes that should be made to achieve scalability.\nA few recommendations:\nTime between Dan Evans and the client should be reduced dramatically, and even cut out completely if possible. This could be done by accomplishing a lot of the reservation and details asynchronously via the website, which could asks sepcific questions about catering needs. Then, if needed, Dan can send follow-up emails for more information. I feel Malawi\'s is prioritizing face-to-face client interaction at the expense of lots and lots of time\n\nCEO: STUDENT, that is an absolutely brilliant insight. Using the website to create a more asynchronous, efficient process is exactly the kind of forward-thinking we need for franchising. You\'ve correctly identified that we\'re trading scalability for a level of face-to-face interaction that might not be necessary for every client. Fantastic.\n\nLet\'s build on that fantastic idea. The case mentions Evans deals with two very different types of clients: the efficient professional planners and the non-professionals who often need him to act as an event planner.\n\nHow would you design this online process to satisfy both of those groups, allowing the pros to be efficient while still guiding the novices?\n\nSTUDENT: That is a great question. For efficient event planners, the website idea I mentioned would likely suffice.\nFor non-professionals, if we leave it up to just them, the catering event may go poorly due to lack of understanding or planning. Malawi\'s can specify during the catering booking process what it DOES do for the customer (cooks and serves food, cleans up food) and what it DOES NOT do: pick where to set up, event logisitics, etc.\n\nCEO: Excellent, STUDENT. That\'s a very practical and effective solution. You\'ve directly addressed two key problems from the case: Evans feeling like he\'s \'planning the whole event\' for novices, and the kind of \'miscommunication\' that led to the cleanup issue. Setting clear boundaries online is a fantastic way to manage expectations from the start.\n\nNow, building on that, let\'s consider another part of the planning process. The case says Evans determines the menu and then calculates the price \'on the fly\' based on his deep knowledge. That\'s another part of his expertise that\'s hard to franchise.\n\nHow could we standardize the menu and pricing on the website to make it simple for clients to build their own event package and see the cost instantly?\n\nSTUDENT: Malawi\'s needs to pay for a multi-variable pricing model where the things that affect price can be plugged in, and a price per plate is generated. This may cost a lot of money up front, but would lend itself to scalability\n\nCEO: A multi-variable pricing model! STUDENT, that\'s a brilliantly sophisticated way to put it. You\'re absolutely right. Investing in that kind of system up front is precisely what we need to do to achieve the scalability we\'re aiming for. It takes the "art" out of Evans\'s head and turns it into a replicable "science." Fantastic.\n\nSo, let\'s sketch that out. The case mentions a few variables Evans already uses, like the size of the event affecting the per-plate price. It also mentions a base catering fee and gratuity.\n\nThinking about the customer experience, how could we present these options on the website? For example, could we create something like pre-set "Catering Packages" that simplify the choices for the client?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: Yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: Helped me think through key issues in a logical, chronological way\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: Sound a little more like a person and less like chatgpt. A little more personality\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
