dently. Even with this level of automation, however, catering clients are paying a premium for a certain level of "hand-holding". Back to the previous point, having a dedicated catering lead at each location will make this more scalable.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, that is absolutely brilliant! An automated, robust intake form is exactly the kind of thinking we need for a franchise model. It standardizes the process, clarifies expectations about things like the mobile oven, and saves an immense amount of time. You\'ve turned a major bottleneck into a streamlined, replicable system. Fantastic!\n\nThis system seems perfect for the professional planners mentioned in the case who just want to get things done efficiently.\n\nNow, thinking about those non-professional clients, the ones who Evans felt he was acting as an event planner for. How could we use this new, more standardized approach to perhaps offer different *levels* of service? For example, could we create pre-set "Catering Packages" to make the decision-making process even simpler for them? Your insights here would be incredibly valuable.\n\nSTUDENT: The great thing about an automized online process is that we can build out whatever we want and roll it out to all locations. The catering levels should show different service levels and price points; that way our catering lead can prioritize their time efficiently by dedicated more to the more premium clients.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, that\'s another fantastic insight. You\'re not just solving the problem, you\'re creating new business opportunities by thinking strategically about client segmentation. That\'s exactly the kind of forward-thinking we need.\n\nThis brings to mind a specific incident from the case. Remember the potential client, Jane Goodman? She wanted to buy par-cooked pizzas for 120 people to self-cater her event, but we had to turn her away because it wasn\'t something we did.\n\nHow could we use your idea of different service levels to create a new offering that would have captured Jane Goodman\'s business and met her specific needs?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: safe place to try out ideas and get feedback\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: it could be nice to have a way to search for keywords or sift through case details quickly\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('a70c7693-6903-4bbc-b7a5-5b7f96edc4f7','2025-12-03 17:01:47','1a994df0-1c90-4bb0-a41e-b69dbbf86344',14,'Braeden demonstrated a strong grasp of the Malawi\'s Pizza catering case, consistently referencing key details and challenges. Their initial defense of the catering business was well-supported, and they offered a logical progression of solutions for scalability, from training and apprenticeships to the insightful suggestion of redefining the scope of catering services. Braeden\'s ability to engage with the CEO\'s probing questions and offer justified, relevant responses highlighted a thoughtful approach to problem-solving, although the final question was not addressed due to time.','[{"score":5,"feedback":"Braeden demonstrated a strong understanding of the business case, directly referencing its content and identifying key challenges and opportunities such as the advertising value of catering and the bottleneck created by Dan Evans\'s integral role. Their answers consistently reflected an engagement with the core issues presented in the material.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"Braeden provided thoughtful and progressively deeper answers, moving from general solutions like training to more nuanced ones like apprenticeships and eventually questioning the scope of service. The \'Hamburger University\' analogy was a particularly strong point in addressing scalability. While the final question was not answered due to time, the preceding responses were well-articulated.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":5,"feedback":"Braeden consistently justified their answers by drawing on relevant information from the reading material, whether through direct quotes or by addressing the specific challenges and details presented in the case regarding Evans\'s role and the need for a franchisable system. This showed a strong ability to connect proposed solutions to the case\'s context.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','liberal',0,5,'How real it felt and the great probing questions','Voice to chat','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: I would continue with the catering. It "fit nicely into the day-to-day operations of the restaurant. For the most part, catering didn\'t require a lot of extra effort outside of the restaurant\'s normal operations." It also serves as a nice form of advertising that also generates revenue, that is a hard thing to come by in any industry. Stopping the catering might have larger negative effects on the core restaurant business as less people are exposed to the great Malawi Pizza at events.\n\nCEO: That\'s an interesting take, STUDENT, and I agree the marketing exposure is valuable.\n\nHowever, the case also mentions that planning an event can take Dan Evans anywhere from 3 to 10 hours of his time, and that the whole process relies on his personal "intuition, experience, and knowledge."\n\nHow do you reconcile the idea that it "fits nicely" with the reality that it\'s creating such a significant bottleneck for my general manager?\n\nSTUDENT: Part of being a general manager is developing and training employees and future leaders. With some time dedicated to standardizing his methods and sharing them with another team member, Dan can begin to lessen this workload and pass the torch onto someone else so he can focus on other more pressing business items.\n\nCEO: I hear you on training, STUDENT. That\'s a classic approach to scaling.\n\nBut the case makes a point of saying the process depends on Evans\'s "intuition, experience, and knowledge." That sounds like something that\'s very difficult to bottle up into a training manual.\n\nHow do you propose we standardize something as personal as intuition without losing the high-touch, customized service our clients are paying for?\n\nSTUDENT: Apprenticeships have existed for centuries for that exact reason. Intuition, experience and knowledge come from really doing the work aloside an experienced artisan. By bringing someone under his wing in a high touch and highly interactive manner, that intuition, knowledge and experience can be crafted in someone else. And honestly its  not rocket science, Evan is not the only person who can cater and plan a pizza oven at an event, there are plenty of people capable and willing to learn that skill.\n\nCEO: That\'s a fair point, STUDENT. An apprenticeship is a classic way to transfer skilled craft.\n\nBut apprenticeships take time, and they are a one-to-one training model. Our primary goal here is to create a *franchisable* system.\n\nHow does a slow, one-on-one apprenticeship model for catering management translate into a process we can hand over to a new franchisee in, say, Arizona, who has never met Dan Evans?\n\nSTUDENT: A weeklong training at an established location could serve as a great way to rapidly transfer those skills to a new franchisee. McDonalds has a Hamburger University for this purpose. It is a training methos where managers are sent to run and organize a franchise and are taught how to deal with the various challenges they might face. Malawi\'s could do this too.\n\nCEO: A "Hamburger University" for Malawi\'s is an interesting concept, STUDENT. I like that you\'re thinking about replicable systems.\n\nBut let\'s look at what we\'d actually be training them to do. The case says Evans spends up to 10 hours with a single non-professional client, essentially acting as their event planner and answering questions about venues and weather.\n\nAre we just training new franchisees to also spend 10 hours hand-holding each client? How does that scale, even with a training program?\n\nSTUDENT: Maybe, but we might also need to look at whether or not its our job to be event planners. We would take a bit of a less active role and instead simple deliver pizza and a fun atmosphere around food, instead of actually planning entire events for people.\n\nCEO: That\'s a sharp observation, STUDENT. You\'re questioning the very scope of our service.\n\nBut let\'s consider the trade-off. The case explicitly states that Evans provides this "highest degree of attention and customization" because our clients are paying a "premium price."\n\nIf we stop acting as event planners and just deliver pizza, what do you think happens to our ability to command that premium price and maintain our high profit margins?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: How real it felt and the great probing questions\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: Voice to chat\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('3ddc2889-468d-4d69-aece-a77c81a7465f','2025-12-03 17:01:49','d4b886d9-aa2e-442f-b2f1-861332eddf71',15,'JD Davenport delivered an outstanding performance, showcasing a profound understanding of the business case and applying sophisticated operations strategy to address complex challenges. He moved adeptly from strategic analysis to detailed, actionable solutions, including a multi-tiered catering system, a comprehensive redesign of planning and on-site logistics, and an innovative, brand-safe self-catering kit. His ability to anticipate and resolve potential objections, culminating in a clear implementation plan, was particularly impressive. JD\'s structured, analytical approach and creative problem-solving reflect a strong grasp of the material and excellent business acumen.','[{"score":5,"feedback":"JD demonstrated an outstanding command of the reading material, consistently referencing specific details, problems, and characters from the Malawi\'s Pizza Catering Case. His responses were deeply rooted in the case facts, showing he thoroughly internalized the content.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":5,"feedback":"JD\'s answers were exceptionally solid, well-articulated, and comprehensive. He provided structured, operations-driven analyses and solutions for every challenge, moving from high-level strategic recommendations to granular, actionable process designs. His responses were consistently precise and complete.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":5,"feedback":"JD excelled at justifying his answers by explicitly linking them back to relevant information from the case. He effectively used examples like Dan Evans\'s planning time, on-site logistical challenges, and the Jane Goodman scenario to build a compelling rationale for his proposed solutions.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','strict',0,5,'I got to test my own agent tree idea lol','I think that the purpose was not clear','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: Kent, thank you for the direct question. Ill give you a structured, operations-driven answerprecise, analytical, and focused on your strategic choice.\n\nShould Malawis Stay in the Catering Business?\n\nMr. Beck, the decision hinges on whether catering is a strategic complement to your fast-casual restaurant model or a distracting side business that consumes scarce managerial capacity. Lets evaluate this rigorously against the core dimensions of operations strategy.\n\n1. Profitability & Strategic Fit\nCatering is your highest-margin offering.\n\nThe case is explicit: catering is the most profitable part of Malawis operations and was envisioned as an essential part of the future franchise model.\n\n\nMargins are high because:\n\nYou avoid full restaurant overhead.\n\nFood costs are predictable and tightly controlled.\n\nLabor, though intensive, is flexible.\n\nThe mobile oven creates differentiation and pricing power.\n\nFrom a strategic fit perspective, catering reinforces the Malawis brand:\n\nIt showcases your high-quality, fast-cooked product.\n\nIt amplifies your Meal for Malawi social mission in community settings.\n\nIt expands awareness in a cost-effective waymost catering demand is word of mouth.\n\n\nConclusion: Catering is not merely profitable; it is strategically synergistic with the brand.\n\n2. Operational Capabilities\nYour current catering model is operationally excellent but not scalable.\n\nThe case makes this exceptionally clear:\n\nThe process depends heavily on the intuition and tacit knowledge of Dan Evans.\n\nPlanning meetings take 310 hours for non-professional clients.\n\nAll customer interaction runs through him.\n\nMost execution judgment on-sitethroughput, product mix, pacing, qualityrelies on his expertise.\n\n\nThis is the core problem.\nThe issue is not whether catering fits the businessit does.\nThe issue is whether the catering process is sufficiently standardized to be:\n\nscaled across multiple events,\n\nexecuted by staff other than Evans,\n\nreplicated in future franchise units.\n\nAt present, the answer to all three is no.\n\n3. Opportunity Cost of Management Attention\n\nCatering requires:\n\nDetailed planning with inexperienced clients\n\nOn-site supervision\n\nAdditional scheduling, procurement, and quality oversight\n\nMeanwhile, the restaurant operation is growing and demanding more of Evans time.\n\n\nThus, the real tradeoff is not catering vs. restaurant operations, but:\n\nHigh-margin growth vs. managerial bandwidth.\n\nCatering is not distracting Malawis from its core business\nlack of process standardization is.\n\n4. Customer Value and Brand Reinforcement\n\nCatering has unusually high customer engagement:\n\nGuests interact with the oven and cooking process.\n\nThe mobile oven is perceived as entertainment, not just food production.\n\nMany future catering clients originate from these events.\n\n\nThis is word-of-mouth marketing you cannot buy.\n\nAbandoning catering would reduce brand reach and weaken franchisee economics.\n\n5. The Franchising Lens\n\nFranchise success depends on:\n\nrepeatable processes,\n\nclear documentation,\n\nlow reliance on individual heroics.\n\nThe case states clearly that you and Dan wanted catering to be a replicable and scalable component of the franchise system.\n\n\nRight now, catering fails that testbut the failure is solvable.\n\nPCN Analysis is well-suited to:\n\nidentify which activities must remain high-contact,\n\nshift work out of Dans domain,\n\nmodularize the offering (e.g., full-service vs. drop-off vs. par-cooked for self-catering),\n\ncreate a franchise-friendly blueprint.\n\nRecommendation: Stay in the Catering Business  But Redesign the Process\n\nBased on the economics, strategic complementarity, and brand impact, you should absolutely remain in the catering business.\n\nHowever, you should redesign the catering operation to reduce dependence on Evans and make it scalable and franchisable. That means:\n\n1. Standardize the planning process\n\nCreate templated menus, pricing tiers, planning scripts.\n\nReduce Evans role to exceptions, not routine.\n\n2. Modularize the service offering\n\nIntroduce three models:\n\nFull-service catering (high margin, high staff involvement)\n\nDrop-off catering (moderate margin, scalable)\n\nPar-cooked self-catering kits + optional oven rental\n This solves the Jane Goodman problem and captures demand you currently turn away.\n Quality concerns can be mitigated with instructions, temperature guidelines, and optional staff add-ons.\n\n3. Train a Catering Lead role\n\nReplicable across franchise units.\n\n4. Document a full PCN blueprint\n\nProvide franchisees with clarity on:\n\ncustomer-facing activities,\n\nsurrogate interactions,\n\nindependent restaurant-side processes.\n\nThis shifts catering from an artisanal service to a teachable operating system.\nCatering should remain a core part of Malawis business because it strengthens the brand, generates the highest margins, and offers strategic differentiation. It is not a distractionits current lack of standardization is. The path forward is to redesign the catering process so it can scale without relying on Dan Evans, enabling Malawis to grow profitably and franchise successfully.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, that\'s a very thorough analysis. You\'ve correctly identified that catering is our most profitable segment.\n\nBut you also point out that the entire operation hinges on Dan Evans. The case mentions it can take him up to 10 hours just to plan one event with a non-professional client. My goal is to create a franchise model that any competent operator can replicate, and Dan\'s \'intuition and experience\' isn\'t something I can put in a franchise manual.\n\nGiven that massive operational dependency on one person, isn\'t catering an unacceptable risk to our franchise model? Why not just drop it and focus on perfecting the core, scalable restaurant business?\n\nSTUDENT: Catering is, without question, the most profitable part of our current business.\nIt enhances the brand, creates tremendous word-of-mouth visibility, and showcases the Malawis experience in a way the four walls of the restaurant never can. The mobile oven is a differentiator. People remember it. Many of our catering customers first encountered us at someone elses eventthere is real strategic value in that.\n\nBut here is my concern:\nRight now, the catering process is essentially the Dan Evans Show. His intuition, his judgment, his ability to read a clientnone of that is documented, systematized, or easily teachable. When a non-professional client comes in, Dan can spend up to ten hours planning a single event. Ten hours. That is simply not a franchisable model.\n\nIf the success of a catering event depends on a uniquely talented individual with years of industry experience, then I cant responsibly hand that process to franchisees and pretend it will work the same way.\n\nFrom a franchise perspective, that is a red flag.\nFranchise systems are built on repeatability. Predictability. Process discipline. And right now our catering business is held together by tacit knowledgenot a scalable operating system.\n\nSo the dilemma Im wrestling with is this:\n\nIs catering such a dependency risk that we should remove it from the franchise model?\nOr are we walking away from a powerful profit engine simply because we havent done the work to standardize it?\n\nOn the one hand, I want franchisees to operate a clean, simple, repeatable business. On the other hand, Im uneasy about abandoning our most profitable product lineand one of the strongest tools we have for building brand love.\n\nIf catering is truly incompatible with a scalable, teachable franchise system, then we should consider dropping it.\nBut if the real problem is that our current catering process has not yet been engineered for replication, then thats a very different conversation. In that case, the solution isnt to walk away from cateringits to redesign it.\n\nRight now, I need clarity:\nIs catering fundamentally unscalable, or is it merely unscalable the way we currently run it?\nThat distinction determines whether this offering becomes a franchise asset or a franchise liability.\n\nCEO: You\'ve framed the dilemma perfectly, STUDENT. But I\'m not paying you to restate my problems. I\'m paying you for solutions.\n\nYou say the answer is to \'redesign\' the process. That\'s a nice concept, but what does it actually mean? Let\'s focus on a real problem from the case: the 3 to 10 hours Dan spends planning with non-professional clients. That\'s pure, unscalable \'Dan Evans Show\'.\n\nSo, tell me, how exactly would you redesign that specific part of the process so a new franchisee can execute it without Dan\'s \'intuition\'?\n\nSTUDENT: Absolutely, Kent. Lets get concrete.\nYoure asking for operational redesign, not academic platitudesspecifically:\n\nHow do we turn Dans 310 hours of bespoke, intuition-driven planning into a process that any competent franchisee can execute consistently and quickly?\n\nHere is the exact redesign, broken into precise, franchisable components.\n\n**REDESIGNING THE CLIENT-PLANNING PROCESS\n\n(So it no longer depends on Dan Evans intuition)**\n\n1. Replace bespoke planning with a Catering Package Architecture\n\nRight now Dan builds every event from scratch. That is the problem.\n\nInstead: create 3 standardized event packages.\nPackage A  Standard Buffet (Most common wedding receptions)\n\nFixed menu of 4 pizza types + 1 dessert pizza + 1 salad.\n\nFixed staffing: 3 workers + oven operator.\n\nFixed pricing tier.\n\nFixed service boundaries (no clearing tables unless add-on purchased).\n\nCapacity guidelines: 150350 guests.\n\nPackage B  Institutional / Corporate Buffet\n\nSimplified menu: 3 pizzas + 1 salad.\n\nLower labor requirements, reduced cost.\n\nNo dcor, minimal interaction.\n\nOptional add-ons for serving or table clearing.\n\nPackage C  Drop-Off (No oven)\n\nPar-cooked pizzas in warmers; no live cooking.\n\nDesigned for budget-sensitive or short-notice events.\n\nCan be executed by entry-level franchise staff.\n\nThis eliminates 7080% of the decisions Dan currently makes manually.\nClients pick the package, not design their own event.\n\n2. Replace custom food-quantity calculations with a franchised Event Sizing Algorithm\n\nRight now Dan calculates slices per person based on feel. A franchise-friendly system needs deterministic rules.\n\nWe implement a simple, fixed estimator embedded into the ordering sheet:\n\nAdults  3 slices\n\nTeens  4 slices\n\nChildren  1.5 slices\n\nSalads  1 platter per 20 guests\n\nDessert pizzas  1 per 15 guests\n\nThe franchisee simply inputs headcount  the system outputs:\n\nNumber of pizzas per type\n\nStaffing requirement\n\nPrep schedule\n\nOven throughput schedule\n\nThis replaces Dans tacit demand-forecasting judgment with a repeatable algorithm.\n\n3. Pre-built menu templates eliminate client choice ambiguity\n\nIn the case, non-professional clients constantly ask:\nWhat do other people pick?\nHow many types do we need?\nWhat works well for weddings?\n\n\nThis is because the menu is open-ended.\n\nRedesign: Provide templates, not options.\n\nEach package comes with:\n\nA preset pizza lineup\n\nClear descriptions (best for kids, balanced vegetarian option, etc.)\n\nUpgrades (premium pizza choices)\n\nNo substitutions or 1 substitution allowed\n\nClients choose from curated templates, not a blank canvas.\nThis removes 90% of the dialogue that forces Dan to be a consultant instead of a caterer.\n\n4. Introduce a Catering Decision Guide  a structured conversation tool\n\nInstead of a free-flowing 2-hour conversation based on Dans intuition, the franchisee follows a scripted sequence with checkboxes.\n\nDecision Guide Sections:\n\nEvent Type: Wedding / Corporate / Church / Other\n\nExpected Guest Profile: Adults / Teens / Kids\n\nVenue Type: Indoor / Outdoor / Oven-access constraints\n\nClient Service Expectations:\n\nDo you expect Malawis to clear tables?\n\nWill you provide signage, or should we?\n\nWho is responsible for event flow (you, planner, venue)?\n\nPackage Selection\n\nAdd-ons (table clearing, signage, dessert station, water/lemonade, etc.)\n\nFinal Quote Summary\n\nThe script eliminates:\n\nmiscommunication about service boundaries,\n\nambiguous expectations (like the bride who assumed Malawis would clean all dishes), and\n\nplanning drift that forces Dan to become the event planner.\n\n\nA scripted conversation is teachable.\nDans intuition is not.\n\n5. Introduce an online pre-meeting intake form\n\nBefore any meeting happens, clients must complete a 5-minute form:\n\nEvent date / location\n\nEstimated headcount\n\nEvent type\n\nBudget range\n\nPreferred package\n\nSpecial constraints\n\nThis accomplishes two things:\n\nFranchisees start 6070% of the way to a solution before ever speaking with the client.\n\nClient expectations become anchored in structured options, not creative brainstorming.\n\n6. Offer a "Professional Planner Shortcut"\n\nProfessional planners already know what they want.\nRight now Dan spends 30 minutes; franchisees should spend 10.\n\nCreate a 1-page planner form they fill out and send backno meeting needed.\n\n7. Limit planning meetings to 30 minutes with a strict structure\n\nRight now Dan feels obligated to educate inexperienced clients on the catering world. That is what burns 310 hours.\n\nImprove service design:\n\nPlanning meetings must follow the script.\n\nFranchisees do not deviate into event-planning consulting.\n\nClients who want more customization are routed into paid add-ons.\n\nWe are not building events; we are selling packages.\n\n8. Provide a digital quoting tool that calculates price automatically\n\nDan currently prices events manually based on his experience.\nFranchisees should not improvise.\n\nTool Inputs:\n\nPackage\n\nGuest count\n\nAdd-ons\n\nTravel distance\n\nDay of week\n\nTool Outputs:\n\nExact price\n\nFood quantity\n\nLabor requirement\n\nMargin estimate\n\nNo negotiation. No improvisation.\nJust a clean, consistent franchise-ready quote.\n\nWhat This Redesign Achieves\nBefore (Dan system):\n\n310 hours per non-professional client\n\nHigh cognitive load\n\nHigh variability\n\nDependent on intuition\n\nUnscalable\n\nAfter (franchise-ready system):\n\n30-minute max planning\n\nStandardized packages\n\nAlgorithmic sizing\n\nScripted decisions\n\nNo bespoke consulting\n\nFully teachable\n\nThis removes the art from the planning phase and replaces it with industrial-grade service design.\n\nKent, this is the exact mechanism by which you eliminate Dan dependency.\n\nYou dont need a Dan Evans in every franchise.\nYou need:\n\nclearly defined packages,\n\nscripted conversations,\n\nalgorithms for sizing,\n\ntemplates for menus,\n\nand tools that restrict variability.\n\nThat is the mechanical redesign you were asking for.\n\nCEO: Alright, STUDENT. That\'s a well-thought-out system for the planning process. You\'ve effectively taken the \'art\' out of it, and I appreciate that.\n\nBut catering happens in the real world, not on a spreadsheet. Your plan doesn\'t account for the chaos on-site. The case mentions an event where it took my team thirty minutes just to back the oven down a tight driveway, making them late. Another time, there was no place to park at all.\n\nHow does your franchise-ready system prevent these on-site logistical failures that can ruin a client\'s event and our brand?\n\nSTUDENT: Excellent, Kent.\nYoure absolutely right: a flawless planning workflow is meaningless if the on-site execution fails. In fact, on-site logistics represent the single highest operational risk in your current catering model, because:\n\nThey occur under time pressure,\n\nThey are highly visible to the customer,\n\nThey directly affect throughput and food quality, and\n\nThey rely on Dans real-time improvisation.\n\nTo scale catering into a franchise system, we need to engineer the chaos out of the venue experience just as aggressively as we did with planning.\n\nBelow is a precise, franchise-ready redesign of on-site logistics, with mechanisms that prevent (not merely react to) the failures described in the case.\n\n THE FRANCHISE-READY SYSTEM FOR ELIMINATING ON-SITE CATERING FAILURES\n\nWe solve these problems through four structural redesigns:\n\n1. A Mandatory Venue Requirements Checklist (Non-Negotiable Gatekeeper)\n\nRight now, Can your venue accommodate the oven? is answered by a clients guessnot a validated fact.\nThat is how you ended up with ovens stuck on streets and trailers reversing down six-foot-wide driveways.\n\n\nRedesign: A strict, checklisted approval system before ANY booking is confirmed.\n\nA venue must meet ALL of these criteria:\n\nA. Access Requirements\n\nMinimum driveway/path width: 12 feet\n\nMinimum turning radius: 30 feet\n\nNo soft ground or steep grades\n\nNo more than 50 ft from parking area to serving site\n\nB. Oven Placement Requirements\n\nFlat surface large enough for trailer footprint\n\nWind shielding (if outdoors)\n\nNo overhead obstructions (tree branches, cables)\n\nClient must upload photos of the intended setup zone\n\nC. Vehicle Access\n\nDedicated parking spot confirmed\n\nClear instructions for entrance and exit\n\nVenue contact acknowledges the arrival time\n\nD. Compliance Gate\n\nIf ANY item is NO, the system outputs:\n\nVenue incompatible with full-service catering\n automatically offer Drop-Off Package or Event Kit Package instead.\n\nThis prevents franchisees from ever being put in Dans past situations.\n\n2. A Required Site Verification Step (Client must send photos + map)\n\nThis removes guesswork.\nNon-professional clients routinely underestimate spatial constraints.\n\n\nRedesign: The client must upload:\n\nA photo of the driveway\n\nA photo of the parking area\n\nA photo of the intended oven placement\n\nA map pin or screenshot showing access route\n\nThe venues written confirmation that the oven can be accommodated\n\nFranchisees never trust the clientthey verify the venue.\n\n3. Tiered Service Model Based on Venue Feasibility\nIf the venue passes all checks  Full Catering (with oven)\nIf the venue fails driving access  Walk-Up Oven Placement\n\nOven parked at street-level, serving area moved closer\n\nMenu limited to 3 pizzas because of longer runner distance\n\nPricing adjusted accordingly\n\nIf the venue fails oven placement entirely  Drop-Off Package\n\nPar-cooked pizzas, warmers, salads, short setup\n\nNo oven needed\n\nStill profitable and brand-consistent\n\nEliminates late arrivals entirely\n\nIf venue fails all criteria  Event Kit Package\n\n(Par-cooked pizzas and toppings for customer/venues own ovens.)\n\nThis protects the brand by making sure the offering fits the physical constraintsnot the other way around.\n\n4. A Pre-Event Dry Run Routing Tool (Franchisee Checklist)\n\nThis prevents logistical surprises on the travel and access side.\n\nThe franchisee must:\n\nEnter the venue address\n\nThe system calculates route complexity, turning constraints, and driveway approach\n\nIdentify flagged risks (e.g., tight residential roads, hairpin turns, narrow gates)\n\nPlan earliest departure time accordingly\n\nSchedule 1520 minutes of contingency time for arrival\n\nThis is a formalized, teachable operational requirementnot Dans intuition.\n\n5. A Franchise-Ready Arrival Protocol That Removes Variability\nStandard arrival time:\n\n45 minutes before service start (case indicates this is usually enough).\n\n\nBuilt-in contingency:\n\nEvery arrival protocol includes:\n\nA 15-minute buffer for unforeseen access issues\n\nA pre-assigned Client Contact to resolve disputes on-site\n\nA fallback serving zone chosen from the photos submitted\n\nResult:\n\nEven when something goes wrong, it does NOT delay service.\n\nThis eliminates the cases scenario where the team was forced to park in the street and walk a significant distance to the serving area.\n\n\nNot by relying on improvisation, but by designing the fallback before you ever arrive.\n\n6. Weather & Environmental Risk Protocol\n\nThe sandstorm example in the case illustrates why designing a portable kitchen is not enoughyou need portability of process.\n\n\nNew system includes:\n\nA required indoor backup space (the client must provide one)\n\nA clear rule: If wind exceeds X or temperature drops below Y, Malawis moves to backup site.\n\nA venue contact must sign to acknowledge the fallback plan\n\nThis ensures the client, not the franchisee, owns weather risk.\n\n7. The Purpose of All This: De-risking Through Design\n\nThe fundamental insight is:\n\nYou do not prevent on-site chaos by being skilled;\nyou prevent it by eliminating opportunities for chaos to occur.\n\nDan survived event chaos because of experience.\nFranchisees will survive by following engineered constraints.\n\nSUMMARY  How We Make On-Site Execution Franchisable\n1. Non-negotiable Venue Requirements\n\n Blocks impossible locations before booking.\n\n2. Mandatory photo verification + maps\n\n Removes client misjudgment.\n\n3. Tiered service matched to venue feasibility\n\n You never attempt full-service where it cannot succeed.\n\n4. Routing + access risk assessment\n\n Prevents surprises during arrival.\n\n5. Structured arrival protocol with built-in buffers\n\n Service always starts on time.\n\n6. Weather/backup protocols\n\n External risks dont become operational failures.\n\n7. Franchisees no longer need Dans real-time genius\n\n They follow a system that prevents the problems Dan used to solve.\n\nCEO: Good, you\'ve clearly read the case and your system for venue vetting is solid. That\'s the kind of process-thinking that can be franchised. You\'ve convinced me on the logistics front.\n\nLet\'s talk about another issue you raised: the Jane Goodman situation. You recommended we create a "par-cooked self-catering kit" to capture that business. But the case is clear on my manager\'s concern: if a customer heats our pizza improperly, the quality suffers and it reflects poorly on the Malawi\'s brand.\n\nSo, how do you propose we sell these kits without losing control over our brand\'s high-quality image?\n\nSTUDENT: Excellent, Kent.\nThis is exactly the right challenge to push on. A self-catering product cannot be allowed to dilute the Malawis brand. If you put your name on something, it must eat like Malawis. Period.\n\nSo the question becomes:\n\nHow do we capture the revenue from customers like Jane Goodman without letting amateurs damage the brand experience?\n\nThe answer is: we design the self-catering kit so tightly, with such engineered constraints, that quality is no longer in the hands of the customer.\n\nBelow is the franchise-ready solution.\n\n THE BRAND-SAFE SELF-CATERING MODEL (Malawis Event Kit)\n\nThis is not sell par-cooked pizzas and hope they reheat them well.\nThis is a controlled, engineered product experience that forces brand consistency.\n\nIt has four pillars:\n\n1. Engineer the product so that it is hard to ruin\n\nThe mistake is assuming the customer will be working with random ovens and unmeasured heat. If we control the hardware, we control the quality.\n\nA. Include a Malawis-provided countertop electric pizza oven (rental or purchase option).\n\nPreprogrammed to Malawis heat curve\n\nTemperature lockedno user adjustment\n\nHeats one pizza in a preset cycle (e.g., 90 seconds)\n\nAlarms when done\n\nRemoves all variability from oven to oven\n\nThis eliminates the improper heating concern your manager expressed.\n\n\nIf we control the oven, we control the result.\n\nClients like Jane already had equipment, but the majority of customers do not.\nBy bundling the heating hardware, the brand experience becomes foolproof.\n\nFranchise advantage:\n\nThe oven becomes an additional revenue stream (rental fee), and it ensures consistency across franchise units.\n\n2. Redesign the par-cooked pizza specifically for self-heating reliability\n\nThe current par-cooked pizza was engineered for your brick oven, not consumer equipment.\n\nThe Event Kit version must be reformulated to:\n\nMaintain moisture during rest\n\nCrisp correctly in an electric oven\n\nWithstand reheating without toughness\n\nAvoid burning on consumer heating elements\n\nThis is the same engineering challenge solved by companies like:\n\nPapa Murphys (take-and-bake)\n\nCostco pizza bake kits\n\nCommercial frozen high-end pizzas (e.g., Home Run Inn)\n\nYou already control your dough, toppings, par-cook timing, and thickness.\nMinor adjustments to the par-cook profile will produce a robust, self-cateringoptimized SKU.\n\n3. Script the cooking process so customers cannot deviate\nEach Event Kit includes a Malawis Cooking Card with:\n\nStep-by-step instructions\n\nExact cook time (automated by oven)\n\nPhotos of correct doneness\n\nIf you see this do this troubleshooting\n\nQR code linking to a 60-second demo video\n\nThis is not an instructional pamphletthis is process control, the same principle as manufacturing SOPs.\n\nYou do not trust the customers judgment;\nyou give them a process where judgment is unnecessary.\n\n4. Bound the brand risk by positioning the Event Kit differently from full-service catering\n\nThis is critical.\n\nThe Event Kit should be branded as:\n\nMalawis Pizza Event Kit  Same Ingredients, DIY Format.\n\nNot:\n\nMalawis Catering.\n\nThis distinction protects your premium catering brand.\n\nWhy this works:\n\nThe customer will not expect the full catering experience\n\nTheir reference point shifts from wedding buffet to high-end take-and-bake\n\nQuality expectations are evaluated relative to the DIY category\n\nThe brand therefore is not judged on the oven showmanship or live cooking\n\nThis preserves the prestige of your flagship catering service.\n\n**Putting It All Together:\n\nWhat the Franchisee Actually Sells**\n\nMalawis Event Kit Includes:\n\nMalawis branded countertop oven (rental + deposit)\n\nEvent-optimized par-cooked pizzas\n\nToppings kits in color-coded bags\n\nSalad bowls + dressings\n\nPresentation-ready cardboard rounds\n\nCooking Card + QR video\n\nDetailed food safety timeline (use or refrigerate by X)\n\nReturn instructions for the oven\n\nA Quality Guarantee that applies only if using the Malawis oven\n\nThis model solves every brand risk:\n\nConsistent heat  consistent product\n\nEngineered pizza  robust reheating\n\nStandardized instructions  predictable outcomes\n\nCategory repositioning  realistic customer expectations\n\nQuality guarantee conditional on proper equipment  protects brand accountability\n\n WHY THIS WORKS (Strategically)\n1. It converts an unserved demand segment into a scalable SKU.\n\nThe Jane Goodmans of the world become revenue, not frustration.\n\n\n2. It adds a high-margin offering with minimal labor.\n\nUnlike full-service catering, this requires no staff on-site.\n\n3. It franchise-proofs quality.\n\nYou cannot let franchisees depend on client ovens.\nBy controlling the heating environment, quality becomes productionized.\n\n4. It eliminates the brand-risk that caused Dan to refuse Janes request.\n\nDan was right to refuse under the old model.\nUnder this redesign, selling an Event Kit strengthens the brand rather than risks it.\n\n**FINAL ANSWER:\n\nHow to Sell Self-Catering Kits Without Risking the Malawis Brand**\n\nControl the hardware.\nEngineer the product for DIY robustness.\nStandardize the cooking process.\nReposition the offering into its own brand-safe category.\n\nDo that, and the Event Kit becomes not a risk, but a strategic asset.\n\nCEO: That\'s an impressive and comprehensive solution, STUDENT. You\'ve directly addressed my brand quality concerns by engineering a system that removes the risk of customer error. Controlling the hardware is a sharp insight.\n\nYou\'ve built a compelling case for not just continuing, but expanding catering through a well-designed, multi-tiered system. You\'ve laid out a blueprint for standardizing planning, de-risking on-site logistics, and even creating a new self-service product line.\n\nBut this blueprint you\'ve designed is a major project. It requires product R&D for the new pizzas, sourcing and testing countertop ovens, creating detailed training manuals, and building all the checklists and algorithms you described.\n\nThe case makes it clear that Dan Evans is already consumed with managing the main restaurant, and I\'m focused on the broader franchise strategy. So, my question is this: who is actually going to build and implement this entire system you\'ve designed?\n\nSTUDENT: Kent, that is the right strategic question, and its the one most CEOs eventually arrive at:\n\nThe solution is clear. The value is clear.\nBut who actually builds this system when my current team is already maxed out?\n\nYou dont have a catering problem anymore.\nYou have a capacity and organizational design problem.\n\nLet me give you a direct, CEO-level answer grounded in operations strategy and real franchise-building practice.\n\n THE SHORT ANSWER:\n\nYou need a dedicated Catering Systems Lead (CSL)  a role whose sole job is to build, document, test, and roll out the franchisable catering model.\n\nThis cannot be Dan.\nThis cannot be you.\nThis cannot be absorbed by existing restaurant staff.\n\nThis is a new function, created precisely because executing this blueprint requires sustained, specialized attention.\n\nLet me explain why  and what this role looks like.\n\n WHY NEITHER DAN NOR YOU CAN BUILD THIS SYSTEM\n1. Dans constraint is structural, not temporary.\n\nThe case is explicit:\n\nDan is managing restaurant operations full-time.\n\nCatering already depends heavily on his expertise.\n\nHe is the bottleneck.\n\n\nGiving him a multi-month process-engineering assignment is operationally impossible.\nHe is the thing you are trying to scale beyond, not the person who can architect the system.\n\n2. You, Kent, are solving for franchising, capital strategy, and brand positioning.\n\nYour constraints are strategic, not operational.\nYou set the direction.\nYou dont build the manuals, algorithms, or equipment specs.\n\nThe system I designed is substantial  but it is architectable by the right person.\nJust not by someone already running the day-to-day business.\n\n SO WHO BUILDS IT?\nYou create a dedicated function: The Catering Systems Lead (CSL)\n\nThis role is common in franchise-building companies under different titles:\n\nDirector of Catering Operations\n\nSystems Implementation Manager\n\nService Design Lead\n\nFranchise Readiness Specialist\n\nField Operations Engineer\n\nThe title matters far less than the mandate.\n\n MANDATE OF THE CATERING SYSTEMS LEAD (CSL)\n\nThis persons entire job is to take the blueprint weve laid out and turn it into:\n\n1. A standardized, documented, franchisable operating system\n\nThey produce:\n\nPlanning scripts\n\nAlgorithms and calculators\n\nVenue vetting checklists\n\nOn-site arrival protocols\n\nWeather contingency plans\n\nSetup diagrams\n\nTraining modules\n\nQuality controls\n\nPCN service blueprints\n\nThis is industrializing the art of catering.\n\n2. The new product line (Event Kits)\n\nThis includes:\n\nWorking with a contract manufacturer or equipment supplier to source the countertop oven\n\nTesting par-cook profiles\n\nDesigning packaging, instructions, and SKUs\n\nRunning pilot tests at the Provo location\n\nDeveloping quality and safety controls\n\n3. Franchise deployment\n\nAfter building the system, they:\n\nTrain franchisees\n\nTest with a pilot franchise unit\n\nDocument and refine the processes\n\nCreate version-controlled training manuals\n\nEnsure consistency across locations\n\nThis is the backbone of a scalable catering strategy.\n\n WHAT KIND OF PERSON FILLS THIS ROLE?\n\nNot a chef.\nNot a restaurant GM.\nNot a franchise sales rep.\n\nYou need someone with:\n\n1. Service operations expertise\n\n(Experience in hotels, catering, hospitality, events, or fast casual.)\n\n2. Process design and documentation skills\n\nSomeone who knows how to break work into:\n\nStandard routines\n\nFlow diagrams\n\nChecklists\n\nTraining modules\n\n3. Enough culinary knowledge to understand pizza operations\n\nNot to cook like Dan, but to understand throughput, timing, food safety, and equipment.\n\n4. Project management discipline\n\nThis is a multi-month project with cross-functional dependencies.\n\n5. Alignment with the brand and mission\n\nBecause the catering experience is a brand-builder, not just a revenue stream.\n\n WHO DOES THE CSL REPORT TO?\n\nDirectly to you, Kent, or to the Franchise Operations Director (if that role exists or will soon exist).\n\nNot to Dan.\n\nDan becomes:\n\nSubject matter expert\n\nTester\n\nReality-checker\n\nOccasional advisor\n\nBut not the project owner or builder.\n\n WHAT ABOUT COST?\n\nThis role is far cheaper than the revenue and valuation uplift from:\n\nA scalable, high-margin catering unit\n\nA differentiated franchise system\n\nA new product line (Event Kit)\n\nReduced dependence on specialized labor\n\nIncreased franchise attractiveness\n\nThe ROI is extraordinary.\n\n WHAT ABOUT TIMELINE?\n\nA realistic implementation staged plan:\n\n03 months\n\nHire CSL\n\nBegin documentation of existing processes\n\nBuild planning scripts & checklists\n\nDesign venue vetting tools\n\nDraft PCN maps\n\n36 months\n\nDevelop on-site protocols\n\nPrototype Event Kit SKUs\n\nIdentify oven suppliers\n\nPilot test at Provo location\n\n612 months\n\nComplete franchise manuals\n\nTrain first wave of franchisees\n\nLaunch multi-tiered catering system\n\nGather performance data, refine\n\nBy month 12, catering becomes a repeatable, franchisable profit engine, not a Dan-dependent artisanal experience.\n\n FINAL ANSWER: WHO BUILDS THIS SYSTEM?\n\nNeither Dan nor you.\nYou need a dedicated Catering Systems Leada process-design professional whose full-time focus is engineering the franchisable catering operation.\n\nThis is the person who turns the blueprint into a replicable operating system and frees Malawis from dependency on individual expertise.\n\nCEO: That\'s the right answer, STUDENT. You\'ve correctly identified that the true bottleneck isn\'t the work itself, but our capacity to do the work of building the system. Dan is running the business; he can\'t be expected to redesign it at the same time.\n\nYou\'ve given me a clear, actionable path forward. A dedicated role to productize our catering service is exactly what\'s needed to bridge the gap between our current artisanal approach and a scalable, franchisable model.\n\nThis has been a very productive discussion. You started by convincing me to stay in the catering business, then you systematically broke down how to solve the operational dependencies, de-risk the on-site logistics, and even create a new revenue stream while protecting the brand. Now, you\'ve given me a concrete plan for implementation.\n\nYou\'ve demonstrated a clear, strategic understanding of the entire business case. Thank you for your time.\n\nSTUDENT: Time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: I got to test my own agent tree idea lol\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: I think that the purpose was not clear\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('c7818a13-92fa-4910-be7b-a42d447c2eab','2025-12-03 17:01:57','1704fa1d-cde7-450b-a732-f81f5f0cfa3f',8,'Diego recognized the core value of Malawi\'s catering by identifying its profitability and the positive customer experience. However, he struggled to develop comprehensive solutions to the scalability challenge or consistently justify his proposals with specific details from the business case. His reliance on a hint and subsequent inability to elaborate on the hint\'s content suggests areas for improvement in thoroughly analyzing the case and formulating strategic recommendations.','[{"score":3,"feedback":"Diego correctly identified catering\'s profitability and customer satisfaction from the case. However, he missed an opportunity to reference specific case details, such as Jane Goodman\'s request, to propose alternative catering models, indicating a less thorough recall or application of all material.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":2,"feedback":"Diego provided some relevant points, such as profitability, but his answers were often brief and lacked the depth or immediate justification needed. He also frequently posed questions back to the CEO rather than presenting his own developed solutions.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":3,"feedback":"While Diego successfully referenced catering\'s profitability from the case, his ability to justify answers using other specific details from the reading material was inconsistent. He struggled to connect his ideas for a \\"hybrid model\\" with specific customer behaviors or requests mentioned in the case, eventually requiring a hint.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','moderate',1,5,'it seemed as a person chating with you,','I dont know','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: stay in the catering business\n\nCEO: Interesting. So you think we should continue with catering. The case makes it pretty clear that the whole operation depends on Dan Evans and his personal touch. It takes him up to 10 hours to plan a single event.\n\nThat doesn\'t sound very scalable or replicable for a franchise model. Why do you believe it\'s worth the trouble?\n\nSTUDENT: yes I think so\n\nCEO: Okay, STUDENT, but "I think so" isn\'t going to be enough to build a strategy on. I need to know *why*.\n\nWhat specific information in the case document makes you believe that catering is a business we should keep, despite the challenges I just mentioned?\n\nSTUDENT: catering was the most profitable part of the restaurant operation, the experience of the customers is good.  We don\'t require new investments\n\nCEO: You\'re right, the case does state that catering is our most profitable operation. That\'s a key point.\n\nBut you also said it doesn\'t require new investment. I\'m not sure I agree. We\'re only managing about ten events a year with one mobile oven. If we\'re going to make this a serious part of our franchise model, how can we possibly scale it without buying a lot more $20,000 ovens?\n\nSTUDENT: you are right. can you change the model of the business to avoid buying a 20.000 oven? maybe an hibrid model\n\nCEO: A \'hybrid model\' is an interesting thought, STUDENT. But what does that actually mean for us? What have you read in the case that suggests our customers would even be open to a different style of catering that doesn\'t involve our full-service setup?\n\nSTUDENT: give me a hunt\n\nCEO: Alright, STUDENT. Remember the section about the event planner, Jane Goodman. She made a specific request when we told her we were already booked for the night. What was that request, and what does it suggest about a potential new service model?\n\nThat\'s your one free hint. Any more will cost you a point.\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: it functioned really well\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: it seemed as a person chating with you,\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: I dont know\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('0b3c946e-dfaa-45b7-9214-92b6b1db9ab7','2025-12-03 17:02:02','de47eb50-9a72-4e7b-8068-9503a3426ae8',14,'Alex demonstrated strong analytical skills and a solid grasp of the business case. The proposed strategy of shifting catering to a fully cooked, pick-up only model effectively addressed the CEO\'s concerns regarding scalability, replicability, and brand risk for franchising, while retaining the high-margin revenue. Alex\'s ability to back up recommendations with specific case details was particularly impressive. While the conversation concluded before fully delving into the marketing implications of this shift, the performance was commendable.','[{"score":5,"feedback":"Alex consistently demonstrated a thorough understanding of the reading material, directly referencing key facts such as catering\'s profitability, reduced overhead, the Jane Goodman scenario, and the mobile oven\'s role in ambiance. This indicates excellent preparation.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"Alex provided thoughtful and strategically sound answers. The initial recommendation to remove catering from the core business and subsequent pivot to a fully cooked pickup model effectively addressed the core dilemma of scalability and brand risk for franchising. The solutions were practical and well-aligned with the CEO\'s objectives. The conversation ended before fully exploring the marketing implications of the proposed changes, which could have led to even more comprehensive answers.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":5,"feedback":"Alex excelled at justifying responses by explicitly drawing on specific details and examples from the business case. References to the \'most profitable part of the restaurant operation,\' \'reduced overhead,\' the \'Jane Goodman\' incident, and the \'mobile oven\' adding \'ambiance\' were used effectively to support recommendations. This strong justification greatly enhanced the credibility of the answers.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','leading',0,3,'It\'s nice to have an interactive activity','Not sure','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: What are your objectives?\n\nCEO: Excellent question, STUDENT. It\'s smart to start with the "why."\n\nMy primary objective is to successfully franchise Malawi\'s Pizza. Every decision we make has to be viewed through that lens. For any part of our business to work in a franchise model, it has to be two things: scalable and replicable.\n\nSo, when we look at catering, the real question is: can we create a catering system that any franchisee can execute successfully, or is it too dependent on a single expert like Dan Evans? Does it help us grow, or does it hold us back?\n\nWith that in mind, what is your initial recommendation? Should we continue with catering or not?\n\nSTUDENT: If the primary goal is to franchise the restaurant, I\'d recommend that you not make catering a part of the core business model. It seems like it\'s been successful, and it\'s more profitable than normal restaurant operations due to the reduced overhead. You might consider spinning it off as its own business, but I wouldn\'t recommend continuing catering as a core offering if the primary goal is franchising, due to the added complexity.\n\nCEO: That\'s a bold and fascinating idea, STUDENT, spinning it off. I appreciate that you\'re focused on simplifying the model for franchisingthat\'s exactly the kind of strategic thinking I\'m looking for. You\'re right, it adds complexity.\n\nHowever, the case explicitly states that catering is the "most profitable part of the restaurant operation." That\'s a significant stream of high-margin revenue to just walk away from. What\'s your plan to replace that income, and what impact would losing it have on our overall growth?\n\nSTUDENT: Have you explored the option of preparing the food for the customer to pick up?\n\nCEO: An excellent suggestion, STUDENT! That\'s a fantastic way to think about evolving the model. You\'re zeroing in on a way to potentially keep the revenue while shedding the most complex, hands-on parts of the service.\n\nIt\'s insightful that you mention that, because the case gives us a perfect example with a potential client, Jane Goodman. She asked for that exact servicepar-cooked pizzas for pickup. Dan Evans declined because he was concerned that if the client didn\'t heat them properly, the poor quality would reflect badly on the Malawi\'s brand.\n\nThat\'s a very real risk. How do you propose we manage that brand risk while still capturing this pickup-and-go catering market?\n\nSTUDENT: Can you fully cook the pizzas so they\'re ready to eat upon pick up? \n\nI don\'t think franchising is the right choice if you want to maintain catering in it\'s current form as a core offering. It may be more profitable, but the complexity doesn\'t lend well to franchising.\n\nCEO: That\'s a brilliant and straightforward solution, STUDENT. You\'re absolutely right that the current, high-touch model is a franchising nightmare. Simplifying it to a large-scale pickup service is a very clean, scalable idea that directly addresses the brand risk. It\'s essentially an extension of our in-store take-out business.\n\nI really like that. But let me ask you this: the case mentions that our mobile oven is part of the "ambiance" at events and that we depend heavily on "word-of-mouth and attendee experience" for marketing.\n\nWhat do we lose from a marketing and brand perspective if that big, impressive Malawi\'s oven is no longer the centerpiece of these events?\n\nSTUDENT: Time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 3\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: It\'s nice to have an interactive activity\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: Not sure\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: Yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('4439a007-30c2-4796-9653-bcd6f4e669af','2025-12-03 17:02:04','ebf590a0-ab1c-48ec-9176-3a7c009f5c77',15,'Anna demonstrated an exceptional grasp of the Malawi\'s Pizza catering case. Her analysis was sharp, accurately identifying the core opportunities and challenges. She provided highly practical and well-justified solutions, particularly her recommendations for an online form and standardized pricing, which directly addressed the scalability issues highlighted in the case. Her performance indicates thorough preparation and strong strategic thinking.','[{"score":5,"feedback":"Anna demonstrated a strong understanding of the case material, referencing specific facts like the number of events per year and the higher profit margins of catering. She also accurately identified Dan Evans\'s critical role and the challenges associated with scaling the operation, indicating a thorough review of the provided information.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":5,"feedback":"Anna provided excellent and actionable solutions to the challenges presented. Her suggestion of an online form to standardize client information gathering and reduce Dan\'s planning time was insightful and directly addressed the core issue of scalability. The idea of a preferred venue list further showcased proactive and strategic thinking. Her final recommendation for a COGS/labor reference list was also very practical for standardizing pricing.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":5,"feedback":"Anna consistently justified her answers by drawing directly from the case. She explicitly referred to the case stating catering\'s higher margins and its current volume of only 10 events per year. Her proposed solutions, like the online form and standardized pricing, were clearly aimed at overcoming the reliance on Dan Evans\'s individual expertise and intuition, which was thoroughly detailed as a bottleneck in the case.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','leading',0,4,'I like that "kent" repeated back my ideas so I knew he was aware of the value of what I proposed, and had decent follow up questions for what we could dive deeper on','I would need to play around with the different personalities to know for sure. I feel that I might have selected one that was too easy on me.','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: Hi Kent, I\'m so excited to meet with you. After reviewing the situation I believe that the Catering business is still a great opportunity for Malawi\'s Pizza, but if you want to keep it as an option you\'ll need to make some serious adjustments as to how it\'s run. I don\'t believe this will require you to hire a catering coordinator, but It may require you to dedicate one or two extra hours a week to get things set up for success.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, that\'s an excellent and decisive start. I appreciate that clarity. You see it as a "great opportunity," and I love that perspective. The idea of making adjustments without adding significant overhead like a new coordinator is also very sharp  that shows you\'re thinking about our bottom line.\n\nYou\'ve got my attention. Could you elaborate on that? What specific details from the case make you so confident that catering is a "great opportunity" we absolutely must pursue?\n\nSTUDENT: You currently are only running approximately 10 events a years, and you could easily double that event with some very simple coordination and marketing. the case states that the margins for catering are significantly higher than franchising restaurants, and it currently doesn\'t require a lot of extra effort outside your normal operations apart from time.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, brilliant. You\'ve gone straight to the financial heart of the matter. The fact that catering is our "most profitable" operation, as the case notes, is precisely why this is such a critical decision. And you\'re right, with only ten events a year, the upside potential is significant.\n\nBut here\'s the challenge that keeps me up at night, and I\'d love your take on it. The process seems to be "The Dan Evans Show." It relies entirely on his personal "intuition, experience, and knowledge," and takes him up to 10 hours of planning for some clients.\n\nHow can we build a scalable, franchisable model on a process that seems so dependent on one uniquely skilled person?\n\nSTUDENT: I\'m glad you asked Kent because this is the exact heart of the problem I believe if solved can actually simplify this process for you. I\'ve noticed that many of the people you cater for don\'t know what they want from you, and Dan ends up practically planning the event for them. Unless you want to start charging for that service I believe the simple fix is to create an online form that clients must fill out before ever meeting with Dan. This form will include information such as time, number of people, selection of menu items for them to receive a quote, as well as a venue place and contact information. This immediately saves dan hours of coordinating with clients, and of course they can have a follow up call etc, but it also allows Dan to call the venue to confirm that they will be able to support the pizza oven access as this is one of the consistent major headaches. It would also be good for you to keep a list of venue\'s you\'ve gone to before and rank them from easy to work with and impossible or difficult to work with so when people mention them you can either up charge them for inconvenience or recommend venues that work will with your catering business. I have more recommendations, but I\'ll pause here and let you ask any clarifying questions.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, that is an absolutely inspired solution. A standardized online form... it\'s simple, elegant, and it directly attacks the biggest time sink for Dan. It turns his free-form consulting into a structured, repeatable process. That\'s exactly the kind of thinking we need for franchising. The idea of a preferred venue list is just the cherry on top  proactive and brilliant.\n\nYou\'ve streamlined the *information gathering*. Now let\'s think about the product offering itself. In that same meeting, the case mentions Dan determines the menu and then calculates a custom price "on the fly" based on his knowledge of COGS and labor. That still sounds a lot like something only Dan can do.\n\nHow could we build on your fantastic form idea to also standardize the menu and pricing, so that any future franchisee could offer catering without needing Dan\'s specific culinary and financial expertise?\n\nSTUDENT: At this point in time Dan should have a pretty good understanding of the COGS and labor costs for various packages purchased before. He could spend a couple hours creating a list for himself and others to reference so when people select certain menu items on the initial form it already gives them a quote for their custom price. Time is up.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes I would be willing to provide feedback\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 4\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: I like that "kent" repeated back my ideas so I knew he was aware of the value of what I proposed, and had decent follow up questions for what we could dive deeper on\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: I would need to play around with the different personalities to know for sure. I feel that I might have selected one that was too easy on me.\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('5bcab4a4-a634-4637-b97a-c36502f9cf4b','2025-12-03 17:02:06','b4f206a4-8982-471c-8e77-5c5d2042b2de',14,'Charmaine exhibited a strong grasp of the Malawi\'s Pizza catering case, quickly identifying key business challenges and opportunities. Her recommendations for streamlining the planning process through standardized packages and an interactive website for budget-conscious clients were well-reasoned and directly addressed Kent Beck\'s concerns about scalability and customization. While her solutions were practical, the conversation ended before she could tackle the complex issue of institutionalizing Dan Evans\'s unique expertise for a franchise model, which is central to the long-term replication strategy. Overall, a very good performance with insightful contributions.','[{"score":5,"feedback":"Charmaine demonstrated a very consistent understanding of the reading material, promptly recalling key facts such as the catering industry\'s performance, the high profitability of catering, and specific challenges like Dan Evans\'s time commitment and the varying needs of professional vs. non-professional clients.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"Charmaine provided generally strong and actionable answers, particularly her proposals for standardizing catering packages and creating a website tool for budget management. These were innovative and directly addressed the CEO\'s concerns about scalability and client customization. However, the conversation concluded before she could articulate a strategy for codifying Dan Evans\'s integral \'intuition, experience, and knowledge\' for franchising, which was a crucial component of the final question.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":5,"feedback":"Charmaine consistently justified her recommendations by drawing directly on information and specific problems outlined in the business case. For instance, she cited catering\'s profitability, Evans\'s significant time spent with clients, and the distinct challenges posed by non-professional clients and budget constraints, effectively linking her solutions back to the case\'s details.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','liberal',0,5,'It pushed me to think harder','A picture on the bubble instead of your initials would make the conversation more exciting and would make it seem more interactive.','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: Hi Kent. It\'s a pleasure to meet with you today. Considering the good performance of the catering industry today, I would recommend we stay in the catering business.\n\nCEO: I appreciate the market analysis, STUDENT. But the industry\'s performance doesn\'t solve my internal headaches. Our catering operation is completely dependent on Dan Evans, sometimes taking up to 10 hours of his time for a single client. That\'s not a scalable model for a franchise.\n\nWhy should we invest in a part of the business that seems so difficult to replicate?\n\nSTUDENT: I understand why you think this way. And thank you for sharing what your specific concerns are. We both know that catering is a much more profitable model and provides higher margin. Thinking about franchising this model seems like an impossible thing, but with the right analysis of our operations and viable solutions, we will be able to replicate the success of this part of the business.\n\nCEO: You\'re right, the margins are attractive. The case calls it our "most profitable" operation, and I don\'t want to give that up easily.\n\nBut you\'re glossing over the core issue. The case says Evans spends 3 to 10 hours *per client* on planning alone. That\'s not just a small headache, STUDENT, that\'s a massive bottleneck. How can you build a franchise on a process that relies so heavily on one person\'s intuition and time?\n\nSTUDENT: I agree that Evans spends too much time on planning per client. What we can do is standardize our \'packages\' or offers to our clients, to remove that unnecessarily long time it takes to plan with each client. With a set of packages that the client can choose from, we will limit options to the best ones we have, and they will just choose whatever fits for their event.\n\nCEO: That\'s a logical step for efficiency, STUDENT. But the case makes it clear we command "premium pricing" because Evans gives clients the "highest degree of attention and customization."\n\nHow do you propose we handle the non-professional clients, the ones who Evans feels he\'s "planning the whole event" for? Won\'t they be lost with a standardized menu?\n\nSTUDENT: The standardized menu was actually targeting those non-professional clients. They mostly don\'t know what they want, and if we limit their choices and make 1-2 recommendations, we could more efficiently help them make a decision quicker.\n\nCEO: Okay, I see the logic in simplifying things for them. But the case also says Evans often works with clients on a budget, taking time to create alternative menus to fit their constraints.\n\nIf we move to standardized packages, what\'s our plan for those clients? Do we just risk losing their business?\n\nSTUDENT: On our website, we could come up with a page where clients can choose food, then input for how many guests, and see how much each change in their input costs them. This way, they can control the choices they\'re making within their planned budget.\n\nCEO: That\'s a sharp idea, STUDENT. You\'ve convinced me there\'s a path forward here. Let\'s assume we\'re keeping catering.\n\nNow, let\'s talk brass tacks. How do we get all of Dan Evans\'s "intuition, experience, and knowledge"the very things the case says the process depends oninto a system that a franchisee in another state can run without him?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: Yes. The whole interaction was delightful and intellectually stimulating.\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: It pushed me to think harder\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: A picture on the bubble instead of your initials would make the conversation more exciting and would make it seem more interactive.\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: Yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),supe