INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('5c5c8d34-dcf2-467f-ba40-fc1469a4dca9','2025-12-03 17:02:07','069f3d0d-983b-40ac-b086-d1c904debd51',12,'Lakely demonstrated a good grasp of the case details and the core challenges faced by Malawi\'s Pizza Catering. She offered several practical solutions for streamlining the planning process and addressing the time demands on Dan Evans. While her suggestions for scaling the \'intuition\' aspect of the catering service were less developed, she engaged thoughtfully with the problem. Her strong understanding of the reading material and ability to connect her suggestions to the case were commendable.','[{"score":5,"feedback":"Lakely demonstrated a strong understanding of the business case, accurately identifying key challenges like Dan\'s time sink with non-professional planners and the high-margin nature of catering. She also correctly referenced the case\'s mention of hiring a part-time catering salesperson/manager. Her responses consistently aligned with the details and strategic direction presented in the reading material.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":3,"feedback":"Lakely provided good initial answers, identifying valid solutions such as using forms, hiring a manager, or a chatbot. However, when pressed on the scalability of training and documenting Dan\'s \'intuition,\' her answer about \'shadowing\' was less robust and ultimately she conceded when asked for a system-level solution. While her initial problem identification and proposed solutions were solid, the conversation highlighted a gap in developing truly scalable and replicable systems.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"Lakely consistently tied her answers back to the case. She cited the high profit margin of catering, the time investment required from Dan Evans, and the specific challenge of documenting his \'intuition, experience, and knowledge\' as mentioned in the text. Her justifications were good and directly referenced pertinent points from the business case to support her arguments.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','moderate',0,5,'It forced me to think deeper than I had when I read the case on my own. It also felt like a real conversation versus me just guessing what Kent would say.','Well I couldn\'t connect to the API at first. But after I connected it worked great!','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: Hi Kent, I\'ll get right to it then. We should definitely stay in the catering business.\n\nCEO: I appreciate the directness, STUDENT. But I\'m not convinced. The case mentions catering is a huge time sink for my GM, Dan Evans, and we only do about ten events a year. It seems like a lot of hassle for a small part of the business. What makes you so sure it\'s worth the trouble?\n\nSTUDENT: You\'re right, it is a small part of the business right now. However, this part of the business has low maintenance costs and thus high margin. Growing this segment could be advantageous to Malawi\'s. The biggest cost of this segment is the time, like you\'ve mentioned. However, I believe we can decrease the time Dan needs to spend. Currently the biggest time drain is the planning portion of the catering event. Through what I\'ve seen, Dan prefers to have in person meetings to enhance client experience and often ends up helping non-professional planners actually plan their event. I agree that in person meetings help enhance your brand. There doesn\'t appear to be a set process however. Developing a strict process, through a form to fill out perhaps, could shave down the time and help make these meetings more efficient. When a client calls for a consultation about an event, sending over the form for them to pre fill out will reduce the meeting time and put more of the planning work on the person requesting the event than Dan.\n\nCEO: That\'s a reasonable idea, STUDENT. A form could certainly help with standardization.\n\nBut the case mentions that a large part of Dan\'s time is spent hand-holding non-professional planners who don\'t know what they\'re doing. They come to him for advice, not just to fill out an order.\n\nHow does a form address their needs without alienating them or creating a poor experience?\n\nSTUDENT: This is a good point Kent. Some ideas to address this could be to hire a part-time catering manager who could take over these meetings for him. Then Dan could spend his valuable time doing more high value activities than event planning. Another idea is to create a chatbot online that can answer many of these common questions before the customer even comes to the meeting. A third idea is to actually offer planning as part of the service. Charge separately for it and offer it as a "value add." We can also help you plan your event kind of a thing.\n\nCEO: Those are three very different paths, STUDENT. Let\'s focus on the first one for a moment: hiring someone.\n\nThe case states the current process depends on Dan\'s personal \'intuition, experience, and knowledge.\' If we just hire another person, aren\'t we just creating another bottleneck? How does that solve our core problem of making this process replicable for a franchise?\n\nSTUDENT: Good point. This would require an upfront time cost for Dan to train someone. However, if we plan to keep the catering business and expand it, we will need a full team dedicated to it in time. Investing time in training someone now will prevent us from having a scramble later when we