at!\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('e56898be-ad8d-43ae-a214-8972064c0aa9','2025-12-03 17:02:12','17151321-e7ff-45a2-a309-756730295597',9,'John demonstrated a foundational understanding of the Malawi\'s Pizza Catering case, particularly in recognizing the strategic importance of catering\'s profitability. He effectively identified a key financial statement after some prompting, indicating good comprehension. However, his overall performance was impacted by not fully developing his initial answers and, most critically, by not addressing the significant challenge of scaling the catering operation beyond Dan Evans. To excel, John should focus on anticipating and proactively addressing the core strategic problems presented in the case, providing well-articulated and complete solutions.','[{"score":4,"feedback":"John demonstrated a good understanding of the case material. While he initially struggled to recall the specific financial claim about catering\'s profitability, he did eventually provide the exact quote when prompted, indicating he had read and could locate the information. His earlier responses also referenced relevant elements of the case, such as the potential for expansion and the challenges with Dan Evans\'s workload.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":2,"feedback":"John\'s answers were fair but inconsistent. He provided some good points early on regarding the potential for catering, but his initial response was a simple conclusion without justification. He did successfully identify the key profitability statement when guided. However, a significant area for improvement was his abrupt end to the conversation with \'Time is up\', leaving the critical question about solving the Dan Evans bottleneck completely unanswered. This omission prevented him from providing a comprehensive solution to a central problem in the case.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":3,"feedback":"John\'s justification improved over the course of the conversation. Initially, his justifications were general references to the case, such as \'profit margin and expansion capabilities\'. He then attempted to justify his inability to provide specific numbers by referencing the case\'s overall EBITDA. He ultimately provided a solid justification for the profitability question by directly quoting the case. However, the lack of an answer to the final question meant no justification was offered for a major strategic challenge.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','sycophantic',0,5,'I liked most that it forced me to keep thinking more deeply about the question being asked. Farther than the surface level response.','The conversation seemed to be leading me into a single answer whereas many times there is not 1 single answer.','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: Expand the catering business.\n\nCEO: Interesting, STUDENT. You\'re suggesting we double down on catering.\n\nI\'m not so sure. From what I see, the catering operation is a huge headache. It seems completely dependent on Dan Evans, taking up massive amounts of his time. We\'ve had issues with venues, miscommunications with clients, and it seems incredibly difficult to standardize.\n\nFrankly, it looks like a high-risk distraction from our core restaurant business. Why should we expand it? What specific evidence in the case convinces you that the reward outweighs these obvious risks?\n\nSTUDENT: The profit margin and expansion capabilities of the catering market are fantastic opportunities for the business. It costs significantly less to add another mobile oven and truck while allowing more flexibility in your offerings. Dan or another employee should be designated as contact person for catering and that is their sole responsibility as opposed to splitting roles. Venue issues and miscommunication will happen in any service, but with mistakes come learning and the team can do better with each event.\n\nCEO: You\'re touching on some important points, STUDENT, but your argument feels a bit general. You say the profit margin is a "fantastic opportunity," but that\'s an assertion. I\'m looking for evidence.\n\nThe case document has very specific language describing the financial contribution of the catering business relative to our other operations. Before we talk about hiring new people or buying more trucks, I need to be convinced the foundation is solid.\n\nWhat, specifically, does the case say about the profitability of our catering operation? Let\'s start there.\n\nSTUDENT: The case mentions that catering has a higher profit margin, but I do not believe it states exactly how much higher. We may be able to rough calculate based on the pricing for the catered event, but do not have the COGS either. The case gives an overall EBITDA margin of 10% rising to 12% in year 3, but that would be all operations together.\n\nCEO: You\'re correct, the specific numbers aren\'t broken out for us to calculate. But you\'re overlooking a crucial statement in the case. It\'s not just that the margin is "higher." The case makes a much stronger claim about catering\'s financial role, a direct quote that explains why this is even on my radar despite the operational headaches.\n\nWhat is the exact description of catering\'s profitability mentioned in the case? This is the core of the financial argument.\n\nSTUDENT: The catering process was an important part of the planned\nmovement into franchising, and catering was the most profitable part of the restaurant operation\n\nCEO: Exactly. "The most profitable part of the restaurant operation." That\'s the phrase that keeps me up at night. On one hand, it\'s our golden goose. On the other, it\'s a house of cards built entirely on one person.\n\nYou\'ve convinced me of the *value*, STUDENT. Good. You\'ve clearly read the case.\n\nNow, let\'s talk implementation. The case makes it painfully clear that the entire catering process depends on Dan Evans\'s "intuition, experience, and knowledge." He spends 3 to 10 hours per client on planning alone. This model is not scalable, and it\'s certainly not replicable for a franchise. We can\'t clone Dan Evans.\n\nSo, how do you propose we solve the Dan Evans bottleneck? How do we standardize this process so it can be run by any competent manager in any future Malawi\'s franchise location?\n\nSTUDENT: Time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: Yes, I would be willing to provide feedback.\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: I liked most that it forced me to keep thinking more deeply about the question being asked. Farther than the surface level response.\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: The conversation seemed to be leading me into a single answer whereas many times there is not 1 single answer.\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: Yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
