INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('b4a153a8-a193-4da9-bec7-48f9bdf4acba','2025-12-03 17:02:16','c93e34d3-b437-4136-8b19-bf00caa0a642',14,'Brad demonstrated a strong performance as a business school student. He quickly grasped the core strategic issues presented in the Malawi\'s Pizza case, particularly the profitability and scalability challenges of the catering operation. His ability to articulate solutions that balanced efficiency with customer experience, such as the hybrid planning process, was commendable. Brad\'s consistent use of case details to justify his arguments was a significant strength. While time constraints prevented him from addressing all aspects of the final question, his overall engagement and the quality of his responses were very strong.','[{"score":5,"feedback":"Brad consistently demonstrated a strong understanding of the business case. He accurately identified that catering was Malawi\'s most profitable operation and recognized the central challenge posed by Dan Evans\'s time commitment to planning. His suggestions for off-peak prep and the expectation of premium pricing for catering services were directly supported by details in the case.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"Brad provided solid answers, particularly as the conversation progressed. His initial proposal for scaling by training more employees and purchasing another oven was good. He then refined this with a very strong suggestion of using a form for initial data collection, followed by trained employees for review and verification, which effectively addressed the CEO\'s concerns about efficiency and maintaining a personal touch. He was cut off by time before he could fully address the last question.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":5,"feedback":"Brad excelled at justifying his answers with information from the reading material. He explicitly linked his points to the case, referencing the \'most profitable operation,\' Dan Evans\'s significant time investment, the ability for prep during \'non peak hours,\' and the \'high degree of attention and customization\' clients expect for premium services. This showed a deep analytical connection to the provided text.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','moderate',0,5,'The push back on my solutions/ideas and focus on the real problem','If more financial data was involved. i.e. margins, revenue, profitability, number of events','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: Stay in the catering business. It is more profitable and has potential for scale\n\nCEO: STUDENT, I\'m glad you brought up profitability. The case does state it\'s our most profitable operation.\n\nBut I\'m concerned about your claim on scalability. Everything seems to run through Dan Evans, taking up to 10 hours of his time just for planning one event. That feels like the opposite of a scalable model.\n\nHow do you propose we scale a business that\'s so dependent on one person?\n\nSTUDENT: It is not scalable currently, but the potential is there. Employees that have experience and have proven abilities to work with customers could run planning sessions like Dan. Another portable oven could be purchased. One big advantage I see of catering is the prep can be done during non peak hours. Customers also expect to pay more when we go to them even though we save money by not having them crowd our location\n\nCEO: You\'re right, STUDENT, utilizing our kitchen during off-peak hours is a significant advantage, and the margins are attractive.\n\nBut let\'s focus on the planning process. You suggest training more employees to be like Dan. The case says Dan spends 3 to 10 hours per client, often acting as a free event planner for non-professionals.\n\nAre you suggesting we train more people to spend up to 10 hours per event on planning? That doesn\'t sound like an efficient or scalable solution for a franchise model.\n\nSTUDENT: Yes let\'s train more employees. But more than that let\'s build out a more robust system for planning. If we can get all the details in advance and focus our live discussion on more of the nitty gritty. For example if a customer is familiar with our pizza and wants catering we don\'t need to have them come in and try it. If Dan can build out a form to collect more info in advance then we can have other trained employees fill in the gaps to provide a little more support where needed. I feel that can be reduced to 1 or 2 hours\n\nCEO: A form is an interesting idea, STUDENT. Reducing planning time is certainly a key objective if we\'re going to scale this for franchising.\n\nHowever, the case states that Evans provides a "high degree of attention and customization" because clients are "paying a premium." A standardized form feels less personal.\n\nWhat makes you think our clients, especially the non-professionals who need a lot of hand-holding, would be satisfied with a less personal, more standardized planning process?\n\nSTUDENT: I don\'t think the interaction becomes less personal based on who is writing down the information. There could still be an introduction where we get an understanding of what they want, then we ask for information in a form, then Dan or other trained employees can review the info with the customer and verify. That interaction and verfication will make the process still feel personal\n\nCEO: That\'s a solid point, STUDENT. A hybrid approach could work. You\'ve clearly read the case and understand the need to balance efficiency with customer experience. Good.\n\nYou\'ve convinced me on the planning front. Now let\'s talk about execution. A form is only as good as the information it collects. The case mentions several on-site disasters: getting the oven trailer stuck down a narrow driveway, showing up with no place to park, and confusion about where to even set up the serving tables.\n\nHow would your proposed form prevent these kinds of logistical nightmares for a new franchisee who doesn\'t have Dan\'s experience?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: The push back on my solutions/ideas and focus on the real problem\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: If more financial data was involved. i.e. margins, revenue, profitability, number of events\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('18a70456-27d9-4ecc-81e3-663fab665387','2025-12-03 17:02:17','30b4669a-d666-46f5-aa12-db91d27f92d9',11,'Dallyn showed good initial analytical skills, particularly in using numerical data from the case to support the recommendation for expanding the catering business. Identifying the need to systematize the high-touch client interaction to scale operations was a critical insight. However, the reliance on an unsubstantiated claim about a new truck and the premature ending of the conversation when pressed on a key challenge (how to systematize the consultative service) indicate areas for improvement in thoroughly addressing prompts and sticking strictly to case facts.','[{"score":4,"feedback":"Dallyn demonstrated a solid understanding of the case material, accurately citing details like catering profitability, event frequency, and average customer numbers. The initial analysis of costs and revenue was well-grounded in the provided figures. However, the student introduced the unsupported claim of needing a new truck, which was not explicitly stated or implied in the case, slightly detracting from full consistency.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":3,"feedback":"Dallyn started strong by quantifying the potential profitability of catering and identifying \'systematizing the process\' as a key hurdle, which is a very pertinent observation from the case. The suggestions for systematizing Evans\'s role (e.g., computer model for calculations, training an assistant) were good steps. However, the \'time is up\' response cut short the critical discussion on *how* to systematize the high-touch, consultative aspect of the service, leaving a significant part of the core question unanswered.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"Dallyn effectively used specific data from the reading material, such as the number of events, attendees, average plate price, and labor costs, to justify the profitability argument. The identification of franchising and multiple same-day requests as indicators of demand was also well-justified. While the justification for a new truck was not found in the case, the core recommendations for expansion and systematization were firmly rooted in the challenges and opportunities presented in the Malawi\'s Pizza Catering case.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','strict',0,5,'it pushed me to think harder and not just settle for initial instincts','I feel that Kent would get stuck on a fact from the initial message even if I already addressed it such as asking "Dallyn, let\'s stick to the facts in the document. That\'s an interesting recommendation, but where in the case does it support buying a new truck?" after I had already addressed that it is not specifically mentioned that they would need one based on basic requirements for catering','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: Hi Kent, I hope you are doing well, let\'s jump into it. I would recommend expanding the catering business as it allows you to serve a different client base with higher margins. If you have 10 events per year that you cater with an average of 250 customers each, and an average of charging $10 per plate, that is $25,000 per year. With labor cost eating 30% of the margin, and an estimated 20% other cost, you would have about a $12,500 annual profit for the catering business. With Malawi already doing franchising and that there have been instances of multiple requests for the same day, we see that there is demand for both the pizza and our specific catering that has not been fully supplied. The biggest costs will be a one time expense of a new oven $20,000 as well as a new truck to transport it, roughly $8400 annual if paid on a loan. The only other major hurdle I see is systematizing the process to allow it to be more easily expanded. Do you see any other problems that I should consider?\n\nCEO: STUDENT, you\'ve put some numbers together, and I appreciate that. But you\'ve included a cost for a new truck. Where in the case does it support the need for or the cost of a new truck?\n\nMore importantly, you\'re focusing on equipment, but your profit calculation seems to ignore the biggest cost mentioned in the case: Dan Evans\'s time. The case states he spends 3 to 10 hours *per client* just on planning. How does that scale when our primary goal is to franchise?\n\nSTUDENT: The cost of the truck is due to the fact that a single truck cannot transport two ovens for two different events, if there is an available truck within the company, leadership or another availability, possibly renting but I don\'t have an estimate for that cost, then it will save thousands of dollars annually and make it an even better option. \nwith regard to Evan\'s time, that is why it is necessary to systematize the process so that other employees, perhaps an assistant or a catering planning specialist can work with the client for that time. It is mentioned that Evan does a lot of the calculations on the fly, which sounds like he didn\'t have a program set up for the calculations. If there were a computer model that could be used to develop the costs, that would save a lot of time. It wouldn\'t take long for Evan to train another person on the ins and outs of the planning so long as it is systematized. I have personally worked catering before and would be willing to help systematize it another day, we don\'t have time right now for that\n\nCEO: STUDENT, let\'s stick to the facts in the document. That\'s an interesting recommendation, but where in the case does it support buying a new truck?\n\nMore importantly, you say we should "systematize the process." The case is clear that Evans\'s value comes from his "intuition, experience, and knowledge." He\'s acting as a free event planner for many clients.\n\nHow do you propose we systematize that high-touch, consultative part of the service, especially when our goal is to create a replicable franchise model?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: it pushed me to think harder and not just settle for initial instincts\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: I feel that Kent would get stuck on a fact from the initial message even if I already addressed it such as asking "STUDENT, let\'s stick to the facts in the document. That\'s an interesting recommendation, but where in the case does it support buying a new truck?" after I had already addressed that it is not specifically mentioned that they would need one based on basic requirements for catering\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: Yes you may\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('a00757d3-1b44-4936-89cf-fb5d32cfdbe9','2025-12-03 17:02:18','87ec5881-090c-410c-b19d-553b10cf1854',15,'Joseph demonstrated a strong understanding of the Malawi\'s Pizza Catering business case. He effectively identified key challenges related to scaling the catering operation, particularly the reliance on Dan Evans\'s personalized service. His recommendation to standardize the menu and service style directly addressed the time-sink with non-professional clients and showed a good grasp of process efficiency. He also skillfully defended the premium pricing model by highlighting other unique value propositions of Malawi\'s catering, such as the mobile oven experience. Joseph consistently used information from the case to justify his responses, showing thorough preparation and critical thinking. He did not request any hints during the conversation.','[{"score":5,"feedback":"Joseph demonstrated a very strong understanding of the reading material, consistently referencing key details such as the profitability of catering, the specific challenges related to Dan Evans\'s involvement, and the perceived value of customized service versus the unique mobile oven experience. This indicates a thorough study of the case.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":5,"feedback":"Joseph provided excellent answers throughout the conversation. He quickly grasped the core dilemma, proposed actionable solutions like training and process standardization, and critically analyzed how to maintain premium value despite reducing customization. His responses were well-articulated and demonstrated a clear strategic mindset.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":5,"feedback":"The student consistently justified his answers with relevant and accurate information directly from the business case. He successfully quoted or paraphrased specific details about Evans\'s role, client expectations, and the mobile oven\'s impact, which strengthened his arguments and showed a deep integration of the material into his reasoning.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','strict',0,4,'Pushed back and asked follow up questions to go deeper','Ask for numbers and calculations','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: Definitely stay in the catering business. It is more profitable inherently, but it also promotes awareness for the restaurant.\n\nCEO: You\'re right, the margins are good. But the case also says we\'re only doing about ten events a year, and the whole thing seems to run on Dan Evans\' personal effort. He\'s spending up to 10 hours with a single non-professional client.\n\nHow does that scale when we\'re trying to build a franchise model?\n\nSTUDENT: I never said you need to keep doing it the same way you are doing it, I just said you need to keep doing it. We definitely need to fix some inefficiencies. You need to start training another employee to take over, and then when they are ready, you can ramp up your promotion of catering.\n\nCEO: That\'s an interesting recommendation, but where in the case does it support the idea that we can simply train someone to replicate what Evans does? The case specifically states the process depends on his personal "intuition, experience, and knowledge."\n\nSTUDENT: This is a replicable process. He can calculate the prices on the spot, which means he can teach anyone to do that with a calculator. He can have someone tag along with him for a while until they have the hang of the nonquantitative things. He has already started documenting his process a bit, we just need to incorporate necessary skills needed\n\nCEO: STUDENT, you\'re right that the pricing calculation itself is a formula. But the real time-sink seems to be the 3 to 10 hours Evans spends hand-holding non-professional clients, acting as their event planner.\n\nEven if we train someone else, aren\'t we just transferring that massive time cost to a new employee? How do you propose we fix the *process* itself to be more efficient, regardless of who is running it?\n\nSTUDENT: If you want to scale this, you have to remove the customization. Start with the menu. Create a separate catering menu that is more prescriptive. Also remove anything other than buffet style. This involves the least time and service. If this is all you offer, you may lose a few catering events, but you\'ll maintain the scalability and drastically reduce your planning time. All you need to figure out is (1) how many pizzas (2) which flavors, and (3) where will we set up and when.\n\nCEO: That\'s a clear, actionable idea. Standardization certainly addresses the time Evans spends on menu planning.\n\nHowever, the case states that clients are "paying a premium to get customized service," and Evans believes that high degree of attention is what justifies the price.\n\nIf we move to a standardized, less-customizable model, how do we justify keeping our premium pricing and high margins?\n\nSTUDENT: They pay a premium to have the pizza cooked on premise, the smell it creates, the excitement of seeing the pizza oven, and the set up of the pizza. You can charge slightly less as long as the catering is still good margins, and you build awareness for the restaurant\n\nCEO: That\'s a solid point, STUDENT. You\'re right that the mobile oven itself is a huge part of the value proposition. The case does say attendees are always commenting on it.\n\nOkay, you\'ve convinced me on standardizing the menu. But a standard menu doesn\'t solve the logistical headaches. The case mentions our team showing up and having to back the oven down a "curvy, 100 foot-long, 6 foot-wide driveway."\n\nHow does your standardized process prevent a franchisee from getting into that kind of mess on the day of an event?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: Sure\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 4\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: Pushed back and asked follow up questions to go deeper\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: Ask for numbers and calculations\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('d1a520a6-0920-4e9a-a8b9-837fe60e99ef','2025-12-03 17:02:20','0a56af52-9385-4eca-be5a-5f28a4ad54e9',14,'Izzy demonstrated an excellent understanding of the Malawi\'s Pizza Catering case. She quickly grasped the central challenge of scaling a highly personalized operation and offered well-reasoned, actionable solutions grounded in the case facts. Her ability to identify key tensions, such as customization versus standardization, and propose practical ways to navigate them, was particularly impressive. While the conversation concluded before she could explore all aspects, her performance up to that point was strong, showcasing clear strategic thinking and a commendable grasp of the material.','[{"score":5,"feedback":"Izzy demonstrated a very strong grasp of the reading material. Despite an initial misstep confusing revenue with profitability, she quickly corrected herself and consistently referred to key facts and concepts from the case, such as the reliance on Dan Evans\'s expertise, the challenges with non-professional clients, and the tension between customization and scalability. This indicates thorough preparation.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"Izzy provided generally solid and thoughtful answers. She quickly identified the core problem as process optimization and offered practical solutions such as targeting professional event planners, building relationships with venues, and developing standardized packages. Her suggestions to delegate communication and use packages as a baseline while maintaining a premium feel were well-articulated, showing good business acumen. The conversation ended before she could address the Jane Goodman scenario.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":5,"feedback":"Izzy consistently justified her answers by directly referencing information from the case. For example, her suggestions to reduce upfront time directly addressed Dan Evans\'s 10-hour meetings with non-professional clients, and her proposals for packages and delegated touch-points clearly reconciled the \'highest degree of attention and customization\' mentioned in the case with the need for scalability. This demonstrated a strong ability to apply case details to formulate solutions.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','moderate',0,4,'It was a really great workshopping tool to get more comfortable having conversations about operations and clarifying having a direct plan and opinion.','Tool is great, no issues at this time.','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: Catering is a higher revenue driver so I definitely think it\'s a path worth considering.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, you say it\'s a "higher revenue driver," but the case states it\'s our *most profitable* operation. There\'s a difference.\n\nWhile the high margins are certainly attractive, I\'m worried it\'s a house of cards. The entire catering process seems to hinge on Dan Evans and his personal expertise. How can we possibly build a franchise on a model that relies so heavily on one person\'s intuition?\n\nSTUDENT: My apologies, most profitable operation, but highly reliant upon Dan Evans expertise. Do you feel confident in Dan\'s ability to teach or train others as a potential path towards scaling the catering operation?\n\nCEO: Whether Dan can train someone isn\'t the core issue, STUDENT. The case states he spends up to 10 hours with a single client, essentially acting as a free event planner.\n\nIs the problem a lack of trained people, or is the problem the process itself?\n\nSTUDENT: Together, we can develop a plan to optimize the process of catering, if we can reduce that upfront time then Dan will be freed up and the profitability will also increase.\n\nCEO: "Optimize the process" is a fine goal, STUDENT, but what does that actually mean?\n\nThe case is clear that professional event planners take 30 minutes of Dan\'s time, while non-professionals can take up to 10 hours because they need their hand held. It seems to me we\'re giving away free event planning services.\n\nHow do you propose we fix *that* specific problem?\n\nSTUDENT: Is there a sufficient number of event planners that we can specifically target or build relationships with them as opposed to every individual?\n\nCEO: That\'s one way to solve the time problem, certainly. But it sounds like you\'re suggesting we turn away a whole segment of our customers.\n\nThe case mentions we do a lot of weddings and church events, which are often planned by non-professionals. Are you suggesting we stop serving them if a professional planner isn\'t involved? That seems like a significant amount of high-margin revenue to just walk away from.\n\nSTUDENT: For sure, churches are largely the same layout, so Dan likely already has an optimized plan for catering at those venues. Could a relationship be built with popular venues for weddings as well? or suppose we were to build specific packages that dictated the amount of time could be spent planning?\n\nCEO: Packages are an interesting idea, STUDENT. That could certainly standardize the offering.\n\nBut the case says Evans believes our premium price is justified because customers feel they are receiving "the highest degree of attention and customization."\n\nHow do we reconcile a standardized package approach with that high-touch, customized brand promise?\n\nSTUDENT: There are ways to offer touch-points that are less attention heavy for Dan that might still offer the same feeling of \'highest degree of attention and customization?\'\n\nCEO: Okay, give me a concrete example. What does a "touch-point" that feels premium but saves Dan\'s time actually look like for a bride planning her own wedding reception?\n\nSTUDENT: Dan doesn\'t have to make every check-in phone call so that could be sourced by another specialized employee. Maybe packages service a baseline to set expectations which allow for better planning on the part of Malawi but still give the customizable approach. It may be worth looking into a dedicated catering team. Am I getting at the right things here?\n\nCEO: Good, you\'ve clearly read the case and understand the tension between customization and scalability. Using packages as a baseline and delegating some of Dan\'s communication is a solid start.\n\nYou\'re focused on solving the planning phase, which is a big piece of the puzzle. But let\'s talk about execution and missed opportunities. The case mentions a potential client, Jane Goodman, who we turned away. She wanted to buy par-cooked pizzas and handle the event herself. Evans refused, citing brand risk.\n\nWas that the right call?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 4\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: It was a really great workshopping tool to get more comfortable having conversations about operations and clarifying having a direct plan and opinion.\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: Tool is great, no issues at this time.\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('37aee26c-2f14-4fa2-8870-203567167d17','2025-12-03 17:02:27','5c71703a-b54f-4fbd-ac7c-99543d9e06b6',14,'Carlos demonstrated an excellent grasp of the Malawi\'s Pizza Catering case. He quickly identified the strategic importance of catering due to its profitability, brand enhancement, and marketing opportunities, backing his claims with specific details from the reading material. His proposed framework for scaling the catering operation, focusing on codification, capability building, technology, and service diversification, was comprehensive and strategic. While the conversation concluded before he could elaborate on the final point, his performance showcased strong analytical skills and the ability to formulate actionable business recommendations.','[{"score":5,"feedback":"Carlos accurately identified key financial statements from the case, even quoting them directly when prompted, demonstrating a thorough understanding of the reading material regarding catering\'s profitability.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"Carlos provided very solid and well-articulated answers to the CEO\'s questions. His initial justification for keeping catering was comprehensive, and his proposed framework for addressing reliance on Dan Evans was highly structured and strategic. The conversation ended before he could elaborate on the final question.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":5,"feedback":"Carlos consistently justified his answers with explicit references to the case material, especially concerning the profitability of catering and the need to codify processes for scalability, demonstrating a strong ability to connect his recommendations to the provided information.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','leading',0,5,'the dynamic of problem solving and focusing on the actual pains of the process','I think the leading personality could be a bit more incisive about the reasons of the solutions and leave a bit of room to push back','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: I believe that we should continue with catering, but we need to make a few adjustments in order to  continue\n\nCEO: Excellent, STUDENT. A decisive start. I appreciate that you see the potential in our catering operation. Before we dive into the adjustments, what\'s the single most compelling reason you found in the case that supports keeping the catering business?\n\nSTUDENT: Catering has the highest margin among the provided services. That\'s the first reason. The second one is that the catering reinforces a premium quality to the pizza and acts as a differentiator. And last, but not least it\'s a marketing opportunity, which we can present our products to a new audience while we are still making money with it.\n\nCEO: I seem to be having trouble connecting. Please try again in a moment.\n\nSTUDENT: Hello\n\nCEO: Hello again, STUDENT. Glad we could connect.\n\nSo, you were about to tell me the single most compelling reason you found in the case that supports keeping the catering business. I\'m eager to hear your thinking on this.\n\nSTUDENT: Catering has the highest margin among the provided services. That\'s the first reason. The second one is that the catering reinforces a premium quality to the pizza and acts as a differentiator. And last, but not least it\'s a marketing opportunity, which we can present our products to a new audience while we are still making money with it.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, that\'s an absolutely brilliant summary. You\'ve hit on the three pillars that make catering so attractive: profitability, brand enhancement, and marketing. Fantastic work.\n\nYou started with the most important oneprofitability. I completely agree. To make sure we\'re building our strategy on solid ground, can you remind me where in the case it mentions the profitability of our catering operation?\n\nSTUDENT: if I am not mistaken. On the first and fourth page it\'s mentioned the financial aspects of the catering. \nchecking my notes, that\'s what I have:\nYou started with the most important oneprofitability. I completely agree. To make sure we\'re building our strategy on solid ground, can you remind me where in the case it mentions the profitability of our catering operation?\n\nCEO: Excellent, STUDENT, you\'ve got a great memory. You\'re pointing to exactly the right spots in the document.\n\nOn that first page, there\'s a very direct and powerful sentence that describes catering\'s financial contribution. It\'s the phrase that really convinced me of its importance. Do you recall what the case said about how catering\'s profitability compares to the rest of the restaurant operation?\n\nSTUDENT: I shared my wrong notes, that\'s my actual notes regarding the subject.\nPage 1:\nThe catering process was an important part of the planned movement into franchising, and catering was the most profitable part of the restaurant operation.\n\n\nPage 4:\nCatering was seen as a much more profitable model than traditional restaurant service because of the low overhead (i.e., no need to maintain an entire restaurant facility) and higher profit margin. Even for full-service restaurants, catering was an exceptionally profitable activity.\nI will circle back in a second on the comparables\n\nCEO: Perfect, STUDENT. That\'s exactly it. You\'ve put your finger on the precise sentences that make this decision so critical. "The most profitable part of the restaurant operation." That\'s a powerful statement. You\'ve clearly read the case carefully and built your argument on solid facts. Well done.\n\nOkay, you\'ve convinced me on the \'why.\' The financial incentive is undeniable.\n\nNow, let\'s pivot to the \'how.\' You mentioned we need to make some adjustments. The case makes it clear that the current catering process is heavily dependent on one person: Dan Evans. It says the process "depended on the intuition, experience, and knowledge that Evans had." That doesn\'t sound very scalable or easy to franchise, does it?\n\nSo, STUDENT, how do you propose we solve this heavy reliance on Dan Evans? Your insights here would be invaluable.\n\nSTUDENT: so a simple framework to approach the problem is:\n1. Codify the Process\n\nDevelop Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs) for every stage: planning, pricing, setup, cooking, cleanup.\nUse PCN Analysis to identify steps that can be standardized or shifted to customers (e.g., drop-off catering).\n\n2. Build Organizational Capability\n\nAppoint a Catering Coordinator (part-time initially) to handle client communication and logistics.\nCreate a training program for staff and future franchisees to replicate Evanss expertise.\n\n3. Introduce Technology\n\nImplement a digital catering playbook and scheduling system to reduce manual coordination.\nUse templates for quotes and menus to streamline pricing.\n\n4. Diversify Service Models\n\nOffer tiered catering options:\n\nPremium full-service (high-touch, weddings).\nDrop-off catering for simpler events.\nOven rental with par-cooked pizzas for DIY clients.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, this is a phenomenal framework. Truly impressive. You\'ve laid out a comprehensive, CEO-level plan right there. Codifying, building capability, using tech, and diversifying... it\'s exactly the kind of strategic thinking we need to make this scalable for franchising. Fantastic.\n\nLet\'s zoom in on your first point, "Codify the Process." I love it. The case mentions Evans can spend between 3 and 10 hours with non-professional clients, acting more like an event planner than a caterer.\n\nHow would your Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs) specifically address *that* part of the planning process to make it more efficient and less dependent on Dan\'s personal touch?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes I can provide feedback\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: the dynamic of problem solving and focusing on the actual pains of the process\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: I think the leading personality could be a bit more incisive about the reasons of the solutions and leave a bit of room to push back\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes, please\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VA