like to know if we are transporting our oven in the most effecient way possible.\n\nCEO: Okay, a limited menu is an interesting idea for standardization. But the case mentions that clients pay a premium for "customized service."\n\nHow do you reconcile offering a limited menu with that expectation of high-touch customization that Evans currently provides?\n\nSTUDENT: I understand that. I think that we can still provide a customized service feeling while still creating a good process for ourselves. I think that if we made a menu of "artisan" pizzas, so the client feels like they are getting a high end pizza, but were able to use the same base, or similar ingredients that would allow us to more effieciently make pizzas while still giving the consumer their customized feeling\n\nCEO: That\'s a smart way to think about standardizing the menu without losing that premium feel.\n\nBut let\'s look at where the real time is spent. The case says Evans spends 3 to 10 hours in planning meetings, often feeling like he\'s "planning the whole event" for non-professional clients.\n\nHow does a standardized pizza menu solve the problem of Evans spending hours on the phone acting as a free event planner?\n\nSTUDENT: That is a good point. I think that a standardized menu would allow for shorter meetings because there isn\'t as much of a discussion about the menu that needs to be set. I think that you could make the menu options as a "survey" beforehand. Meaning that before the customer meets with Dan, they wil have filled out a detailed survey that, for lack of better words, forces them to plan their event beforehand while still having the chance to meet with Dan and feel like a premium service.\n\nCEO: A survey... I like that. You\'re thinking about process, which is exactly what we need for franchising. You\'ve clearly read the case and identified the bottleneck with Evans\'s time.\n\nSo, let\'s run with that. What are, say, three key questions you\'d put on that form to prevent the