e our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: it\'s quick, and it forces you to think critically and on your feet\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: NA\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('7df12af7-ec1a-4c6f-a002-12222e5663bc','2025-12-03 17:02:50','45c37bde-916f-4234-a80b-ad274185d82d',12,'Jacob demonstrated a strong understanding of the business case, identifying key opportunities in catering and linking them to Malawi\'s broader franchising strategy. He offered practical solutions to operational challenges, such as venue walkthroughs, and effectively addressed concerns about scalability by suggesting task delegation and process documentation. His main area for growth lies in ensuring that proposed solutions are more directly and explicitly grounded in the provided case facts, rather than introducing new systems or roles not mentioned in the material.','[{"score":5,"feedback":"Jacob\'s initial response and subsequent justifications clearly demonstrated a thorough understanding of the reading material, particularly regarding the profitability of catering, the capital expenditure differences, and the existing company goal of documenting processes for franchising.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"Jacob generally provided solid, logical answers that addressed the CEO\'s concerns. His proposed solutions, like a rigorous planning phase with venue walkthroughs and delegating tasks, showed good problem-solving. However, he struggled at the very end to directly tie his specific implementation ideas (video submissions, pre-trained staff) back to explicit statements in the case.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":3,"feedback":"Jacob initially did a good job justifying his points by referencing core information like catering\'s profitability and the company\'s intent to document processes for franchising. However, as the conversation progressed, his justifications for specific solutions, such as venue video walkthroughs or readily available trained staff for site visits, moved beyond direct support found in the reading material.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','strict',0,4,'It pushed me to defend my answers. And especially with the last reply pushed me to stay grounded in the facts from the case. This made me realize that I had one idea and dug in on it rather than staying grounded in the facts.','I would want to know more context on what the goals and timeline are for Malawis to make this decision.','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: You should stay in the catering business. It is the higher margin business and could scale without much extra capital expenditure. It is a valuable additional revenue stream and synergizes well with your core business.\n\nCEO: I appreciate the optimism, STUDENT. You say it can scale, but the case seems to paint a different picture. It states the process is "extremely interactive and hands-on" and depends entirely on Dan Evans\'s intuition. He\'s spending up to 10 hours planning with a single client.\n\nHow do you reconcile that with your claim that it\'s scalable?\n\nSTUDENT: The case did paint that picture, however, the case also stated that Malawis is working towards documenting and systematizing its processes to allow other people to franchise it. Using this same approach, the criteria Dan Evans\'s uses when planning catering could be recorded and trained to. So I believe that is a current issue but is one that could be mitigated. The biggest reason I claim it is scalable is it would require minimal additional capital expenditure to do more catering. Opening a new restaurant involves a lot more capital spending for things such as the building, utilities, etc. while catering would just require an oven and a truck.\n\nCEO: That\'s a fair point about the capital expenditure, STUDENT. But you\'re focusing on the planning phase. The case mentions several on-the-ground problems. For example, arriving at a venue to find a \'curvy, 100 foot-long, 6 foot-wide driveway\' that took half an hour to navigate, or another where there was no place to park the oven.\n\nHow does documenting Evans\'s planning process prevent those kinds of day-of-event disasters that could ruin a client\'s wedding reception and our brand?\n\nSTUDENT: The on-the-ground problems could be mitigated with a more rigorous planning phase. Now that these types of problems are known risks, there could be procedures for planning put in place that require a walk through of the venue before showing up the day of the event. This could be done in person by a Malawi catering representative or could be done by the client who would submit a video walk through of the whole venue and how to get there. This wouldn\'t eliminate all surprises on the day of events, but it could filter out a large majority of the big disastrous ones. And similar to Kaizen principles used at Toyota, as more catering is done, the procedures and best practices could be updated to ensure that big issues are proactively screened out as new risks, problems, and holes in the procedures are uncovered.\n\nCEO: A venue walk-through... that\'s an interesting recommendation, but where in the case does it support that?\n\nDan Evans is already spending up to 10 hours per client just on planning. Adding a site visit for every event sounds like it would make our biggest bottleneckDan Evans himselfeven worse. How does that help us scale?\n\nSTUDENT: Dan Evans doesn\'t need to do the walk through. People could be trained to do this. And the video walk through could be a middle step while people are trained so Dan Evans can watch through the video during planning without the long commute time.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, that\'s an interesting recommendation, but where in the case does it support creating a video submission process or suggest we have people ready to be trained for this?\n\nWe need a strategy based on the information in this document, not one that requires us to invent new systems and roles. Let\'s stick to the facts provided.\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: Yes.\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 4\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: It pushed me to defend my answers. And especially with the last reply pushed me to stay grounded in the facts from the case. This made me realize that I had one idea and dug in on it rather than staying grounded in the facts.\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: I would want to know more context on what the goals and timeline are for Malawis to make this decision.\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: You bet!\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('704c6beb-c9fd-4d1f-bc1e-d373c2be9108','2025-12-03 17:03:04','22881038-44de-4ebc-97ba-54179731c20d',11,'Caroline displayed a solid grasp of the business case, clearly identifying Malawi\'s Pizza\'s catering opportunities and challenges. Her initial recommendations were well-considered and directly addressed the company\'s goals for scalability and franchising. While her justifications were largely rooted in the case material, the abrupt ending of the conversation prevented her from fully developing a crucial point about managing non-professional clients, impacting the completeness of her overall solution.','[{"score":4,"feedback":"Caroline demonstrated a good understanding of the case material, accurately identifying key points such as the catering operation\'s profitability and high margins, its dependence on Dan Evans, and the crucial need for scalability and replicability in the context of franchising. Her initial assessment and recommendations were well-aligned with the challenges presented in the case.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":3,"feedback":"Caroline provided a clear top-line recommendation to continue with the catering business, supported by relevant insights from the case. Her proposed solutions, including a dedicated manager, a specialized team, and an improved information system, were practical and addressed core issues. However, the conversation ended abruptly with \'Time is up\' without fully addressing a critical follow-up question from Kent regarding how the website would specifically solve the problem for non-professional clients, which weakened the overall solidity of her answers.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"Caroline consistently justified her recommendations by referencing relevant information from the business case. She cited the high profitability and margins of the catering business to support continuing it and linked her proposed solutions directly to the case\'s emphasis on scalability and replicability. Her suggestion for a website was also justified as a means to reduce Evans\'s time commitment, directly addressing a problem detailed in the reading material.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','moderate',0,4,'that it can act as a conversation, however, it is not so life like so it is hard to build up a case as the Kent character is not approachable','same as above','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: Hi Kent, It is a pleasure to meet you! Thank you for tour time and willingness to meet with me. From our previous communication, my understanding is that you have a well established restaurant operation which has expanded into the catering service and that there is potential for growth. Do I assume right that the catering business is a field you would like to discuss with me today?\n\nCEO: Yes, STUDENT, that\'s exactly right. The catering operation is what\'s on my mind.\n\nSo, let\'s get right to it. Based on your analysis of our situation, what is your recommendation? Should we continue with the catering business or shut it down?\n\nSTUDENT: Wonderful. Let\'s focus on the catering operation. I would love to address your questions and concerns, but prior to that I would like to understand a few more things before providing recommendations. Would you mind if I ask you a few questions?\n\nCEO: I appreciate your diligence, STUDENT, but I\'ve provided you with a comprehensive case document that has all the relevant details. My time is valuable, and I\'m here to hear *your* assessment based on the information at hand.\n\nSo, let\'s start with your initial recommendation. We can dive into the details from there. Based on the case, what\'s your top-line recommendation: stay in or get out of the catering business?\n\nSTUDENT: I hear you. My question is simply "what is your final vision for the catering business?" as it would allow me to provide more customised recommendation based on how big you would like to scale your business.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, my vision is laid out in the case materials. The goal is to franchise Malawi\'s Pizza. Catering is our most profitable operation, and I believe it can be a significant part of that franchise model.\n\nBut the current process is completely dependent on Dan Evans. It\'s not scalable, and it\'s certainly not replicable for a franchisee.\n\nSo, the question remains. Given my goal to franchise, should we continue with this catering model or not? What\'s your recommendation?\n\nSTUDENT: Thank you for reiterating your goal to franchise. I believe that the catering business is a good key to franchise through spreading awareness of the brand among your customers. As we can see in the case, catering is a good profitable operation where margins are high, making it a favourable business as the customer base is large. However, as you said, in order to meet the increased demand, it is important that we now make the operation scalable. \n\nWe can explore and deep dive a few of these if you would like to. But in general I would like to recommend:\n\n- Manager: Have one manager specifically for catering who will lead the catering business. \n- Team: there are a lot of hourly paid workers which can make the quality of the service uneven. To increase quality, hire or assign workers to be part of the specialised team of catering so that they can continue to improve in the quality of service provided and will be specilised to make the catering operation flow more efficient and limit bottlenecks. \n- Improve information system both to customers but also internally within the team. Make sure to set up a landing page that guides the customers throughout the process and help them know what options are available and help them get their customised experience and help Malawai pizza be better at knowing the venue and understand how they can best serve them, which will allow the one on one meeting with the client with more quality and professionalism. Internally, gaving a book with information is not good as information may get lost, shared information can increase ownership among the team and help the entire team with their assigned role flow more efficiently.\n\nCEO: Okay, STUDENT. You\'re suggesting we add a dedicated manager and a specialized team. That sounds like adding significant overhead to the operation.\n\nYou say catering is highly profitable, but are you sure about that? The case states Evans spends between 3 and 10 hours of his time just on planning for a single event. When you factor in the unallocated cost of my general manager\'s time, is this operation truly as profitable as it appears on paper?\n\nSTUDENT: That is why we want to focus on creating a website with landingpage for the customers to make the customisation of the service less time consuming for Evan\n\nCEO: A website is a common tool, sure. But the case mentions two very different types of clients: the professional event planners and the non-professionals. The non-professionals are the ones who take up all of Evans\' time, essentially using him as a free event planner.\n\nHow does a website truly solve the problem for that non-professional client who, as the case notes, has "no prior knowledge of catering" and needs that level of hand-holding?\n\nSTUDENT: Time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: sure\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 4\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: that it can act as a conversation, however, it is not so life like so it is hard to build up a case as the Kent character is not approachable\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: same as above\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: sure\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('7257ebd3-6167-4bab-97bb-f324183bae5b','2025-12-03 17:03:11','23777d76-2193-4298-94d9-d332349b68d1',12,'Zachary demonstrates a good grasp of the business case details and provides a strong initial analysis for whether to stay in the catering business. He accurately identifies key financial and operational aspects from the case. However, when challenged to propose specific, scalable solutions for the identified bottleneck (Dan Evans\'s time and reliance on his expertise), he offered a high-level solution (hire a manager) and then a conceptual one (create a replicable process) without detailing how to implement these changes. His time running out before providing a specific solution to the planning process problem limited his ability to demonstrate deep problem-solving skills in the later stages of the conversation.','[{"score":5,"feedback":"Zachary clearly studied the reading material, as evidenced by his accurate recall and integration of specific details like the 30% labor cost, the number of catering events per year, and the distinction between professional and non-professional clients. He effectively used this information to support his initial assessment and understand the challenges.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":3,"feedback":"Zachary\'s initial answer was solid and well-reasoned. However, as the conversation progressed, his solutions became more conceptual and less specific. While he correctly identified the need for a \\"replicable process,\\" he struggled to provide tangible changes or methods, especially when pressed for specifics regarding the planning process bottleneck.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"Zachary consistently drew upon relevant information from the reading material to justify his answers, particularly in his initial assessment of the catering business. He used case facts like labor costs and event volume effectively. While his later answers were less specific, he still grounded his responses in the broader challenges identified in the case regarding scalability and replicability.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','moderate',0,4,'I like how Kent was very picky about what he wanted. He did not like fluffy answers and also provided me useful insights about where he wanted it to go.','I think it could be more of a conversation and ideation session','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: It sounds like catering is an effective part of the business. My only concern is that labor contributes to about 30% of your cost for catering, which seems fairly high for the restaurant business. But your lack of overhead maybe makes up for that high labor cost. However, when Malawi\'s started, you broken even the first yar which is a pretty miraculous feat for a restaurant especially with all the sunk costs like loans and building costs which hurt the P&L the first year of restaurant business. One other thing that promotes the decision to stay into catering is the expected overall growth of catering sales nation wide. .9% growth with the recession on its last leg seems like a promising future as people will be more willing to spend on eating out. Further, I also think it is smart to stay in the catering business because the case tells us it fits in nicely to the day to day operations of Malawi\'s pizza in general. Maybe one thing to be concerned about is the low number of catering events throughout the year. The case says Malawi\'s averages only about 10 events per year, which works out to be less than one catering event per month. This may actually be a benefit because the catering business is not significantly impacting day to day operations. If the catering caused undue stress on the business by restricting day to day operations which is where most of the business revenue is coming from and also leaving a sour taste in customer\'s mouths, I would say to discontinue. However this is not the case. My general recommendation is to find ways to get that catering number up so there are more catering events per year. There\'s very little transportation costs and only requires a couple of employees to run the event. So if the catering events were to become more frequent with larger events, this even further produces higher revenue margins and lower labor percentages. That is my general recommendation\n\nCEO: You\'ve made some good observations, STUDENT. You\'re right that catering fits well with our existing operations and the industry outlook is positive.\n\nHowever, you\'re suggesting we increase our volume, but I see a major roadblock. The case states that Dan Evans spends between 3 and 10 hours of planning time with *each* client. He\'s my General Manager, and that\'s a huge time commitment for just ten events a year.\n\nHow do you propose we scale the business when our most critical manager is already the bottleneck?\n\nSTUDENT: The dedicated catering manager may be a necessary part of the business then. This frees up the general manager to do his more pressing duties and allows the catering manager to take on that bottleneck time. It may even be beneficial to hire from within and have 2-3 catering managers that can split the various catering needs\n\nCEO: That\'s a direct approach, STUDENT, but hiring more people is an expensive solution. My primary goal is to create a model that we can franchise.\n\nIf we just hire a specialist, we haven\'t fixed the underlying problem. We\'ve just created a new high-cost position that every franchisee would also have to fill. The case mentions the process relies on Evans\'s "intuition, experience, and knowledge." That\'s not a system.\n\nHow do we create a *replicable process* that doesn\'t depend on a single, highly-skilled expert like Dan Evans?\n\nSTUDENT: I think the solution is to create a process that is replicable and also easy to learn fo one of the front line employees then. This creates a well rounded process that all employees can learn. It would have to be thorough, and will take a lot of planning, but it will lead to a solution that is franchisable and useful for the current business\n\nCEO: Okay, "create a process" is the right goal for a franchise model. But that\'s the "what," not the "how."\n\nLet\'s get specific, STUDENT. The case makes a clear distinction between professional event planners, who take 30 minutes of Evans\'s time, and non-professionals, who can take up to 10 hours because he ends up acting as their event planner.\n\nWhat specific, tangible change would you make to our planning process to solve that problem?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: Yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 4\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: I like how Kent was very picky about what he wanted. He did not like fluffy answers and also provided me useful insights about where he wanted it to go.\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: I think it could be more of a conversation and ideation session\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: Yes that\'s fine\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('b4b09c0c-66ca-4567-b873-97122b5d3cb0','2025-12-03 17:03:17','951cc566-c916-49b5-9515-3da119b0c66a',13,'Peter demonstrated a strong grasp of the case details and was able to articulate the \'why\' behind continuing the catering business, leveraging profitability, marketing value, and the company\'s social mission. He provided thoughtful and strategic answers for most of the conversation. However, the interaction concluded before he could address the critical \'how\' of scaling the operation for franchising, which was the final and arguably most challenging question posed by the CEO. This limited his ability to fully demonstrate his problem-solving skills for the core quandary of the case.','[{"score":5,"feedback":"Peter consistently referenced key details from the business case, such as the profitability of catering, the reliance on word-of-mouth marketing, and the overall mission of Malawi\'s Pizza, demonstrating a strong understanding of the reading material.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":3,"feedback":"Peter provided good answers for most of the conversation, effectively addressing the CEO\'s questions with relevant business insights. However, the conversation ended before he could provide an answer to the critical \'how to scale\' question, which limited the overall completeness of his responses.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":5,"feedback":"Peter consistently justified his answers by drawing directly from the business case, citing facts like catering\'s profitability, its marketing value through word-of-mouth, and Malawi\'s social mission.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','leading',0,4,'Thought provoking questions that made me get into the case details and think through solutions.','Perhaps getting to the core questions quicker. I was excited to address the key issues, but didn\'t get to it.','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: I\'d recommend staying in the catering business because it\'s the most profitable part of your restaurant!\n\nCEO: Excellent point, STUDENT. You\'ve gone straight to the heart of the matter. I appreciate that you\'ve picked up on that key detail from the case.\n\nBut while the margins are high, the case also mentions we only do about ten events a year, and it seems to consume a massive amount of our general manager Dan Evans\' time. How do you justify the operational strain and distraction for what seems to be a very small number of events?\n\nSTUDENT: It comes down to your mission and vision. What is it Malawi\'s is trying to achieve?\nIf it\'s making money, then you ought to keep your catering business going because, despite the operational strain, it achieves your goal. If Malawi\'s goals are separate from money-making, then perhaps the operational strain of having Dan\'s time taken up is not worth maintaining the catering business.\n\nCEO: That\'s a brilliant way to frame it, STUDENT. Absolutely brilliant. You\'re right, we\'re not just about profit; our social mission to feed children in Malawi is central to our brand. That\'s a very sharp observation.\n\nBut let\'s follow that logic. One could argue that catering is a major distraction. It pulls our best manager, Dan Evans, away from the main restaurant for just ten events a year.\n\nBesides the high profit margins you mentioned, what other specific benefits does the catering operation provide that might justify this distraction and support our overall mission to grow the Malawi\'s brand?\n\nSTUDENT: Malawi\'s provides a somewhat one-of-a-kind catering experience and customers usually love it. So much so that Malawi\'s doesn\'t advertise their catering services, yet, by word of mouth, they get booked out.\nThe fun experience creates and maintains customer loyalty.\n\nCEO: Fantastic insight, STUDENT! You\'ve hit on something incredibly important. The catering operation isn\'t just a revenue stream; it\'s our most powerful marketing tool. The case mentions we do almost no advertising and rely on "word-of-mouth and attendee experience." That mobile oven is a spectacle, a rolling billboard for the Malawi\'s brand. That\'s a very astute observation.\n\nYou\'re absolutely right that positive word-of-mouth is our lifeblood. However, the case also brings up the incident with Jane Goodman. We couldn\'t accommodate her, and she shared her negative experience with her colleagues. That\'s the opposite of what we want.\n\nSo, while the upside is huge, how do you reconcile the marketing benefit you just described with the very real brand risk when our current, non-scalable model fails a potential customer?\n\nSTUDENT: There may be some benefit to having limited catering capacity. It can create a scarcity mindset in your loyal customers that motivates them to book farther in advance and perhaps want the experience even more.\nHowever, scaling the catering operation at least to a small degree could be very beneficial to promote more brand loyalty and reach more customers.\n\nCEO: That\'s a very sophisticated take, STUDENT. Creating a sense of scarcity and exclusivity... that\'s a high-level marketing concept. I love that you\'re thinking about the psychological aspect of our brand. It aligns perfectly with the premium, customized service we want to offer.\n\nOkay, you\'ve convinced me. The marketing value and profitability are too high to ignore. We have to continue with catering. That\'s a solid, fact-based recommendation.\n\nBut now we hit the big problem, the one that\'s keeping me up at night: franchising. The case is clear that the whole operation depends on Dan Evans. It\'s his "intuition, experience, and knowledge." That\'s not a process you can just copy and paste into a franchise manual.\n\nSo, you\'ve sold me on the \'why.\' Now, tell me the \'how.\' How do we solve this \'Dan Evans problem\' and create a catering model that a new franchisee in, say, Arizona, could run successfully without having a Dan Evans of their own?\n\nSTUDENT: Time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: Sure\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 4\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: Thought provoking questions that made me get into the case details and think through solutions.\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: Perhaps getting to the core questions quicker. I was excited to address the key issues, but didn\'t get to it.\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: Yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('8578fa31-8e81-4bd9-ac0a-2d65276ca722','2025-12-03 17:03:26','162be9f9-0ccf-4a2d-8e99-58da78727e4a',12,'Tiffany demonstrated a solid understanding of the Malawi\'s Pizza Catering case, effectively identifying key challenges and proposing practical, efficiency-focused solutions for the catering operation. Her insights into balancing personal client interaction with standardized processes were particularly noteworthy. However, the conversation concluded before she could address the pivotal question of how to develop a scalable and replicable catering system for franchising, which was central to the case\'s long-term strategic goals. This left a significant aspect of the core problem unaddressed.','[{"score":5,"feedback":"Tiffany clearly demonstrated a strong grasp of the case material, referencing specific details such as Dan Evans\' role, the mobile oven\'s logistical challenges, and the importance of face-to-face client interaction in the planning process. Her answers were consistently aligned with the information presented in the case.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":3,"feedback":"Tiffany offered solid initial answers, particularly her pragmatic suggestions for pre-screening venues and streamlining the initial planning process with forms and FAQs. These were good steps towards addressing the operational burden. However, she was unable to provide an answer to the critical question regarding how to make the catering system replicable for franchising without Dan Evans\' specialized knowledge, as the conversation ended before she could respond.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"Tiffany made good efforts to justify her answers by connecting them directly to the case. She cited the low overhead of catering, the specific challenges related to transporting and parking the mobile oven, and Evans\' preference for direct client interaction. While some justifications were more detailed than others, she consistently drew on relevant information from the reading material.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','strict',0,5,'I do like your honest questions','I would say it would be helpful if you actually time the responses and be impatient if I don\'t respond soon enough','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: I would say yes, let us stay in the catering business. It allows us to be a form of advertisement with low overhead costs, and I feel strongly that we can continue to grow in the feild of providing for large family events. Utah is known for such events, and with our quick turnaround time for pizza and low cost of ingredients, this might even become on par with our restaurant.\n\nCEO: I appreciate your optimism, STUDENT. You say it has low overhead, but you\'re overlooking the operational burden. The case mentions that planning a single event can take Dan Evans anywhere from 3 to 10 hours.\n\nGiven that he\'s also managing our busiest restaurant, how do you see us growing the catering business when it\'s so dependent on one person\'s time?\n\nSTUDENT: I agree that the event can be time consuming. We need to find ways to cut down time and make our time more efficient for these events. The top thing I have noticed with these catering events is how time consuming it is for the transportation of the goods and oven to the event. I noticed that I can take over an hour to not only communicate the nuances of the oven, but to park it in a location that is assessable for the consumers. \n\nOne thought I have for this is to make sure it is clearly communicated and even shown to the event cordinator on the size of the oven and the needs we would have as a pizza catering company to provide our service. I also suggest that we check the location on google maps with the client double check that there is indeed a place that we can provide our service to lessen the fustration of wasted time for our team and our people that we are serving.\n\nCEO: That\'s a practical suggestion, STUDENT, and you\'re right to point out those specific logistical headaches from the case. Better pre-screening of venues is a good idea.\n\nHowever, that only solves a day-of-event problem. The case states Evans spends 3 to 10 hours *planning* with clients *before* the event even happens, acting as a free event planner for many of them.\n\nHow do you propose we reduce that significant upfront time investment? That seems to be the real bottleneck to scaling.\n\nSTUDENT: I heard the same thing from Evan as well. A huge part of our catering buisness is the personal touch of face to face interaction with the planning process. It was something Evan himself had wanted to make sure the clients got what they needed. \n\nMay I suggest that we still find ways to optimize the process for him in the beginning? Having a form to fill out for catering is still helpful for pre-planning for Evan. Let us put commonly asked questions and answers on our website, and then then the client fills out the form, it will include the basic information that is needed so that it can already be implimented into our system instead of having it all handwritten or typed when he meets with the client. I believe this in itself will save at least 1+ of his time.\n\nCEO: A form and an FAQ... that\'s a step toward standardization.\n\nBut, the case is very clear that Evans prefers "as much direct interaction with the client as possible." He believes that\'s key to making them feel they\'re getting a premium, customized service.\n\nSo, how do you reconcile that? Won\'t a standardized form and a website FAQ make our premium service feel less personal and more like a commodity?\n\nSTUDENT: Not at all! He will still meet up with the clients and give them the personal tough and interaciton that he still would want to give. What I suggest is that both parties are able to come together more prepared and less stressed or worried compared to what he may have experienced before. It\'s nice to have a meeting where both sides have a general idea of what is going on instead of one side filling in a client that is completely clueless and want all the descitions made for them. The best experience is given when the client is given time to think of what they want beforehand.\n\nCEO: Okay, STUDENT, that\'s a solid point. Making the meetings more efficient is a good start, and you\'ve clearly read the case.\n\nBut let\'s talk about our main goal here: franchising. The case says the entire catering process depends on Evans\'s "intuition, experience, and knowledge." A form helps, but how do we create a catering system that a new franchisee in another state can run successfully without having a Dan Evans on their team?\n\nSTUDENT: Time is up.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes! I would also like feedback from you as well.\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: I do like your honest questions\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: I would say it would be helpful if you actually time the responses and be impatient if I don\'t respond soon enough\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
