}]','liberal',0,5,'I appreciated the simulation emphasizing what Ken saw as the most crucial concerns.','I would suggest having some questions that were more pointed rather than being very open ended.','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: My recommendation is to continue in the catering business. While challenging, the catering operations represent strong opportunity for profit as well as good exposure for new customers.\n\nCEO: Alright, STUDENT, I hear you. You\'re focusing on the upside. But from where I\'m sitting, I see a major bottleneck. The entire catering operation seems to depend on one person: Dan Evans. The case says the process relies on his personal "intuition, experience, and knowledge."\n\nThat doesn\'t sound like a business we can scale, let alone franchise. How do you reconcile the opportunity you see with that operational reality?\n\nSTUDENT: I agree that this is a primary concern for this decision. However, I actually believe that Dan Evans\' skill and expertise would be best utilized through scaling of the catering operations. The case states that Evans is familiar with all steps of the catering process including planning and staffing of the event. Yet he is also frustrated by some of the tasks that go into the planning such as some customer interactions. By scaling the business, Malawi\'s could bring in other staff that are able to handle things like the event planning, while making better use of Evans\' time by positioning him as a manager and expert to support the staff fulfilling each part of the process.\n\nCEO: That\'s an interesting thought, STUDENT. You\'re suggesting we turn Evans into a manager rather than the main point of contact.\n\nBut the case is clear that clients are "paying a premium to get customized service." Evans himself wants them to feel they\'re receiving the "highest degree of attention and customization." If we replace him with junior staff for those crucial planning meetings, are we still delivering that premium experience that justifies our price point?\n\nSTUDENT: An excellent question. While Evans\' presence does provide some legitimacy to the catering process, his time being split across multiple clients is already watering down his impact. Additionally, because the business is so heavily reliant upon him, if he is absent for any reason, the current system falls apart. As the case describes, he has an understanding of what he needs when staffing events. I believe leveraging this experience when choosing staff to aid in scaling the business will be crucial to ensuring customers feel the same level of care and customization.\n\nCEO: Good, you\'ve clearly read the case and you\'re thinking about the risks. You\'ve convinced me that keeping Evans as the sole point of contact is a bigger risk than trying to scale the team.\n\nSo let\'s get practical. You want to bring in other staff. The case says Evans spends between 3 and 10 hours with each client, often acting as a free event planner. How do you propose we standardize that specific planning process so we can hand a playbook to a franchisee and have it work without Dan Evans?\n\nSTUDENT: Time is up.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: Yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: I appreciated the simulation emphasizing what Ken saw as the most crucial concerns.\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: I would suggest having some questions that were more pointed rather than being very open ended.\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: Yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
